1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 { [%csl Gc4] The famous Sozin - or Fischer-Sozin - Attack. The bishop takes an active role on the a2-g8 diagonal attacking the fragile f7-pawn, and White can consider the advance f4-f5 to increase the pressure on the kingside. The Sozin used to be more popular at the amateur level as it offered dangerous attacking chances for White. At the high level, it lost popularity as Black found more than one reliable path to solve the opening problems, but recently it became fashionable again thanks to a different plan used by Aronian in some games. } 6... e6 { Naturally, we advance the pawn only one square now to limit the dangerous bishop. } 7. Bb3 { By far the most played, anticipating b7-b5 and keeping White's development flexible. Nevertheless, there are many options, and in the last few years, White players have tried different plans. } ( { Let's begin by } 7. Be3 $5 { intending to continue with Qe2 and 0-0-0. This setup is known as the Velimirovic Attack. It has never been so popular in this move order, but it gained attention after some games by Aronian and Kramnik as White. } 7... Be7 8. Bb3 ( 8. Qe2 O-O 9. O-O-O $2 { is bad due to } 9... b5 10. Bb3 b4 $1 { when the initiative is already with Black. } 11. Na4 Qa5 $1 { [%csl Ga4][%cal Gc8d7] The knight out of play on a4 brings serious problems for White. } 12. Nf3 Nbd7 13. Nd2 Bb7 14. f3 { Udeshi,A (2330) -Van Kampen,R (2475) Wch U16 Kemer 2009 (10) 0-1 } 14... d5 $19 { [%cal Gb7c6] soon leads to material gains for Black. } ) 8... b5 $1 { It's important to remember that Black should develop the queenside play before castling. } ( { If } 8... O-O $6 { White has } 9. g4 $36 { starting the actions on the kingside. It's better to keep the king in the center for a while and avoid this continuation. } ) 9. f3 ( 9. a3 { is the move order chosen by both Aronian and Kramnik, but after } 9... O-O { the position should transpose, as White plays Qe2 and f2-f3 soon. In one game Aronian played in a more original way: } 10. h4 $5 Bb7 11. h5 h6 12. f3 { [%cal Yg2g4,Yg4g5] White's idea was to provoke h7-h6 in order to make the advance g4-g5 more dangerous. However, a recent game has shown that opening the g-file is not an easy task. } 12... Nbd7 13. Qd2 Nc5 14. Ba2 Nh7 $5 15. O-O-O Rb8 16. g4 Ng5 $1 { [%csl Ge4,Ge6,Gf3,Yg5][%cal Gf6h7,Gh7g5] The unusual maneuver Nh7-g5 is a nice defensive idea to keep in mind. The knight avoids thematic sacrifices on e6, but most importantly it avoids White's advances on the kingside. He tried to insist in the attack with } 17. Qe2 Qc7 18. Rhg1 Kh8 19. f4 $2 { but this is not good. } 19... Ngxe4 20. Nxe4 { Abdrlauf,E (2338) -Kaasen,T (2383) NOR-ch Oslo 2021 (9) 0-1 Here } 20... Bxe4 $1 { would be more precise, as after } 21. g5 hxg5 22. fxg5 d5 $19 { [%csl Ge4][%cal Yb5b4] Black has a strong bishop on e4 and promising chances on the queenside, while White lacks a good way of continuing the attack on the kingside. } ) ( 9. Qe2 O-O 10. a3 { is a move order played by Dubov and Kramnik. The idea is to avoid b5-b4 and make use of the queen on e2 to support the advanced g4-g5. } ( 10. O-O-O $2 { is a mistake in view of } 10... b4 $1 11. Na4 Qa5 $15 { [%csl Ra4] transposing to a variation already seen. } ) 10... Bb7 { Now the bishop goes to b7 and wins a tempo by forcing f2-f3. If we play Bd7 like in other move orders, White can just castle and play more aggressively with g4-g5-f4. } 11. f3 Nc6 12. O-O-O ( 12. Nxc6 $2 { only helps Black as after } 12... Bxc6 13. O-O-O Qb8 $17 { [%cal Ya6a5,Yb5b4] our queenside play seems very fast. } ) 12... Na5 $5 { [%csl Gc3][%cal Ga8c8] An interesting idea suggested by Giri. The position of White's queen on e2 allows Black to consider the thematic sacrifice Rc8-Rxc3. } 13. h4 ( 13. Kb1 $5 { Kramnik,V (2753) -Grischuk,A (2776) Levitov Kramnik-Grischuk m blitz 2021 (3) 1/2-1/2 was played by Kramnik and has a subtle idea: answering Rc8 with Nxe6, since Black is deprived of the intermediate Nxb3 with check. As White is wasting some tempos before launching the attack on the kingside, we can play } 13... Nxb3 14. Nxb3 Qc7 { and prepare the counterplay on the queenside. For example: } 15. g4 Rab8 16. g5 Nd7 17. h4 Ne5 18. h5 Nc4 19. Bc1 Rfc8 { [%cal Gc4a3] } 20. Rd3 Bc6 $13 { [%cal Yb5b4,Ya6a5] when the position is tense, but Black's counterplay can't be underestimated. In such positions it's important to remember that } 21. g6 $6 { might be a bit hasty, especially when Black has the strong reply } 21... Bf6 $15 { [%csl Gf6][%cal Gf6h8,Gf6a1] as the bishop can be useful both for defensive and attacking ideas. } ) ( { Giri analyses } 13. g4 Rc8 14. Kb1 Nd7 { The sacrifice on c3 was already possible, but this is a bit more flexible. Black has the idea Ne5-c4, and in case of } 15. h4 { now we play } 15... Rxc3 $1 16. bxc3 Nb6 $44 { [%cal Gd8c7,Ga5c4,Yd6d5] with nice compensation. Although the Bb3 controls some squares on the queenside, Black has both knights ready to go to c4 and it's very easy to keep improving our position. A possible plan is to play Qc7 followed by Nc4 and prepare the advance d6-d5, which activates both black bishops. An important point is that White's attack seems slow and is still far from creating dangerous threats on the kingside. } ) 13... Rc8 14. Kb1 { Aronian, L (2781) -Giri,A (2764) Airthings Masters Prelim rapid 2020 (2) 1-0 In the game Giri went for the exchange sacrifice and got enough compensation, despite the final result. However, maybe } 14... d5 $5 { was even a simpler path to solve Black's problems. This advance is possible here because White played h2-h4 instead of g2-g4 and didn't threaten to dislodge the knight with g4-g5. } 15. exd5 ( 15. e5 $2 Nd7 16. f4 Rxc3 $1 17. bxc3 Nc5 $17 { [%cal Gc5e4] is a much better version of the sacrifice for Black. } ) 15... Nxb3 { Now White needs to include } 16. Nc6 $1 ( 16. Nxb3 Nxd5 $17 { [%csl Gb7,Ge7] is simply better for Black. } ) 16... Bxc6 17. dxc6 Qc7 18. cxb3 Qxc6 $11 { with an equal game. } ) ( 9. Qf3 Qc7 10. g4 $5 { was a recent idea by Adhiban. } 10... b4 $1 { whenever possible this advance is a good way of disturbing White's position. } 11. Nce2 Bb7 12. Ng3 d5 $1 { This thematic reaction already solves Black's problems and forces White to look for active play to not end up in a worse position. He tried to complicate the game by employing } 13. e5 Nfd7 $1 14. Ngf5 exf5 15. e6 { Adhiban,B (2660) -Mishra,A (2504) Chessable Masters Prelim rapid 2021 (11) 1-0 The most precise way of refuting White's idea now was } 15... fxe6 16. Nxe6 Qe5 { as } 17. gxf5 { can be answered by } 17... Nc5 $1 { exchanging White's most active piece. After } 18. O-O-O Nxe6 19. Bxd5 Bxd5 20. Rxd5 Qf6 21. Rd2 Nc7 $19 { Black can consolidate the position with a decisive advantage. } ) 9... O-O 10. a3 $5 { The position that white players have tried in some recent games. The idea is to keep the center stable, to complete the development with Qe2 and 0-0-0 and start advancing the kingside pawns in English Attack-style. If White's plan succeeds, the light-squared bishop will be very strong when the white pawns reach h5 and g6, opening up the opponent's king. } ( 10. g4 $6 { is hasty due to } 10... b4 $1 { when White doesn't have a good square for the knight. The lesser evil is } 11. Na4 ( 11. Nce2 $6 a5 $1 12. c3 Bb7 $15 { [%cal Gb8a6,Ga6c5] is more pleasant for Black. } ) 11... Bd7 { [%csl Ga4][%cal Gb8c6] and the knight stuck on a4 makes White's position a bit weird. } ) ( 10. Qd2 { seems a more natural square for the queen, like in the English Attack. Here I suggest } 10... Bd7 $5 { [%cal Yb5b4] when the threat of b5-b4 becomes more annoying. } 11. g4 ( 11. O-O-O $2 { now is careless as after } 11... b4 { White doesn't have a good reply. Na4 loses a piece in view of Qa5, and } 12. Nce2 a5 $17 { is also clearly better for Black. } ) 11... Nc6 { In a recent game White played } 12. Nce2 $1 { a nice idea, getting ready to recapture with the knight on d4 and anticipating the advance of the queenside pawns. } ( 12. O-O-O $2 { is the most played, but after } 12... Nxd4 13. Bxd4 a5 $17 { [%csl Yb5,Gd7] Black has a strong initiative on the queenside. Here we can see why the bishop is more useful on d7. } ) ( 12. g5 $6 { also leaves White with problems after } 12... Nxd4 $1 13. Qxd4 Nh5 { [%csl Yg5][%cal Ga6a5] winning an important tempo on g5 to continue with a6-a5. An online game went } 14. Qd2 { Fernandez Guillen,E (2462) -Aguilar,J (2254) Titled Tuesday intern op 22nd Nov Late blitz 2022 (4) 1-0 Now the simple } 14... a5 { would give an easier game for Black. For example: } 15. a4 bxa4 16. Nxa4 Bc6 $15 { [%csl Re1] It's easier to continue developing Black's play and White faces problems on both flanks. } ) 12... a5 $5 13. a3 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Qc7 15. g5 Nh5 16. Ne2 $5 { [%cal Ge2g3] ; Fernandez Guillen,E (2390) -Pichot,A (2641) Barcelona Sants op-A 23rd 2022 (4) 1-0 White plans to exchange knights on g3, removing the blockade and opening the h-file. An interesting way of facing this plan would be } 16... g6 $5 17. Ng3 Ng7 $1 { when the following variation shows that White's attack is not coming so easily: } 18. O-O-O ( 18. h4 $2 { doesn't work due to } 18... d5 $1 { [%csl Rg3][%cal Gc7g3] } 19. f4 a4 20. Ba2 b4 $1 21. axb4 a3 $17 { and White already faces some serious problems. } ) 18... Rfc8 19. Kb1 a4 20. Ba2 b4 $1 21. axb4 a3 $40 { [%cal Yd6d5] it's Black who comes first in the attack. Our next step is to open the center with d6-d5 and include the dark-squared bishop in the action. The engine evaluates the position as equal, but looks like White's first mistake can be fatal. } ) ( 10. Qe2 { was played by Kramnik and also against me in an online game. I think it can be considered imprecise though, as after } 10... b4 $1 { White's coordination is disturbed. } 11. Na4 ( 11. Nd1 $2 { Demchenko,A (2597) -Quintiliano Pinto,R (2469) Titled Tuesday intern op 17th Aug blitz 2021 (5) 1-0 was played against me. In the game I continued with a6-a5 and had a good position. Nevertheless, } 11... e5 $1 { would have been even stronger. After } 12. Nf5 Bxf5 13. exf5 d5 $17 { [%csl Yd5,Ye5][%cal Gb8c6,Ya6a5] Black has an active development and a strong pawn center. } ) 11... Bd7 $11 { [%csl Ga4][%cal Gb8c6, Ga8b8] The practical problems of the misplaced Na4 prevent White from playing for an advantage here. } ) 10... Bd7 $1 { Black has only played this move in a few games, but it seems the right way of facing White's plan. Also, it's Giri's recommendation and my engine's first choice. Although b7 looks like a more natural square, the bishop would be seriously restricted by White's center. The following analysis show how useful it proves to be on d7. } 11. g4 Nc6 { [%cal Gc6a5,Ga5c4,Ga8b8] Black might continue with Na5-c4 or maybe Rb8. } 12. g5 Nh5 $1 { [%csl Gh5] The knight seems out of play on h5, but actually it does a good job by preventing the advance of White's h-pawn. The position after } 13. Nxc6 Bxc6 14. f4 g6 $11 { [%csl Ge4][%cal Ya6a5,Yb5b4] is more or less balanced, but while Black can develop the play on the queenside it's hard to find a good plan for White. Also, further advances on the kingside can lead to more weaknesses on White's camp. } ) ( 7. O-O { is likely to transpose after } 7... b5 { with the difference that White has the option of com a diferença que as brancas tem a opçăo de } 8. Bd3 { [%cal Ya2a4] intending to play a2-a4 to weaken the enemy queenside. However, this leads to a Sicilian Kan with a tempo up for Black, and the advance of the a-pawn doesn't seems dangerous. } ( 8. Bb3 Be7 { is the main move order. } ) 8... Be7 9. a4 b4 10. Na2 e5 $1 11. Nf3 Nc6 12. Qe2 O-O { and Black is fine. For example: } 13. c3 bxc3 14. Nxc3 Nb4 15. Bc4 Be6 $11 ) ( 7. a4 { [%csl Ya4,Yb5] avoids the expansion on the queenside, but the tempo spent allows Black to achieve a good development. } 7... Be7 8. O-O { Of course, after playing a2-a4 White loses the lines with 0-0-0. } 8... O-O 9. Be3 Nc6 10. Kh1 { The most played, making an useful move and waiting a bit. } ( 10. f4 $6 { is strongly answered by } 10... d5 $1 { and Black is fine. For example: } 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. e5 Nd7 13. Bd3 a5 $15 { [%cal Ge7c5,Gd7c5,Yf7f6,Gc8a6] when Black's chances look already better for me. It's possible to exchange one of the enemy bishops by means of either Bc5 or Nc5, and the exchange of bishops on a6 also helps Black. The breakthrough f7-f6 can be used to free Black's play and create some weaknesses on White's camp. } ) ( 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. a5 $5 { is suggested by the engine. The idea is to make it hard to develop the Bc8 and secure the b6-square for White's pieces. However, the exchange on c6 also reinforces Black's control in the center. After the natural } 11... Bb7 { [%cal Yd6d5,Yc6c5] Black obtains a nice game by advancing in the center. For example: } 12. Qf3 d5 13. Rfd1 Qc8 14. Bb3 c5 15. exd5 c4 $1 16. Ba4 Nxd5 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 $11 ) ( { White can try to combine some ideas with } 10. Qe2 { waiting for } 10... Qc7 { and now play } 11. f4 { as this time Black is deprived of d6-d5. However, we have another thematic idea to fight for the center here: } 11... Nxd4 12. Bxd4 e5 $1 13. Be3 Be6 $11 { Conquest,S (2505) -Tukmakov,V (2535) Heraklion op 1992 (4) 0-1 and Black is ok. As the game shows, the doubled pawns on the e-file are actually good for Black. } ) 10... Qc7 ( { If } 10... Bd7 { White can play } 11. f4 $5 { [%cal Yf4f5] } ) ( 10... d5 $5 { is a playable alternative. The position after } 11. exd5 exd5 12. Ba2 Re8 $11 { is a good IQP for Black as we have active development. } ) 11. Qe2 ( { If } 11. Bb3 { we can keep bothering the bishop with } 11... Na5 { [%cal Gc8d7,Ga8c8] } ) 11... Nxe4 $5 { The simplest way of solving Black's problems. } ( { There are more fighting options as well. } 11... Bd7 { is the most played. } ) ( 11... Ne5 { and even } ) ( 11... Nb4 $5 { are also playable. } ) 12. Nxe4 d5 13. Bd3 ( 13. Nxc6 Qxc6 14. Bb5 { is a nice tactical try, but we simply play } 14... Qc7 $1 { [%csl Rb5,Re4] keeping two White pieces attacked. } 15. Bd3 dxe4 16. Bxe4 Bd7 $11 { [%cal Gd7c6] and Black is ok. } ) 13... dxe4 14. Bxe4 Bd7 $11 { [%cal Gc6d4,Gd7c6,Gf8d8] with an equal game. } ) ( 7. a3 { is a passive approach and usually allows Black to achieve a good game without problems. } 7... Be7 8. O-O ( { In a rapid game White tried a different plan with } 8. Ba2 O-O 9. g4 $2 { but this advance is premature in view of } 9... d5 $1 { and the initiative is with Black. } 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 exd5 12. Be3 Nc6 13. Qe2 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 { Amonatov,F (2620) -Vachier Lagrave,M (2804) Wch Rapid Doha 2016 (15) 1-0 White managed to win the game, but Black has a big advantage here. With } 14... Bg5 $1 { [%csl Rc1][%cal Gf8e8] avoiding 0-0-0 and creating the strong threat of Re8, that advantage would be even bigger. For example: } 15. Be3 Bxe3 16. fxe3 Qh4+ $17 { winning a pawn. } ) 8... O-O 9. Ba2 b5 10. f4 $2 { [%cal Yf4f5] The only active plan for White. However, it has the drawback of leaving the center unstable, and Black is ready to take advantage of that. } ( { It's possible to play something more solid like } 10. Be3 Bb7 11. f3 Nc6 { but then Black is simply fine. Ne5-c4 is an interesting idea, and in case of } 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 { [%cal Ya6a5,Yb5b4] we can prepare the advance of the queenside pawns. } ) 10... Bb7 11. f5 $5 ( { In case of something like } 11. Qe2 Qc7 $15 { [%cal Gb8d7,Ga8c8, Gb8c6] Black keeps a normal development and the e4-pawn is always a problem for White. } ) 11... e5 12. Nde2 Nbd7 $1 { Black is not in a hurry to take the e4-pawn: it's enough to fix it as a weakness. } ( 12... Nxe4 $6 { gives the kind of compensation that White is looking for: } 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. Ng3 Bb7 15. Nh5 $36 { [%cal Gd1g4,Gc1h6,Yf5f6] with a dangerous initiative on the kingside. } ) 13. Ng3 { The pawn seems well protected, but Black can increase the pressure with } 13... a5 $14 { [%cal Yb5b4] with the unpleasant threat of b5-b4. A possible continuation would be } 14. Bg5 ( 14. Nd5 { is also better for Black: } 14... Bxd5 15. Bxd5 Nxd5 16. Qxd5 Qb6+ 17. Kh1 Nf6 18. Qd3 h6 19. Be3 Qc6 $17 { [%csl Rc2,Re4][%cal Ga8c8,Gf8d8,Yd6d5] } ) 14... b4 15. Bxf6 Nxf6 16. axb4 axb4 17. Nd5 Bxd5 18. Bxd5 Rxa1 19. Qxa1 { Now we have another strong idea: } 19... h5 $1 { This move makes it hard for White to keep the position unstable. After } 20. Qd1 h4 21. Ne2 Qb6+ 22. Kh1 Rc8 $19 { [%cal Gf6g4,Gb6e3] White has to deal with too many threats. } ) ( { Even } 7. g4 $2 { has been seen in a few games. Obviously, it is a bit too early for this advance. } 7... b5 8. Bb3 ( 8. g5 { is tactically refuted by } 8... Nxe4 $1 { with the following forced variation: } 9. Bxe6 Nxc3 10. Bxf7+ $1 Kxf7 11. Qf3+ Ke8 12. Qxa8 Qe7+ 13. Be3 Qb7 $19 { and Black wins. } ) 8... b4 { [%csl Re4] The lesser evil now is } 9. g5 bxc3 10. gxf6 Qxf6 $15 { with an easier game for Black. } ) 7... b5 $1 { Black has more than one way of facing the Sozin Variation but this seems the most ambitious, fighting for the initiative. } 8. Bg5 $5 { [%cal Gd1f3,Ge1c1] An alternative and very aggressive plan, aiming a quick and active development with Qf3 and 0-0-0. Black is objectively fine, but we should know some complications that may arise. } ( 8. f4 $6 { seems a bit risky as after } 8... Bb7 { [%csl Ge4][%cal Yb5b4] White already faces problems in the center. } 9. e5 { The most concrete way of solving the problem of the e4-pawn. } ( 9. f5 $2 { is a typical idea to improve the light-squared bishop. However, as White is not well developed the advance brings more problems than advantages. } 9... e5 10. Nde2 Nbd7 $1 ( 10... Nxe4 11. Bd5 $1 { [%csl Gd5] leaves White with enough compensation for the pawn. } ) 11. Bg5 Be7 { [%csl Re4] White soon has to deal with the problem of the e4-pawn. } 12. Ng3 ( 12. Bxf6 Nxf6 13. Qd3 { is probably a safer option, but doesn't solve White's problems. } 13... Rc8 14. O-O O-O 15. Ng3 Qb6+ 16. Kh1 a5 $17 { [%cal Ya5a4,Yb5b4] ; Malik,J