ice } 14. Qxe6+ $3 { a brilliant idea by Ivanchuk. Despite the shocking effect of realizing that such a move exists, Black is ok. Still, I give it two exclamation marks for Ivanchuk's huge creativity. } 14... fxe6 15. Nxe6 { [%cal Gh1e1] An amazing position: White has sacrificed the queen for two pawns (!!) only to get an open position of the black king in the center with all the pieces taking part in the attack. The risk of such a position is that sometimes Black only realizes the dangers of the attack when it's too late. The safest path is to return some material and avoid big problems. } 15... Qe7 $1 ( 15... Qe5 { was how Karjakin tried to face the attack in the game. It went } 16. Nxg7+ Kf8 17. Ne6+ Kf7 18. Rhe1 Qxe1 $2 19. Nxc5+ Kg6 20. Rxe1 Kxg5 21. Nxb7 $18 { Ivanchuk,V (2751) -Karjakin,S (2732) Amber-rapid 17th 2008 (4) 1-0 and White had too many pawns for the exchange. } ) 16. Rhe1 Qxe6 $1 { We don't need a whole queen up to win. It's easier to give back the material and relieve the pressure against our king. } 17. Rxe6+ ( { But not } 17. Bxe6 $2 Ne7 $17 { and Black consolidates the material advantage. } ) 17... Ne7 { The analysis show that it's White who needs to be precise here in order to keep the balance. } 18. Rde1 ( 18. Bxf6 gxf6 19. Rde1 $2 ( 19. Bd5 { is a better option, but Black has the nice resource } 19... Kf7 $1 { when White has nothing better than going for a inferior ending with } 20. Rxe7+ Kxe7 21. Bxb7 Ra7 $15 { Arenas Vanegas,D (2406) -Fluvia Poyatos,J (2491) Badalona op-A 38th 2012 (9) 0-1 } ) 19... Kd7 20. Ne4 Bxe4 21. R1xe4 f5 22. R4e5 Bd6 $19 { Andrews,T (2311) -Gopal,G (2562) Philadelphia op 2008 (5) 0-1 and Black's material advantage eventually prevailed in the end. } ) 18... O-O-O $1 19. Bxf6 ( 19. Rxe7 Bxe7 20. Rxe7 Rhe8 $17 { forces favorable exchanges for Black. } ) 19... gxf6 20. Ne4 $1 { Forcing Black to part with the Bb7. } 20... Bxe4 21. R1xe4 { [%csl Ga6,Gf6] } 21... f5 22. R4e5 Bd6 23. Rxe7 Bxe5 24. Rxe5 Rhe8 $11 { Shah,J (