t for White, and Black has a good score in this position. } 14. Qf3 { I like very much the following game by an old Najdorf specialist, which illustrates Black's ideas very well: } 14... Bc6 15. Be3 Qc7 16. c3 a5 { Preventing White from freeing the poor knight. } 17. c4 Qb7 $1 { [%csl Re4] } 18. Bc2 Rac8 19. Rac1 { Janosevic,D-Polugaevsky,L Skopje Solidarnost-05 1971 (10) 0-1 The simplest now was } 19... Rc7 20. h3 Rfc8 $17 { [%cal Gc8c4,Gc6a4] and Black should win at least a pawn in the next moves. } ) ( 10. a3 { avoids b5-b4 but is too slow. As a general rule, any tempo wasted by White allows Black to achieve a good game without problems. } 10... Bb7 11. f5 { White can't avoid making this advance for too long. } ( { In case of } 11. Qf3 Nbd7 { [%cal Gd7c5] Black threatens to increase the pressure with Nc5, so } 12. f5 { is basically forced. } 12... e5 13. Nde2 Nc5 { [%csl Re4][%cal Yd6d5,Gc5b3] Besides the pressure on e4 Black threatens Nxb3 followed by d6-d5, with a lot of activity. The reply } 14. Bd5 { seems natural, but now follows a strong tactical operation: } 14... Ncxe4 $1 { exploiting the fact that the Bb7 is tactically protected by a queen check on b6. } 15. Bxe4 d5 16. Bd3 e4 $19 { Badii,M (2295) -Oll,L (2560) Clichy op 1991 (4) 0-1 Black regains the piece with a big advantage. } ) ( 11. Re1 Qc7 $17 { [%cal Gb8d7,Gb8c6] is also better for Black, as White keeps facing problems with the e4-pawn in the long run. } ) 11... e5 12. Nde2 { Compared to the notes of 10.f5 this seems an improved version for White as the knight was not dislodged from c3. However, the main problem is still the e4-pawn, which gives the better chances for Black. } 12... Nbd7 $1 ( 12... Nxe4 $2 { grabs the pawn, but after } 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. Ng3 Bc6 15. Nh5 $36 { [%cal Yd1g4,Gf5f6] White gets a dangerous initiative. } ) 13. Ng3 Nc5 { [%csl Re4][%cal Gc5b3,Yd6d5] Again increasing the pressure on e4 and threatening to activate Black's play by means of Nxb3 followed by d6-d5. } 14. Bd5 (