an easier game for Black, so it's better to sacrifice it and look for an active development. } ( 12. Qh5 { is the most played. Here Black has the strong resource } 12... Nc6 $1 { which is based on a tactical detail. } 13. Nxc6 ( 13. Nf3 $2 { is bad due to } 13... Ndxe5 $1 14. Nxe5 Qd4+ $19 ) ( 13. Be3 $5 { [%cal Ga1d1] is an interesting practical try. Instead of taking the e5-pawn and trying to deal with White's quick development, the simplest path for Black is } 13... Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Bc5 $1 { The exchanges are good for Black, as without pieces White can't create an attack to compensate for the strategic problems of the position. For example: } 15. Bxc5 Nxc5 16. Rf4 Bb7 17. Rh4 $2 h6 18. Rg4 Qd2 $19 { and Black already has a decisive advantage. } ) 13... Qb6+ 14. Be3 Qxc6 { [%csl Rb3][%cal Gc8b7] This position has occurred in one of my games and is a nice example of what happens when White's plans don't work out well in this line: He got a useless bishop on b3, a weakness on e5 and an exposed king. White's position is already very unpleasant. } 15. Rf3 { White has so many positional problems that his only chance is to play as active as possible. } 15... Bb7 16. Rg3 Bc5 $5 ( 16... g6 $17 { was probably stronger, but I didn't want to commit my kingside yet. } ) 17. Re1 Rfd8 18. Qh6 $2 ( 18. Qg5 { was a better try. } ) 18... Bf8 $1 { [%cal Yg7g6,Gf8g7] Now Black threatens to maneuver the bishop to g7 very quickly. } 19. Ne2 $2 ( 19. Qf4 { was better, but after } 19... Nc5 20. Rf1 Rd7 $17 { [%cal Ga6a5,Ga5a4] Black has a clear advantage. } ) 19... Qe4 $19 { Brandao,R (2109) -Quintiliano Pinto,R (2430) Florianopolis op 2nd 2016 (8) 0-1 and Black is already winning material. } ) ( 12. Bf4 { protects the pawn, but after } 12... Nc5 { [%csl Gb3][%cal Gc8b7,Gb8c6] Black continues developing easily with Bb7-Nc6 while keeps an eye on the Bb3, waiting for the best moment to grab the bishop pair. } 13. Nce2 { [%cal Yc2c3,Gb3c2] Hoping to bring the bishop back with c3-Bc2. } ( { In case of } 13. Rf3 { Black has a thematic idea to avoid any attacking chance on the kingside: } 13... b4 14. Nce2 Bb7 15. Rh3 Be4 $1 { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gb7e4,Ge4g6] It's not like White had any dangerous attacking prospect on the kingside, but after this maneuver it is reduced to zero. } 16. c3 Nxb3 17. axb3 bxc3 18. bxc3 Qd5 $17 { Rezan,S (2430) -Palac,M (2571) CRO-Cup 18th 2009 (2) 0-1 Black has a clear advantage and soon went on to win material. } ) 13... Bb7 14. Qe1 Nc6 15. Nxc6 ( 15. Rd1 { was played in three games. Here I like } 15... Qc7 $14 16. Qg3 Ne4 $1 17. Qh3 Nxd4 18. Nxd4 b4 $19 { [%cal Ya6a5,Ga8d8] avoiding the plan c3-Bc2. Next we can continue with ideas like a5-a4 or Rad8, and looks like White is unable to avoid material losses soon. } ) 15... Bxc6 16. Rd1 Qc7 17. c3 Be4 $1 18. Nd4 { Honfi,K-Tatai,S Bari International-01 1970 (2) 1-0 } 18... Bg6 { [%cal Gc5d3] Again the maneuver Be4-g6 reinforces the kingside and improves Black's position. } 19. Qe2 ( { If } 19. Bc2 Bxc2 20. Nxc2 Na4 $1 21. Rb1 Rad8 $17 { [%cal Gd8d7,Gf8d8,Ga4b6,Gb6c4, Ga4c5,Gc5d3] keeps a clear advantage for Black, as we have different ways of increasing the pressure on White's camp. } ) 19... Nxb3 20. axb3 b4 $17 { [%csl Ge7,Gg6] The bishop pair clearly gives a promising advantage for Black. } ) ( 12. Qf3 $2 { can be simply answered by } 12... Nxe5 $1 { as after } 13. Qxa8 $2 ( 13. Qe4 { is the best option, but after } 13... Bc5 14. Be3 Nbc6 $1 15. Nxc6 Bxe3+ 16. Qxe3 Nxc6 $17 { Black has a clear pawn up. } ) 13... Qxd4+ 14. Kh1 Nec6 $19 { [%csl Ra8] the queen is trapped and soon lost. } ) ( 12. Nf3 { makes sense: White avoids the pin on the a7-g1 diagonal and protects the e5-pawn. } 12... Bb7 13. Qe1 { [%cal Ge1g3, Gc1f4] } 13... Bxf3 $1 { A good exchange, giving up the bishop in order to increase the pressure on e5. } 14. gxf3 { [%cal Yf3f4] This seems the most natural reply, opening the g-file and preparing to reinforce the e5-pawn. } ( 14. Rxf3 { is less committal, but after } 14... Nc6 15. Bf4 Nc5 { [%cal Gc6d4] } 16. Rf1 Qb6 17. Kh1 a5 $17 { Osterman,R-Portisch,L Vidmar Memorial-02 1973 (14) 0-1 Black had a much better game. } ) 14... Qb6+ $14 { The start of a plan that secures a good advantage for Black. } 15. Kh1 ( 15. Be3 $2 Bc5 $19 { [%csl Re5] and White loses the pawn. } ) 15... Nc6 16. f4 Bb4 $1 { [%csl Gc3] The pin avoids the plan Ne4-c3-Bc2 and prepares the exchange on c3. An interesting point is that both white bishops are passive in this structure and therefore are inferior to the knights. } 17. Qe3 ( 17. f5 $2 { is a desperate attempt that doesn't work. } 17... Bxc3 18. bxc3 Ncxe5 $19 { [%cal Yb6e6,Gb6b7] } ) 17... Bxc3 18. bxc3 ( 18. Qxc3 a5 19. a4 Nd4 $40 { [%cal Gb6b7] is also better for Black. } ) 18... Na5 19. Qf3 Rac8 $17 { [%csl Rc2,Rc3] Black has an obvious advantage. White is never able to dominate the position, and the knights are always better in the endgames. } ) 12... Nxe5 $1 { Now we can accept the challenge and take the pawn. } 13. Qh5 Nbc6 ( 13... Nbd7 $6 { allows } 14. Bxe6 $1 { Perez Ponsa,F (2422) -Mareco,S (2525) Buenos Aires Duchamp Memorial 1st 2009 (3) 1-0 and the position suddenly becomes complicated. } ) 14. Nxc6 ( 14. Rad1 { was tried in some games. Here we can play } 14... Qe8 $5 { as the queen is safe on e8 and protects the Nc6. } ( 14... Qc7 { is more popular. After } 15. Nxc6 Nxc6 16. Kh1 $13 { the open lines on the kingside offer some compensation for White. } ) 15. Ne4 { Kick,J-Schrama,P Baden-Baden op 1987 (3) 0-1 } ( { The engine prefers } 15. Nxc6 { first } 15... Nxc6 16. Ne4 { and now } 16... f6 17. Qf3 Bd7 18. Qh3 { [%cal Gd1d7] } 18... Bc8 $1 19. Bxe6+ Kh8 $11 { with a balanced game. } ) 15... Bb7 { [%cal Ge5c4] Black avoids any problem by sending the knight to c4 now. The best continuation according to the engine is } 16. Nf3 ( 16. Ng5 Bxg5 17. Qxg5 Nc4 18. Bxc4 bxc4 $17 { leaves Black with a clear pawn up. } ) ( { If } 16. Nxc6 { we can answer } 16... Qxc6 $19 { That's why White should have exchanged on c6 before, deviating the knight. } ) 16... Nc4 $1 17. Nfg5 h6 18. Bxc4 bxc4 { Now White needs to find the resource } 19. Nxf7 $1 Rxf7 20. Rxf7 Qxf7 21. Qxf7+ Kxf7 22. Rd7 { Still, after } 22... Bc8 ( 22... Rb8 23. Nd6+ ) 23. Rc7 Nb4 24. Nd6+ Kf8 25. Rxc8+ Rxc8 26. Nxc8 Nxc2 $15 { White is still a pawn down and faces an unpleasant endgame ahead. } ) 14... Nxc6 15. Rf3 { [%cal Gf3h3] Threatening a dangerous attack on the kingside. } ( { If } 15. Rad1 Qc7 { [%cal Gc7e5] and the queen goes to e5. } ) 15... Qd6 $1 { [%cal Gd6e5] It's important to remember this move as it prepares a nice resource to neutralize White's attacking ideas. } ( 15... g6 $5 { is more ambitious, but perhaps riskier as well. } ) 16. Rh3 h6 17. Bxh6 ( 17. Rg3 { doesn't avoid the exchange: } 17... Qe5 18. Qxe5 ( { If } 18. Qf3 Bc5 $1 { is a precise reply. } 19. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 20. Kh1 f5 $1 { Another strong move, avoiding Ne4. } 21. Re1 Ra7 $19 { Kulaots,K (2405) -Nisipeanu,L (2500) Wch U20 Medellin 1996 (4) 0-1 and Black managed to coordinate his pieces very well. } ) 18... Nxe5 19. Bxh6 Ng6 { Black has an easier game here given the passive Bb3 and the open lines to keep developing actively. } 20. Bg5 { Groetz,H (2321) -Czakon,J (2510) Illes Medes op 2nd 2007 (6) 1/2-1/2 Now } 20... Bd6 21. Rd3 Be5 $15 { [%cal Gc8b7] followed by Bb7 would keep an advantage for Black. } ) 17... Qc5+ $1 { The point of 16...Qd6: Black returns the pawn but forces the queen's exchange. The endgame that arises after } 18. Qxc5 Bxc5+ 19. Be3 Bxe3+ 20. Rxe3 Rd8 $15 { [%csl Gb3] ;Ashton,A (2294) -Gallagher,J (2565) SUI-ch int Saas Almagell 2005 (6) 0-1 still offers better practical chances for Black in view of the open d-file and the restricted bishop on b3, which costs White some tempos to be improved. Objectively speaking White should be ok with correct play, but his position is always a little bit unpleasant and can become really worse after one or two imprecise moves. This position has occurred in one game and the way as Black exploited his small advantages with good technique is very instructive. } *
