1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 e6 7. Bb3 b5 8. O-O Be7 9. Qf3 { The main line in the Sozin Attack. Instead of carelessly advancing in the center, White tries to develop quickly and with tempo. This move creates the threat of e4-e5 and takes the chance of transferring the queen to the kingside. } 9... Qc7 { Avoiding White's main threat. } ( { As we know, } 9... Bb7 $2 { is bad due to the familiar } 10. Bxe6 $40 ) ( { In his Chessable course Giri recommends } 9... Qb6 10. Be3 Qb7 $1 { which is also interesting. The queen keeps pressure on e4 and supports the advance of the b-pawn, while the bishop keeps the e6-pawn well-defended. } ) 10. Qg3 ( { Now } 10. e5 $2 Bb7 11. exd6 Bxd6 $17 { is simply better for Black. } ) 10... O-O 11. Bh6 { Natural and good, developing with tempo and disturbing Black's coordination. } 11... Ne8 { Black's position might look passive, but is very solid. The Ne8 is not a real problem, as if the bishop retreats from h6 - and often it does - we can go back to f6. } 12. Rad1 { [%csl Gf1] The most natural, as the other rook can either come to e1 or support the advance f4-f5. } ( 12. Rfe1 { was played a few times. Now Black has } 12... Bf6 $1 { improving the bishop and preparing a subtle trap. } 13. Be3 ( { The natural reply } 13. Rad1 $2 { falls for Black's trap: } 13... Be5 14. Qg4 Bxd4 $1 15. Rxd4 e5 $19 { [%csl Rd4][%cal Gc8g4] ;Gdanski,J (2505) -Kempinski,R (2385) POL-ch 51th Gdansk 1994 (8) 0-1 } ) ( 13. Nf3 { also doesn't pose problems for Black. } 13... Nc6 14. Rad1 Bb7 15. Bf4 Rd8 16. h4 Kh8 17. Rd3 { Looks like White has a promising position and can increase the pressure on d6. However, now Black forced an instructive transformation in the pawn structure: } 17... Ne5 $1 18. Bxe5 dxe5 19. Rxd8 Qxd8 { This change of the pawn structure is usually good for Black, as his pawns severely restrict White's minor pieces. It seems that Black still has bad coordination, but as usual Giri shows an excellent understanding of Najdorf positions to solve this problem. } 20. Rd1 $2 ( 20. Nxe5 Bxh4 $11 { wouldn't give advantage for White, but was better than the game's continuation. } ) 20... Qc7 { [%csl Re4][%cal Yb5b4] As the rook has left e1 White already faces problems with the e4-pawn. } 21. a3 g6 { The g7-square can be useful both to the bishop and the knight. } 22. Ng5 Bc8 $1 { [%csl Ye6] Black takes useful prophylaxis against a piece sacrifice on e6 and controls the seventh rank. } 23. Qd3 Be7 24. Qe2 Nf6 25. Rd3 h6 26. Nf3 Kg7 $17 { [%cal Ge7c5] ;Tissir,M (2388) -Giri,A (2755) Olympiad-42 Baku 2016 (1.1) 0-1 Black's position has improved a lot. Giri kept improving his pieces in an instructive way and won a nice game. } ) 13... Bd7 { Black can continue with a normal development like in the main line. } 14. a3 Nc6 15. Nxc6 Bxc6 16. Bf4 a5 $1 17. Qd3 Qb7 $15 { [%cal Gb5b4,Ga5a4,Ya8d8,Ye8c7] ; Sevian,S (2371) -Troff,K (2421) USA-ch Saint Louis 2013 (5) 0-1 Black has a promising position. It's possible to solve the knight's problem by means of Rd8-Nc7 and the advance of the queenside pawns creates unpleasant problems for White. In the game, Black exploited these two plans and won. } ) ( 12. Be3 $5 { was played against me once. Indeed, this less exploited move is very interesting: despite having spent two tempos to put the bishop on e3, White forced the knight to go back to e8. Also, he defends the Nd4 in advance and is ready to consider the advance f4-f5 without defying the rooks. It was unexpectedly difficult for me to find an adequate answer against this move in the game. } 12... Nd7 $5 { [%cal Gd7c5] I think this is the most combative option, despite inviting White to complicate the game. } ( { Of course, } 12... Nf6 { is the most natural move. The drawback is to give White the chance of repeating moves with } 13. Bh6 Ne8 14. Be3 ) ( { In the game I decided to play } 12... Bd7 $2 { like in the main line, but this is a mistake. After } 13. f4 Nc6 14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. f5 $1 { Black is forced to make a serious concession with } 15... e5 $16 { [%csl Gd5] ;De Paula,R (2322) -Quintiliano Pinto,R (2491) BRA-ch 83rd Rio de Janeiro 2017 (8) 1/2-1/2 when the d5-square gives a serious positional advantage for White. } ) 13. Rad1 ( { During the game I was a bit worried about } 13. Bxe6 $5 { but I overestimated the sacrifice. After } 13... fxe6 14. Nxe6 Qc4 15. Nxf8 Bxf8 16. f3 Nef6 $15 { [%cal Gc8b7,Ga8e8] Black is able to mobilize the pieces with a good game. } ) ( 13. f4 $2 { now doesn't work due to } 13... b4 $1 14. Nce2 Nef6 { [%csl Re4] and White is unable to defend e4. } 15. Bxe6 { seems the only practical try, but Black simply plays } 15... Nxe4 $1 16. Qf3 Bb7 17. Bf5 Ndf6 $17 { with a better position. } ) 13... Nc5 { [%csl Re4][%cal Yb5b4] } 14. f3 ( 14. Bd5 $5 { is an attempt to complicate the game, but we can just ignore it and play } 14... Bb7 15. Bxb7 Qxb7 16. f3 Bf6 $15 { [%cal Gf6e5,Ge8f6] with a good game. } ) 14... Bd7 15. a3 Qb7 $15 { [%cal Yb5b4,Ya6a5,Ya5a4] I like Black's position. White is solid but doesn't have an attack on the kingside, while our ideas on the queenside look very promising. } ) 12... Bd7 $1 { [%csl Gd7,Ye6][%cal Gb8c6] Although we've seen this move in previous chapters, I think this is a good moment to explain why the bishop should go to d7 in most positions. It has two important roles here: overprotect the e6-pawn against possible sacrifices and support the advance of the queenside pawns by protecting b5. At first sight that might look strange as we've played b7-b5 very quickly, but the point is that in this line the advance of the b-pawn is meant to limit the enemy bishop and to create chances of counterplay on the queenside, rather than developing our bishop on b7. Another point is that White has not advanced the f-pawn yet, so in the case of f2-f3, our bishop could be passive on b7. Black's position might look cramped at first sight, but it is very solid and even more promising from a positional point of view. The knight remains on e8 for a while, but as usual, it goes back to h6 whenever White retreats the bishop. Also, the central pair e6/d6 does a good job of controlling many squares in the center and limiting the enemy pieces. Black can continue the development on the queenside and prepare the advance of the pawns on that flank to pose practical problems for White. On the other hand, if White doesn't find a concrete way of exploiting the temporary activity of white pieces, the position tends to become worse, and Black's positional advantages - more flexible structure and the Bb3 out of play - start to be felt. } 13. f4 { The previous comment makes it easier to understand why this is White's most principled option. Instead of retreating the bishop, the idea is to increase the pressure on the kingside quickly with f4-f5-f6. } ( 13. Nf3 $5 { is the second most played, aiming to avoid exchanging knights to preserve White's space advantage. } 13... b4 $5 { A natural reaction, taking advantage of White's slower play to fight for the initiative. } 14. Ne2 a5 15. Nf4 { [%cal Yh6g7,Gf4h5] } ( { If } 15. c3 { Black can continue the actions on the queenside with } 15... a4 16. Bc2 bxc3 17. Nxc3 a3 $1 18. Bc1 { The bishop is forced to retreat. After } 18... axb2 19. Bxb2 Nc6 $11 { [%cal Gc6e5,Gc6b4] the position seems equal. } ) 15... Kh8 $8 16. Bg5 Nc6 $1 { The most precise, continuing the development. } ( 16... Nf6 { was played in some games, but } 17. Qh4 $1 { keeps some pressure for White on the kingside. } 17... Bb5 $2 { Black should've developed the knight to c6 anyway. This move has the goal of preparing Nbd7, but it turns out to be a decisive mistake. } 18. Nd4 $3 { Kasparov,G (2805) -Gelfand,B (2690) Linares 11th 1993 (11) 1-0 A brilliant idea found by Kasparov. The tactical point is that if } 18... Bxf1 19. Ndxe6 $1 fxe6 20. Bxe6 $18 { [%cal Gf4g6] gives a winning attack for White. Maybe due to this brilliant win by Kasparov the variation 13...b4 was put aside. } ) 17. Bxe7 $2 { After this exchange Black faces no problems. } ( { An important difference is that now if } 17. Qh4 { instead of transposing to Kasparov-Gelfand, Black can play } 17... Bf6 $1 { [%csl Yb2] a nice detail. } 18. Bxf6 Nxf6 19. Ng5 $2 { White tries to keep playing in an attacking style like Kasparov, but now Black is better developed to face this plan. } 19... Ne5 $1 20. Nh5 { The attack is easily refuted by } 20... Ng6 21. Qh3 e5 $19 { [%csl Rh5][%cal Gd7h3]  ;Niekras,D (2221) -Nurkiewicz,M (2380) Krakow op-A 26th 2015 (2) 1/ 2-1/2 winning material. } ) ( 17. Rfe1 $14 { is a natural and playable alternative. Here Black the nice idea } 17... a4 18. Bc4 Bxg5 19. Nxg5 Ra5 $1 { [%csl Ga5] using the fourth rank to bring the rook to the game. } 20. Nf3 Ne5 $5 21. Bf1 Nxf3+ 22. Qxf3 Nf6 { [%cal Gf8b8,Gd7c6] and Black is ok. For example: } 23. Qd3 $2 e5 $15 { [%cal Gd6d5,Ya5c5] } ) ( 17. Nd5 $14 { is an attempt to create some complications, but Black has a simple way of keeping a good position: } 17... exd5 18. exd5 Nf6 $1 { giving back the piece to avoid any problems. After } 19. dxc6 Bxc6 { [%cal Ya5a4,Gf6e4] Black has active play, and in case of } 20. Bxf6 $5 Bxf6 21. Qxd6 Rac8 $13 { [%csl Rb2,Gc6,Gf6] The bishop pair and the pressure on the queenside provide enough compensation for the pawn. } ) 17... Nxe7 18. Qh4 Nf6 { Black has no problems and can start to exploit the drawbacks of White's position. } 19. Rfe1 a4 20. Bc4 e5 $1 ( 20... Qxc4 $2 21. e5 $1 { [%cal Yf4g6,Gh4c4] is White's resource. } ) 21. Nd5 Nexd5 22. Bxd5 Ra5 $1 { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gc7c2] } 23. Ng5 ( 23. Re2 Rc5 24. Ne1 Bb5 $17 { seems also difficult for White. } ) 23... Kg8 { White's ideas led to nowhere and his position is already very risky. } 24. Rd2 h6 25. Bxf7+ ( 25. Nf3 Rc5 $19 ) 25... Rxf7 26. Nxf7 Kxf7 $19 { Stupavski,Z (2392) -Palac,M (2567) Zadar op 14th 2007 (1) 0-1 and Black has a winning position. } ) ( 13. a3 { avoids b5-b4 for a while, but as we've seen in similar positions this tempo spent often allows Black to complete the development without problems. } 13... Nc6 14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. Rfe1 ( 15. f4 { is more popular but doesn't lead to an advantage for White. Compared to the main line, Black is even better developed to deal with this plan. } 15... Kh8 16. Bg5 Nf6 $1 { [%csl Re4] } 17. f5 $1 { White needs to solve the problems by tactical means. } ( 17. e5 $2 { is worse. Black has a nice way of regrouping the pieces and exploiting this advance: } 17... dxe5 18. fxe5 Bc5+ $1 19. Kh1 Nd7 20. Rfe1 Qb7 21. Rd2 { and now } 21... f6 $1 { is a strong idea. After } 22. exf6 Nxf6 23. Bxe6 Rae8 $40 { [%csl Rh1] Soon it's White who faces problems with the king's position. } ) ( { If } 17. Qh4 Rae8 $1 { [%cal Gf6e4] Black remains solid. For example: } 18. f5 $6 exf5 19. exf5 Bd8 $36 { [%cal Gc7b7,Gd8b6,Gf6e4] and Black has many active ideas to exploit here. } ) 17... Nxe4 { This forces many exchanges. } 18. Nxe4 Bxe4 19. Bxe7 Qxe7 20. fxe6 fxe6 21. Rxf8+ Rxf8 22. Qxd6 Qf6 23. Qd4 e5 $1 24. Qe3 h6 25. h3 Bb7 $11 { [%csl Ge5] ;Cabello Fernandez,E-Roiz Baztan,D (2305) Asturias-ch Preferente 1995 (9) 0-1 The position should be equal with correct play, but in the game Black exploited the passed pawn in the center and eventually won. } ) ( 15. Bf4 { was seen in some games. Here Black has the nice idea } 15... Qb7 $1 16. Rfe1 a5 { when the advance of the queenside pawns seems very unpleasant. White should play to equalize with } 17. e5 ( 17. Nd5 $2 { seems strong at first sight, but } 17... Bd8 $17 { is simple and good for Black. } ) 17... dxe5 18. Bxe5 Bf6 19. Rd4 { Short,N (2655) -Kasparov,G (2805) PCA-World-ch Kasparov-Short +6-1=13 1993 (20) 1/2-1/2 Now } 19... Bxe5 { was the simplest path for Black. } 20. Qxe5 ( { If } 20. Rxe5 b4 21. axb4 axb4 22. Na2 $2 { there is the strong resource } 22... Rxa2 $1 23. Bxa2 Qa7 { [%csl Ra2,Rd4] } ) 20... Nf6 { In the notes of the game Ftacnik considers this position as slightly better for Black. However, the analysis show that Black is fine: } 21. Rd3 { [%cal Gd3g3] This plan of attack can be neutralized by means of } 21... h6 $1 22. Rg3 Qb8 $1 { A nice defensive resource. } 23. Qe3 ( 23. Qxf6 $2 Qxg3 $19 { is the point. } ) 23... Rd8 $15 { [%cal Gg8h8,Ya5a4,Yb5b4] Black has a comfortable game. Qxh6 is not a real threat, but in any case we can play Kh8 soon. On the other hand, Black keeps very good chances on the queenside. } ) 15... a5 { Whenever White makes a calm move we can take the chance of developing our play on the queenside. } 16. Bg5 Bxg5 17. Qxg5 Rb8 18. e5 $5 { White tries to exploit the superior development by opening the game. } 18... dxe5 19. Qxe5 { Polgar,J (2705) -Anand,V (2775) London Classic 4th 2012 (7) 1/2-1/2 Black has no problems in this endgame and can even play for an advantage sometimes. For example: } 19... a4 20. Qxc7 ( { Or } 20. Ba2 Qxe5 21. Rxe5 Nf6 $11 { [%cal Gf8c8] } ) 20... Nxc7 21. Rd6 $1 ( 21. Ba2 Rfd8 $15 { [%cal Gg8f8,Gf8e7] is the kind of position which should be equal with correct play, but in practice is easier to play for Black. } ) 21... Ba8 22. Ba2 Rfc8 $11 { [%csl Ga2] The endgame should be equal, but in practice, I prefer Black in view of the potential on the queenside and White's passive Ba2. } ) ( 13. Rfe1 { is a natural and playable option, developing White's last piece. } 13... Nc6 14. Nf3 $5 { Like in the previous move, White can retreat the knight to avoid exchanges. } ( 14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. a3 { transposes to 13.a3. } ) 14... Ne5 $1 { but Black insists! This is a nice thematic idea to keep in mind. } 15. Nxe5 ( 15. Bf4 { Ahn,M (2312) -Carlsson,P (2461) EU-Cup 22nd Fuegen 2006 (3.3) 0-1 doesn't improve White's chances. } 15... Ng6 16. Bg5 Bxg5 17. Qxg5 { Now Black can start creating problems on the queenside with } 17... b4 18. Ne2 a5 { when White has nothing better than } 19. c3 a4 20. Bc2 bxc3 21. bxc3 { and now } 21... e5 $15 { [%csl Ra2, Rc3,Re4][%cal Ge8f6,Gd7e6] is very strong. Besides taking some squares from both enemy knights, the structure is fixed in Black's favor, in a way that we can put pressure in many points on the opponent's camp. } ) 15... dxe5 { [%csl Ge5,Ge6] We have another case in which the doubled pawns are very good. They limit the enemy pieces and neutralize White's play in the center, besides controlling many important squares. } 16. Bg5 ( { Another game went } 16. a3 Bc6 17. Rd3 Kh8 18. Bg5 { Markiewicz,J (2245) -Lukinov,P (2340) Kochan Memorial op 2001 (4) 0-1 Black can simply organize his position with } 18... Bxg5 19. Qxg5 Nf6 { without fearing an attack, as after } 20. Rg3 Rg8 $15 { [%cal Ya6a5,Yb5b4] White can't increase the pressure on the kingside, while the black pawns keep advancing in the opposite flank. } ) 16... Bxg5 17. Qxg5 Bc6 { Now White decided to put his hopes in an attack on the kingside: } 18. Rd3 ( { The solid alternative is } 18. f3 a5 $15 { with an easier game for Black. } ) 18... a5 19. a3 Kh8 $5 20. Rh3 Nf6 21. Qh4 { [%cal Yg2g4,Yg4g5] } 21... Rg8 $1 { [%csl Gf6,Gg8,Gh8] Black created an unusual fortress on the kingside, which nevertheless is enough to parry any attacking idea. After having secured the king's position, we can turn our attention back to the queenside. } 22. f3 $2 { [%csl Rh3,Rh4] ; Schlosser,M (2380) -Van der Vorm,T (2405) Vienna op 1996 (6) 0-1 White's heavy pieces look simply pointless on the h-file.Now with the simple } ( { The point of Black's plan is to answer } 22. g4 { with } 22... g5 $1 23. Qg3 Kg7 $19 { [%cal Yh7h6,Gg8d8] After consolidating the kingside with h7-h6 Black can play in the center and on the queenside, when White will be in trouble due to his poor coordination. } ) 22... a4 23. Ba2 b4 $1 { Black already has a winning position. For example: } 24. axb4 Qb6+ 25. Qf2 Qxb4 26. Nd1 a3 27. bxa3 Rxa3 28. Bb3 Ra1 $19 { [%csl Rh3][%cal Gg8d8] and the rook stuck on h3 will be the cause of White's defeat. } ) ( 13. Nce2 $5 { was played by a few Grandmasters like Kasimdzhanov, Polgar, and Lautier. Despite not looking so dangerous, the knight maneuver has some interesting ideas: it prepares c2-c3, reinforcing the Nd4 and vacating c2 for the bishop. Another point is that the knight can find an active role on the kingside, as Nf4 increases the pressure on e6 and the knight could go to h5 next, with dangerous threats. } 13... Kh8 { It's better not to wait for a knight arriving on h5 to make this move. } 14. Bg5 ( 14. Be3 { avoids the exchange, but after } 14... Nf6 15. f3 a5 $36 { [%cal Gb8a6,Ga6c5] Black has the initiative on the queenside and the knight can be developed via a6, with a good game. } ) 14... Bxg5 15. Qxg5 Nf6 16. Ng3 ( 16. f3 $2 Qc5 $19 { unexpectedly wins a piece for Black. } ) 16... Nc6 ( 16... Qc5 $2 { now is a mistake: } 17. Qd2 Rd8 18. Nf3 a5 19. a3 Ne8 20. Ng5 Kg8 21. Qf4 $18 { [%csl Rd6, Rf7] ;Kasimdzhanov,R (2704) -Karjakin,S (2762) Wch Rapid Berlin 2015 (11) 1-0 and White's pressure already forces material gains. } ) 17. c3 { Lautier,J (2638) -Gelfand,B (2713) FIDE-Wch k.o. 1999 (3.1) 1/2-1/2 The position is balanced and there is more than one satisfactory path. I like } 17... h6 18. Qd2 ( { Or } 18. Qe3 Na5 ) 18... Rad8 { with a solid position. For example: } 19. f4 Na5 20. Kh1 Nxb3 21. axb3 Bc8 $11 { [%cal Gc8b7] } ) 13... Nc6 14. Nxc6 ( 14. f5 { directly is very aggressive. After } 14... Nxd4 15. Rxd4 { Black has two playable options. I consider } 15... Kh8 { as the most solid. } ( 15... Bf6 { is more ambitious and leads to a complex position after } 16. Rd3 Be5 $1 17. Qg4 b4 $13 { Morozevich,A (2749) -Kasparov,G (2827) Astana 2001 (3) 0-1 with a complicated fight. } ) 16. f6 $1 { White can't slow down and should continue in the same style as in the main line. } ( { In a famous game White tried to keep the tension with } 16. Be3 Nf6 17. Qh3 $5 { [%csl Ge6][%cal Ye4e5,Yd4h4] with the very aggressive plan of e4-e5 followed by Rh4, when the pressure on the kingside seems very dangerous. However, the queen is not on g3 now, and Black took the chance of fighting for the initiative by means of } 17... d5 $1 { a thematic pawn break in the center in Sicilian positions. White tried to keep the game complicated with } 18. e5 $1 Qxe5 19. Rh4 { Mamedyarov,S (2772) -Gelfand,B (2733) Candidates Tournament 2011 (1.3) 0-1 The position looks tense, but Black can simply keep developing with } 19... Rac8 { [%cal Ge7c5,Gc8c3] with threats like Rxc3 or Bc5, avoiding ideas like Bd4 or Bg5 by White. In the game, Gelfand played the rook from f8 here, which makes sense to give that square to the king in some cases. However, the analysis shows that this move was even more precise, as White never achieves a real attack. For example: } 20. Bg5 h6 $3 { Ok, this is not a human move. } 21. g4 Kg8 $1 { and White's attack already comes to an end, as shown in the variation } 22. Bxh6 Rxc3 $1 23. bxc3 Bc5+ 24. Kh1 Qe4+ $19 ) 16... Bxf6 $1 { Black also needs to remember an important defensive resource here: } 17. Rxf6 Qc5 $1 { [%csl Gd4,Gf6,Gh6] Instead of taking on h6 or f6, both bad options, Black attacks a third enemy piece! } ( { After } 17... gxh6 18. Rxh6 Rg8 19. Qh4 Rg7 20. Ne2 $36 { [%cal Yc2c3,Gb3c2,Ge2g3,Gg3h5] the engine sees no problem, but I think White's initiative can be dangerous. } ) 18. Bxg7+ $1 ( { If } 18. Ne2 $6 { Black wins material with } 18... e5 $1 19. Rxd6 exd4 20. Rxd7 gxh6 $15 ) 18... Nxg7 19. Qf2 ( 19. Qe3 $6 { is inferior due to } 19... Qe5 20. Rf3 f5 $15 { and the queen is misplaced on e3. } ) ( 19. Qxd6 $4 { is even worse: } 19... Qxd6 20. Rxd6 Ne8 $19 { [%csl Rd6,Rf6] } ) 19... Qe5 { [%cal Gg7f5] The position remains complex, but Black has nice chances of either equalizing of even playing for an advantage. The game went } 20. Rh6 ( { Another possibility is } 20. Rf4 Bc6 21. Ne2 a5 22. c3 Qc5 { [%cal Ye6e5] } 23. Rd1 Qxf2+ 24. Kxf2 f5 $5 25. Rxd6 Bxe4 $13 { [%cal Ye6e5] with a complex endgame. In case of } 26. Bxe6 $6 Rf6 27. Nd4 Re8 { White is already forced to sacrifice something. } ) 20... f5 $1 { The counterplay comes just in time. The position looks like a mess, but the analysis shows that Black's chances are not worse. } 21. Rd1 $5 { An interesting practical try. } ( { The game continued with } 21. Ne2 fxe4 22. Qh4 Qf5 23. Rd1 e3 $1 24. Ng3 Qf2+ 25. Kh1 Bc6 $1 { Ofitserian,B (2141) -Prizant,J (2523) Izhevsk Corporation Cup 6th 2014 (7) 1/2-1/2 As surprising as it can be, the position is not only equal, as all this has been played! The game ended in a draw after a run of the black king to the center and a series of sacrifices by White. } ) 21... fxe4 22. Qh4 { Here Black has to find } 22... Rf4 $1 ( 22... Qf5 $2 { was good in the game because it created a mating threat on f1, but here White simply plays } 23. Nxe4 $18 { [%cal Ge4f6] and wins. } ) 23. Rxh7+ Kg8 { Despite the position looking extremely dangerous, Black is fine. } 24. Qh6 ( { If } 24. Rh8+ $2 Kf7 25. Qxf4+ Qxf4 26. Rxa8 { White gets two rooks for the queen, but after } 26... Qe3+ 27. Kh1 b4 $19 { [%cal Gg7f5] the better coordination of Black's pieces makes the difference. } ) 24... Raf8 $1 { [%cal Ye5d4,Gf8f1] Black should look for counter-chances instead of being worried about a single check on h8. } 25. Rh8+ ( { If } 25. h3 $6 Rf1+ $1 26. Rxf1 Qd4+ 27. Kh2 Rxf1 $15 { [%cal Gd4g1,Gd4e5] it's White who needs to find a draw somehow. } ) 25... Kf7 26. Nd5 $1 { This is not the only way of forcing a draw, but it is the funniest. } 26... Rxh8 27. Qxh8 exd5 28. Rxd5 Rf1+ $1 29. Kxf1 Qf4+ 30. Ke1 Qe3+ 31. Kf1 Qf4+ $11 ) ( 14. Nce2 $5 { still can be tried, but seems a bit strange with the pawn taking the f4-square away from the knight. Maybe White's idea is to play f4-f5 then Nf4, with a huge pressure on e6, but that is not easy to achieve. } 14... Kh8 15. Bg5 Nf6 $1 16. Qh4 Rae8 $1 { [%csl Re4] Black follows a plan seen in the notes of 13.a3. First he creates the threat of Nxe4. } 17. f5 exf5 18. Nxf5 Bxf5 19. exf5 { Now } 19... Bd8 $1 { [%cal Ge8e1] also resembles some lines seen. The bishop can be activated via b6 and the rook has an open file. } 20. Ng3 $6 { White wants to bring the knight to the kingside, but I think it is misplaced here. } ( 20. Nc3 { was safer, keeping an eye on d5. A possible continuation could be } 20... b4 21. Nd5 Nxd5 22. Bxd5 Bxg5 23. Qxg5 Re5 $11 { [%cal Gc6e7] with a balanced game. } ) 20... Ne5 21. Qd4 { Black found an active set-up now with } 21... Qb7 $1 { [%cal Gd8b6] } 22. Kh1 Neg4 $36 { Blomqvist,E (2492) -Anand,V (2784) Gibraltar Masters 14th 2016 (10) 0-1 with a promising initiative. The d6-pawn is hanging, but in return Balck obtains a nice diagonal for the bishop. } ) 14... Bxc6 15. f5 Kh8 $1 { Black's position would be hard to play without this move. Nevertheless, White can keep increasing the tension with } 16. f6 $1 ( 16. fxe6 $5 gxh6 17. exf7 { seems interesting, but after } 17... Nf6 $1 { Black has nice chances of consolidating the material advantage. One game went } 18. Qf4 b4 $1 19. Qxh6 { Esenov,A (2302) -Nikonov,A (2155) Moscow op-A 13th 2017 (7) 1-0 Despite the result, Black is winning. The simplest was } 19... bxc3 20. Rxf6 Bxe4 $19 { [%cal Yd6d5] when White has no attack and Black remains a piece up. } ) ( { If } 16. Be3 { Black can react actively with } 16... b4 $1 17. Na4 ( 17. Ne2 { is even worse due to } 17... e5 $17 { [%csl Re4][%cal Ge8f6,Gc7b7] with strong pressure on e4. } ) 17... Nf6 $1 { [%csl Re4] Now White needs to be careful. } 18. fxe6 Nxe4 19. Qh3 $1 ( 19. Qg4 $2 { was seen in one game. } 19... fxe6 20. Qxe6 { Olivier,J (2421) -Polak,T (2488) Mitropa Cup 19th 1999 (6) 1/2-1/2 Here Black missed the strong resource } 20... Bg5 $1 { [%csl Re3][%cal Gc7a7] as the undefended position of the Be3 allows to exploit the a7-g1 diagonal. } 21. Bb6 Qb7 22. Rxf8+ Rxf8 { [%csl Ra4,Rb6] and White can't avoid material losses. For example: } 23. Bd4 Re8 24. Qg4 Bf6 $1 25. Bxf6 Nxf6 $19 { [%cal Re8e2] with a decisive invasion by the rook on e2. } ) 19... fxe6 { Damaso,R (2390) -Arnason,J (2540) Olympiad-29 Novi Sad 1990 (12) 1/2-1/2 } 20. Nb6 $1 { [%csl Ge3] With the bishop protected on e3 White avoids the resource seen in 19.Qg4. } 20... Rab8 21. Rxf8+ Rxf8 22. Qxe6 Bg5 $1 23. Bd4 Nc5 24. Bxc5 dxc5 25. Nd5 Qc8 $1 26. Qxc8 Rxc8 $11 { [%csl Gc6,Gg5] The bishop pair still gives practical chances for Black, but with correct play the endgame is equal. } ) ( 16. Bg5 $2 Bxg5 17. Qxg5 Nf6 { [%cal Gb5b4] is simply better for Black. One game went } 18. fxe6 fxe6 19. Bxe6 Qa7+ $1 20. Kh1 { Sieiro Gonzalez,L-Vera Gonzalez Quevedo,R (2430) CUB-ch Cuba 1982 (9) 1/2-1/2 and Black missed a winning idea. } 20... b4 $1 21. Nd5 Nxe4 22. Qe3 Nf2+ 23. Rxf2 Rxf2 $19 ) 16... gxh6 17. fxe7 Qxe7 { After a forced sequence the resulting position has some imbalance. Black is a pawn up, but it's a doubled pawn in the worst file possible. White has lost most of the attacking potential on the kingside, but the pressure on d6 prevents Black from achieving an ideal coordination. Nevertheless, with the minor pieces restricted on the queenside White seems unable to create practical problems, and Black's position still seems quite solid. } 18. Qf2 $1 { The queen keeps an eye on both sides and prevents b5-b4 in view of the check on d4. } ( { If } 18. Qf4 { Black can force an exchange by means of } 18... b4 $1 19. Ne2 Bb5 20. Rf2 { Yu,T (2184) -Hu,Y (2043) CHN Team (Women) 2017 (7.6) 1/2-1/2 } 20... Bxe2 21. Rxe2 Qg5 { Black is fine. After exchanging queens we can bring the king to the center, otherwise the queen achieves a solid post on e5. } ) 18... Ng7 { As White relieved the pressure on d6 we can improve the knight. } ( 18... Qa7 $2 { is bad due to } 19. Qxa7 Rxa7 20. Bxe6 $16 ) 19. Qb6 ( { White managed to win some games with } 19. Qd4 { but after } 19... Rfd8 $14 { I don't see a clear way of making further improvements for White. For example: } 20. Kh1 ( 20. Ne2 Qa7 $1 { makes Black's task easier. } ) 20... Qa7 $1 21. Qf6 $2 { now Black has } 21... b4 $1 22. Ne2 Bxe4 $15 { with advantage. } ) 19... Rfc8 20. Rf2 { Kasimdzhanov,R (2706) -Gelfand,B (2748) Tashkent FIDE GP 2014 (9) 1/2-1/2 White takes measures against Qa7 and gets ready to double rooks either on the f or the d-file. } ( 20. a3 { was played once. The way as Black slowly improves his position is very instructive: } 20... a5 $1 21. Kh1 $6 h5 $1 { [%cal Yh5h4,Yh4h3] If White allows, the idea is to advance the pawn as far as possible. } 22. Rd3 Qa7 $1 { The queens exchange works out nicely for Black here, despite giving back the pawn. } 23. Qxa7 Rxa7 24. Rxd6 b4 $1 { The point: Black loses on d6 but wins the e4-pawn. } 25. axb4 axb4 26. Ne2 ( 26. Na2 $2 { is worse, as after } 26... Bxe4 27. Nxb4 { Black has } 27... Nf5 $1 28. Rd2 Rg8 $19 { [%csl Rg2][%cal Gf5h4,Gf5e3] with a huge pressure on g2. } ) 26... Bxe4 27. Rd4 Ba8 28. Rxb4 Nf5 $17 { [%cal Gf5e3] ;Michiels,B (2442) -Bu,X (2710) Antwerp InventiChess 2008 (3) 0-1 Black has a strong pressure on the kingside and soon forced material gains again. } ) ( { Another point of White's move is that } 20. Kh1 { can be answered by } 20... Rab8 { and White can't play } 21. Qxa6 $2 { due to } 21... b4 $19 { [%csl Rc3][%cal Gc6b5] } ) 20... Rab8 { This might be a small improvement for Black. } 21. Qd4 ( 21. Qxa6 $2 { is a serious mistake as after } 21... Qc7 { [%csl Ra6] the queen is trapped on a6. } 22. Rdf1 Be8 $19 { [%cal Gb8a8] and Black wins. } ) ( { If } 21. Qe3 { we can keep improving the position with } 21... Rb7 $1 { as the h6-pawn is not hanging in view of b5-b4. } 22. Rdf1 { can be met by } 22... Qg5 $1 23. Qxg5 hxg5 24. Rxf7 Rxf7 25. Rxf7 b4 { and Black regains the pawn, although after } 26. Na4 Bxe4 27. Nb6 $44 { White's activity looks enough to keep the balance. } ) 21... a5 22. Rdf1 Rf8 23. a3 h5 $11 { [%cal Yb5b4,Gh8g8,Ge7g5,Ge7b7,Yh5h4,Yh4h3] The game goes on and the engine says the position is equal. This evaluation makes sense, as Black can't easily make use of the pawn and White keeps the pressure on the kingside and on d6. On the other hand, Black's position is solid and we can try to make progress slowly. The first step is to bring the king back to g8 in order to reinforce f7. Then it's possible to consider either Qg5 and h4-h3 or Qb7, increasing the pressure on e4 and creating the threat b5-b4. } *
