1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. g3 { This variation has the reputation of being a solid option for White and was played by many Grandmasters, like Carlsen, Anand, Vachier Lagrave, etc. } 6... e5 { This seems a good reaction to 6.g3 in order to limit White's fianchettoed bishop. On the other hand, from g2 the bishop increases White's control over d5. } 7. Nb3 { The second most played. } ( 7. Nf5 $6 { here is worse than in other lines as after } 7... d5 $1 8. Bg5 d4 9. Bxf6 gxf6 $1 10. Nb1 Bxf5 11. exf5 { Black has } 11... Qd5 $1 12. Rg1 Nc6 $15 { with advantage. } ) 7... Be7 { [%csl Gc8] An important reminder: it's good to keep the bishop on c8 for a while, as in some positions we have the chance of developing it on b7. } ( { I used to play } 7... Nbd7 { but one game made me change this line. First, my opponent played } 8. a4 $1 { avoiding the expansion on the queenside with b7-b5. This also creates the positional threat of a4-a5, so Black is more or less forced to reply } 8... b6 9. Bg2 Bb7 10. O-O Be7 { Now he continued his plan with } 11. Nd2 $1 { [%csl Yd5][%cal Gd2c4,Gc4e3] Threatening Nc4-e3. This wouldn't be possible if Black could play b7-b5. I answered naturally with } 11... Rc8 12. Qe2 { Renewing the previous threat. } 12... Qc7 { and now } 13. Rd1 $1 { [%cal Gd2f1,Gf1e3] bringing another piece to fight for d5 and preparing an alternative route for the knight. } 13... O-O $2 { This natural move is a mistake. As it often happens in this structure, it only takes one imprecise move for Black to face problems with the d5-square. } ( { Correct was } 13... Nc5 14. Nf1 Ne6 $13 { [%cal Ge6d4] and Black achieves some counterplay with the knight coming to d4. White's position still is probably easier, but at least I could have put some fight here. } ) 14. Nf1 Rfe8 $6 ( { Now } 14... Nc5 $5 { is one move late, allowing } 15. Bg5 $1 { and favorable exchanges for White. After } 15... Ne6 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Ne3 Nd4 18. Qd3 $16 { [%csl Gd5][%cal Yc2c3,Gc3d5] White has a clear advantage. He has strong control over d5, and the knight soon will be pushed back from d4. } ) 15. Ne3 $14 { [%csl Gd5] ;Valerga,D (2451) -Quintiliano Pinto,R (2469) Mercosur Cup 21st 2017 (3) 1-0 After making many natural moves I suddenly realized that my position was slightly worse. My opponent showed excellent technique from this point to handle his positional advantage. This is an instructive example of how easy is to face problems in this structure in case of careless play. } ) 8. Bg2 ( { An important detail on the move order is that } 8. a4 { is not as effective now as in the previous note. As Black hasn't committed the knight to d7 yet we can go for a much better set-up, starting with } 8... Nc6 $1 9. Bg2 Nb4 $1 { [%csl Yb4][%cal Gb8c6,Gc6b4] An important idea which should be remembered: always that White plays a2-a4 too early Black has the chance of maneuvering the knight to b4. From here it keeps pressure on c2 and an eye on d5, and White doesn't have an easy way of attacking it. } 10. Bg5 { My opponent looks for favorable exchanges in order to increase his control over d5. } 10... Be6 $1 { In the previous note my main mistake was to castle too early and underestimate the danger of White's mobilization around the d5-square. After getting a better positional understanding of such positions, I do the opposite and develop my pieces in the best way around the outpost before casting. } 11. O-O Rc8 $1 { [%csl Gc2] Now, the pressure on c2 makes it almost impossible for White to play Nd5. } 12. a5 { [%cal Ga1a4] White finally finds a way of disturbing the Nb4. However, after } 12... Qd7 $1 { he had to find another plan. } 13. Nc1 ( 13. Ra4 $2 { fails due to the tactical detail } 13... Nxc2 $1 14. Qxc2 Qxa4 $19 { [%cal Gc8c2] } ) 13... O-O 14. Nd3 Nxd3 15. cxd3 { White finally managed to get rid of the annoying Nb4. However, in doing so he had to move the pawn from c2 to d3, practically losing any chance of making use of the d5-square. Now I started to play for the advantage with } 15... h6 { Guo,A (2219) -Quintiliano Pinto,R (2451) Saint Louis SPICE Cup op 11th 2017 (4) 0-1 as the exchange on f6 leaves Black with the bishop pair, and if the bishop retreats I have the freeing advance d6-d5. Black's position is already easier, and this game is a nice model of how to deal with the positional problems of the d5-square. } ) ( 8. Bg5 $5 { is an interesting move order played by Vachier Lagrave against Wei Yi. } 8... Be6 ( 8... Nbd7 { was Wei Yi move and is also possible. However, after } 9. a4 h6 10. Be3 { Vachier Lagrave,M (2777) -Wei,Y (2724) Hamburg FIDE GP 2019 (1.1) 1-0 } 10... O-O $1 { direct is more precise, instead of b7-b6 like the Chinese GM played in the game. } ) 9. Bxf6 { This quick exchange is seen in some lines of 6.h4 and 6.Be2 e5 7.Nf3. The point is to disturb Black's coordination and establish control over d5 before Black achieves the ideal set-up with Nbd7. } ( 9. f4 $5 { is suggested by the engine and was seen in one game, this time with Vachier Lagrave on the black side. } 9... exf4 10. Bxf4 Nc6 11. Qd2 O-O 12. O-O-O { Le,Q (2709) -Vachier Lagrave,M (2784) Skilling op Prelim rapid 2020 (7) 0-1 Now the position resembles some English Attack variations due to the opposite castles. In this specific position, Black doesn't need to worry about the d6-pawn and can continue developing with } 12... Rc8 { in view of } 13. Bxd6 Bg4 { regaining the pawn on e4 after many exchanges, or } 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. Re1 Ne5 $44 { [%cal Gf8d8,Ge5f3,Yb7b5,Yb5b4] with very good compensation. } ) 9... Bxf6 10. Qd3 { [%cal Ge1c1] White aims to get a quick pressure on d6. } ( 10. h4 { curiously transposes to one line seen in the 6.h4 line. Black should play } 10... Be7 { [%cal Gb8d7] preparing to develop the knight to d7. } ) 10... O-O { As the analysis show, Black shouldn't worry about the pawn. } ( { Also, } 10... Be7 $6 { is not so good now in view of } 11. O-O-O Nd7 12. f4 $14 { and White has some pressure in the center. } ) 11. O-O-O ( 11. h4 { allows Black to play actively with } 11... a5 $5 { [%cal Ya5a4] } 12. a4 Nc6 $36 { [%cal Gd8b6,Ga8c8,Gc6b4] and Black can develop an unpleasant initiative on the queenside with moves like Qb6, Rc8 or Nb4. } ) 11... Qb6 $1 { [%csl Rf2][%cal Ya6a5] A good reply, exploiting the weak points in White's camp. } 12. Qd2 a5 $5 { This is an interesting way of provoking new weaknesses in White's position. In case of } 13. a4 { instead of taking on b3 we can play } 13... Na6 $36 { [%cal Gf8d8,Ga6b4,Yd6d5] with the idea of maneuvering the knight to an active outpost on b4. Also, if we manage to prepare and make the freeing advance d6-d5 then all Black's pieces become active. } ) 8... O-O 9. O-O b5 $5 { This quick advance used to be considered dubious, but both analysis and tournament practice have proved that it's perfectly playable. } ( { The classic set-up } 9... Be6 10. a4 Nbd7 { is still the most popular. White continues with the typical plan } 11. Re1 { [%cal Gb3d2,Gd2f1,Gf1e3] preparing the maneuver Nd2-f1-e3. Black also has a good game and is able to solve the opening problems in this position. } ) 10. a4 { The typical reaction to the quick advance of the b-pawn. The idea is to exploit the fact that Black is not fully developed to create some weaknesses on the queenside. } ( 10. Nd5 { directly is less dangerous as Black keeps the queenside intact. } 10... Nxd5 11. Qxd5 Ra7 12. Be3 Be6 13. Qd2 Ra8 14. a4 ( 14. f4 { doesn't create any threat, so Black can keep playing on the queenside with } 14... a5 $1 15. f5 Bc4 16. Rfe1 Nd7 17. Rad1 Qc7 18. Nc1 { [%cal Yb2b3] ;Lupulescu,C (2627) -Palac,M (2546) EU-ch 19th Batumi 2018 (11) 1/2-1/2 Now } 18... b4 $17 { [%csl Rc2] would be strong, vacating some squares for the bishop and fixing the c2-pawn. } ) ( 14. Na5 $5 { doesn't pose any serious problem for Black's development. We can simply play } 14... Qc7 { [%cal Gb8c6] followed by Nc6. } ) 14... Nc6 { This is the point: Black is not forced to commit the queenside now. } ( 14... Nd7 { maybe is even a bit more precise. } ) 15. axb5 axb5 16. Rxa8 Qxa8 17. Ra1 Qb7 { [%cal Gf8a8] ;Naiditsch,A (2710) -Vidit,S (2693) ESP-chT CECLUB Honor 2017 (6.2) 1/2-1/2 Black had no problems to keep the balance. } ) ( { The plan seen in the notes of 7...Nbd7 doesn't work now. After } 10. Re1 Nbd7 11. Nd2 Bb7 12. Nf1 { Black has } 12... b4 $1 { as after } 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. exd5 { [%csl Yd5] Black has no problems with either the d5-square or the d6-pawn anymore. That's why White always aims to recapture with a piece on d5, keeping control over both the outpost and the d-file. Here the structure was fixed in Black's favour and we can play } 14... f5 { activating the kingside majority. The position is still equal from an objective point of view, but I like Black's prospects. } ) 10... b4 11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. Qxd5 ( { From the last note we can imagine that } 12. exd5 $6 { is imprecise. Here it's even worse as after } 12... a5 $1 { [%csl Ya5,Yb4][%cal Yf7f5,Gb8d7,Gb8a6,Gc8d7] Black reaches a very stable position on the queenside and can develop the pieces in more than one good way. } ) 12... Ra7 13. Be3 Be6 $1 { An important intermediate to disturb the enemy queen. } ( 13... Rd7 $2 14. Na5 $18 { is already a decisive advantage for White. } ) 14. Qd3 { The best way of making Black's development harder. } ( 14. Qd2 { [%csl Yb4] might look more natural, but after } 14... Rb7 { the a6-pawn is not attacked, so Black can bring the knight to the game more easily. } 15. a5 { [%csl Ya6,Yb4] A typical move to isolate the queenside pawns. } ( { In case of } 15. f4 { we can simply continue with } 15... Nd7 $1 { since f4-f5 is not a threat as the bishop has the c4-square. Of course, this wouldn't be possible with the queen on d3. } ) ( { Another game went } 15. Rfd1 Qc7 16. Rac1 Nd7 17. Bf1 Ra8 18. c4 a5 $11 { Adams,M (2729) -Alekseev,E (2716) ESP-chT finals 2007 (2) 1/2-1/2 and again Black was able to stabilize on the queenside, with a solid position. } ) 15... Qc8 $14 { [%csl Ya6] I've already recommended this move in 2018, but it remains unplayed. The queen is well placed on the c-file in many lines, and by defending the a6-pawn it is easier to develop the knight. } 16. Rfc1 ( { Against } 16. Ra4 { Black has an active idea based on a pawn sacrifice: } 16... Nd7 $1 17. Rc1 { and now } 17... Re8 $1 { waiting for } 18. Rxb4 Rxb4 19. Qxb4 { as now Black has } 19... d5 $1 { with an active game. For example: } 20. Qa4 $6 { is already imprecise, as after } 20... d4 21. Bd2 Qb7 $17 { [%cal Ge6d7,Gd7c6,Ge8c8,Gd7f6] Black is very active and can develop strong pressure on White's camp. } ) 16... Qc6 $5 { The queen keeps an eye on many important squares: a4, a6, and e4. } 17. f4 ( { The plan of putting pressure on a6 with } 17. Qd3 Nd7 18. Bf1 { can be answered by } 18... Rb5 $1 { and Black is ok. For example: } 19. c3 $5 bxc3 $1 20. Rxc3 Qb7 21. Nd2 Nc5 $1 22. Bxc5 dxc5 23. b3 Rd8 24. Qc2 Rb4 25. Bc4 Qc6 $11 { Black's position is active enough to keep the balance. } ) 17... Nd7 18. c4 $5 { [%cal Yf4f5] } 18... f6 $1 { It's seems safer to keep the queenside closed. } ( 18... bxc3 19. Rxc3 Qb5 20. Bf1 $1 { [%csl Ga6] leads to a complicated position. The engine says it is equal, but I think is too concrete and therefore risk in practice. } ) 19. Qe2 { [%cal Gb3d2] White can go for a maneuvering game here aiming to bring the knight to d5 at some point via d2-f1-e3. Nevertheless, Black always has a way of facing this plan before the opponent reaches the goal. } 19... Nc5 20. Nd2 ( { The first natural attempt would be } 20. Bxc5 dxc5 21. f5 Bf7 22. Nd2 { [%cal Gd2f1,Gf1e3,Ge3d5] when the knight seemingly has a free path to d5. However, Black's counterplay comes just in time: } 22... Rd8 23. Nf1 Rbd7 $1 { [%csl Yd2] The pressure on the d-file makes White's plan much harder. } 24. b3 Rd3 25. Rd1 $5 Rxd1 26. Rxd1 Rxd1 27. Qxd1 { The exchange of all rooks seems to reduce Black's counterplay, but after } 27... Qd6 $1 { [%cal Gd6d4] } 28. Qxd6 Bxd6 $17 { [%csl Ga5][%cal Gd6c7]  Black wins the a5-pawn. This is an instructive example of how to face the positional plan Nd2-f1-e3 with dynamic play. } ) 20... b3 $1 { Another important move to remember whenever the knight leaves b3. This advance prevents White from consolidating the queenside and secures our counterplay. It's also an important improvement over my 2018 analysis. } ( { Previously I've recommended } 20... Bf7 $2 { but after } 21. b3 $1 Rd8 22. f5 $14 { only White plays. Black is deprived of any counterplay, and White can slowly but steadily prepare a pawn break on the kingside. Back in 2018, I evaluated this position as balanced, but now I think White has slightly better chances. } ) 21. Bf2 { [%csl Ye3][%cal Gd2f1,Gf1e3] A logical continuation, vacating e3 for the knight.The following regrouping is also very instructive: } ( { The inclusion of } 21. f5 Bf7 22. Bf2 { doesn't help much. Actually, keeping the pawn on f4 is good because sometimes White can consider bringing the knight to f5 or improving the bishop on h3. The variation } 22... Rb4 $1 23. Nf1 Rc8 24. Ne3 Ra4 $1 { is a good illustration of that: as Black doesn't need to worry about ideas like Nf5 or Bh3, it's possible to organize the pieces in a very comfortable way. After } 25. Nd5 Bd8 $11 { Black's position seems very safe. } ) ( { If } 21. Nb1 { [%cal Gb1c3] } 21... Rb4 $1 { [%csl Yc4] and the pressure on c4 prevents White from continuing the knight's journey. } 22. Bd2 $2 Ra4 $1 23. Rxa4 Nxa4 $17 { is already better for Black. } ) 21... Rb4 $1 22. Nf1 Bd8 $1 23. Ne3 Ra4 $1 { [%csl Ga5, Gc4] Black has pressure on many points of White's camp, which is enough to keep the balance. Let's see some possible continuations that support this evaluation: } 24. Rxa4 ( 24. Nd5 Kh8 $1 { It's necessary to avoid the check on e7 to threaten the a5-pawn. } 25. Rxa4 Qxa4 26. f5 Bf7 27. Bxc5 $5 dxc5 28. Qe3 Bxd5 29. Qxc5 Be7 $1 30. Qxe7 Re8 31. Qc7 Bg8 $11 { [%cal Ga4a2] The threat of Qa2 forces White to be careful here. } ) 24... Nxa4 25. f5 ( 25. Qd2 { can be answered by the brave } 25... Qc5 $1 { and Black goes after the a5-pawn, as } 26. Nf5 $2 { fails tactically due to } 26... Bxa5 $19 ) 25... Bf7 26. Nd5 Bxd5 27. exd5 Qc7 { [%csl Ya5] Now White has a choice between the active } 28. c5 $5 ( { Or the more solid } 28. Ra1 { but after } 28... Nc5 29. Ra3 Qc8 30. g4 Re8 31. Be4 Re7 $11 { [%cal Ge7b7] Black's position also looks very solid. } ) 28... Nxc5 29. Bxc5 dxc5 30. Qc4 { but the position is probably balanced. For example: } 30... Qxa5 31. d6+ Kh8 32. Qxb3 c4 $1 33. Qxc4 Qb6+ 34. Kh1 Qxd6 35. Qd5 $11 ) 14... Ra8 $5 { I have liked this move since I saw it in Grischuk's game. The rook goes back to its initial square, but the idea is to keep the a6-pawn protected. } ( 14... Rb7 { is the most played, but I find it a bit riskier, mainly due to the following instructive game by Ponomariov: } 15. Rfc1 $1 Qc7 $6 16. c3 $1 { A strong resource, opening the queenside in an advantageous way for White. } 16... Bc4 ( 16... Bxb3 $2 17. cxb4 { [%csl Rc7][%cal Gd3b3] is the tactical point. } ) 17. Qc2 Be6 18. Qd1 $1 Qd8 19. Bf1 $1 { Now Black has to deal with the pressure on a6. } 19... bxc3 20. Rxc3 Bg5 $2 { Although the exchange of this bishop is usually good for Black, here it has the opposite effect. After } 21. Bxg5 Qxg5 22. Bc4 $1 Bxc4 23. Rxc4 $16 { [%csl Ra6,Rd6][%cal Ga1c1] ;Ponomariov,R (2734) -Safarli,E (2620) Olympiad-40 Istanbul 2012 (10.2) 1-0 the two weaknesses on the queenside made Black's position very unpleasant. } ) 15. f4 { The most played, creating tension in the center aiming to provoke some concession by Black. } ( 15. Rfc1 { is a flexible move, but with the a6-pawn defended we can just continue developing with } 15... Nd7 16. f4 { Fluvia Poyatos,J (2445) -Smith,T (2193) Barbera del Valles op 36th 2013 (8) 1-0 Here Black could have played } 16... a5 { and if } 17. f5 Bxb3 18. cxb3 $1 ( 18. Qxb3 $2 Bg5 $17 { [%csl Gd7,Yg2] gives a strong positional advantage for Black as the knight is going to be much superior to the bishop in this structure. } ) 18... Bg5 $5 { still can be considered, this time sacrificing a pawn. In practice, Black gets very good compensation. A possible variation would be } 19. Rc6 ( 19. Bxg5 Qxg5 20. Qxd6 Qe3+ 21. Kh1 Nf6 $36 { [%cal Gf6g4] seems already dangerous for White. } ) 19... Bxe3+ 20. Qxe3 Rc8 21. Rxd6 Qc7 22. Rad1 Nf6 $44 { [%cal Gf8d8] As White's pawn up is double on the queenside, it's not so important by now. A possible plan would be to exchange all the rooks and try to exploit the superior tandem QN x QB. } ) ( 15. a5 { is a logical continuation, but again Black simply develops the knight. } 15... Nd7 { [%cal Gd7c5] Already threatening to exchange knights on c5. White avoided that with } 16. Nd2 { but Black keeps mobilizing his play on the queenside without problems. } 16... Qc7 17. Rfc1 { Marinkovic,I (2444) -Arsovic,G (2483) Serbia-chT Zlatibor 2006 (5) 1-0 The natural } 17... Rfc8 { keeps a good game for Black here. For example: } 18. c3 Nc5 19. Qe2 bxc3 20. Rxc3 Qb7 $11 ) 15... Qc7 ( { In his Chessable course Giri recommends } 15... a5 $5 { keeping Black's position more flexible. } 16. Rfc1 { This also keeps White's position flexible and prepares a possible pawn break on the queenside. Now Giri suggests the clever waiting move } ( { If } 16. f5 { Black can reroute the bishop to another good diagonal: } 16... Bc8 $1 { [%cal Gc8a6] and after } 17. Qd5 Ra6 { [%cal Ge7g5,Gb8d7,Gd7f6] we have a good position. It's possible to continue mobilizing the pieces with Nd7-f6, but Bg5 is always an idea to consider as well. } ) 16... h6 $5 { The point of Giri's idea is to answer } ( { White's idea is to answer } 16... Qc7 $2 { with } 17. c3 $36 { taking the initiative, like in Ponomariov-Safarli. } ) 17. f5 { with } 17... Bxb3 18. cxb3 Bg5 $11 { [%csl Yb8,Ge3,Yg2,Gg5] forcing the exchange of the bad bishop. The position remains objectively equal, but in practice, we are always happy with a knight and promising play on the dark squares against White's bad bishop. } ) 16. Nd2 ( { If } 16. Rfc1 Rc8 $1 { is good, preventing c2-c3. } ) 16... a5 $1 { Securing the queenside pawns. } 17. Rf2 { Played by Hou Yifan. White doesn't have a clear plan here, so she keeps the tension and vacates f1, which can be useful both for the knight or the bishop. } ( 17. f5 Bc8 $1 { [%cal Gc8a6] only helps Black, as the bishop finds an excellent diagonal on a6. } ) 17... f6 { Grischuk keeps playing solid and reinforces his position in the center. } 18. f5 { I don't like this advance, as after releasing the tension Black has a very solid position in the center. } ( { She had a creative idea here: } 18. Bh3 $5 Bf7 $1 ( { But not } 18... Bxh3 $2 19. Qd5+ { [%csl Ra8,Rg8] } ) 19. c4 $5 Na6 20. b3 $11 { and White has a solid position. It seems unlikely that she can hope to play for an advantage, but her position would've been at least safe. } ) 18... Bf7 19. Rc1 Na6 $15 { [%cal Ga6c5] ;Hou,Y (2652) -Grischuk,A (2750) Moscow FIDE GP 2017 (5) 0-1 In practice I already like Black's position. The knight comes to c5 and we can prepare the advance d6-d5 to activate Black's play. White's position seems more passive and the only active plan is to open the c-file, but since it leads to the creation of weaknesses in her camp it is not an easy decision to make. Hou Yifan eventually tried to open the position, but Grischuk answered with dynamic play and won a nice game. } *
