1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. g3 e5 7. Nf3 { In some games White has tried this strange move. There are two possible plans for this knight: reaching d5 via h4-g2-e3, which is impossible, and the maneuver Nh4-f5, which is highly unlikely. } 7... Be7 8. Bg2 ( { White can try to accelerate the plan with } 8. Nh4 $5 { but we simply ignore it and play } 8... O-O $1 ( { If we waste one tempo with } 8... g6 { White plays } 9. Ng2 $1 { [%cal Gg2e3,Gf1g2] and suddenly the idea pays off. } ) 9. Nf5 { The most direct. } ( { If } 9. Bg2 g6 $1 { [%csl Gf5] takes f5 away from the knight, forcing White to find a new plan. } 10. a4 ( 10. Bh6 { looks good, but after } 10... Re8 { White can't avoid b7-b5 in view of the threat Ng4. } 11. h3 b5 $1 12. a3 Bb7 { Black already has a satisfactory position. } 13. Qd2 { [%cal Gh4f5] ;Safarli,E (2676) -Mansner, H (2278) EU-Cup 34th Porto Carras 2018 (1.3) 1-0 White wants to make Nf5 work by tactical means. The right way of refuting this idea was } 13... Nfd7 $1 { [%csl Yg5] preventing the check on g5. After } 14. Nf3 Nb6 15. O-O N8d7 16. Rad1 Rc8 $17 { [%cal Gb6c4,Gd7f6] Black has a very good game. } ) ( 10. O-O { Nepomniachtchi,I (2767) -Volokitin,A (2649) Wch Blitz Doha 2016 (1) 1-0 Whenever that possible Black should play } 10... b5 $5 { looking for an active development on the queenside. A logical continuation now is } 11. a4 b4 12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. Qxd5 Ra7 14. Be3 Be6 15. Qd2 Rb7 { when the position resembles other lines of 6.g3, but White still needs to retreat the knight. } 16. Nf3 { The structure is pretty much the same as seen in the previous chapter, but the knight is probably worse on f3 than b3. } 16... Nd7 $11 { [%cal Gd7f6] Black's position seems at least fine for me. } ) 10... Nc6 $1 { [%csl Gb4] As it often happens in similar positions, when White plays a2-a4 to avoid the expansion on the queenside the knight can go to b4. } 11. O-O Bd7 $5 { A nice and subtle developing move. The bishop might look passive on d7 at first sight, but it is better placed here than on e6 for many reasons. First of all, White can't disturb the bishop by means of ideas like f4-f5 or Nf3-g5. The most important point, however, is that if the white knight jumps to d5 we can simply play Nxd5 without losing a piece. } ( 11... Bg4 { was played in another game. After } 12. Nf3 Rc8 13. h3 Be6 14. Bg5 Nb4 $11 { Schippers,M (2276) -Tsolakidou,S (2414) Gibraltar Masters 17th 2019 (9) 0-1 Black also had a good game. } ) 12. Re1 Rc8 13. Nf3 Na5 { Black keeps making natural and good moves while White has no plan. } 14. h3 Re8 15. Qd3 Qc7 16. Qe3 $6 { [%csl Yh6] A strange maneuver. The idea seemingly is to transfer the queen to h6, but Black always has Bf8 in response. } ( { After } 16. Bg5 Nc4 { the initiative is already with Black. For example: } 17. Bxf6 $2 Nxb2 $17 { [%cal Gc7c3] } ) 16... b5 $36 { Oparin,G (2609) -Nepomniachtchi,I (2768) RUS-ch 71st Satka 2018 (9) 0-1 I like Black's position. We have no problems avoiding the enemy threats on the kingside, while the pressure on the queenside seems more serious and unpleasant for White. } ) ( { In case of } 9. Ng2 { Giri recommends to disturb White's play by means of } 9... Bg4 $5 { although it's also possible to develop normally by means of b7-b5 followed by Nbd7-Nb6. } 10. Be2 { The lesser evil, since f2-f3 would weaken the dark squares and Qd3 leaves the queen exposed to Nbd7-Nc5. } 10... Be6 $1 11. Ne3 Nc6 { [%csl Ye2][%cal Ga8c8,Gc6d4,Ge2f3,Gf3g2] Black can continue with Rc8-Nd4, with a good position. Also, White sooner or later has to spend two moves to bring the bishop back to g2, where it belongs. } ) 9... Bxf5 10. exf5 { White managed to maneuver the knight to f5 and forced the opening of the long diagonal. However, Black is ahead in development now and can take the initiative in the center with } 10... d5 $1 11. Bg2 ( 11. Bg5 Nbd7 { is harmless. Actually, after } 12. Bg2 e4 13. O-O h6 $17 { Black is already better. } ) 11... d4 $1 { Black shouldn't fear the blockade on the light squares, as White is unable to keep it. } 12. Ne4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 { Kovalev,V (2703) -Yuffa, D (2582) EU-ch 20th Skopje 2019 (8) 1/2-1/2 } 13... Qc7 $14 14. O-O ( { If } 14. Qf3 { we can sacrifice the pawn: } 14... Nd7 $1 15. Bxb7 Rab8 16. Be4 Nf6 17. O-O Nxe4 18. Qxe4 Bf6 $44 { [%csl Gb2,Gc2] The pressure on the queenside makes it hard for White to continue developing. } ) 14... Nd7 { [%cal Ga8c8,Gd7c5,Gd7f6] Black has a good game: the blockade on e4 is not stable, and we can develop counterplay against c2. A possible continuation would be } 15. Re1 ( 15. Bg2 Rac8 { [%csl Gc2] } ) 15... Rfe8 16. Bd2 Nf6 17. Bd3 Bf8 $11 { with a balanced game. } ) 8... O-O 9. O-O ( 9. Nh4 g6 $1 { transposes to the previous note. } ) ( 9. a4 { avoids b7-b5, but as we know Black can always exploit this move by means of } 9... Nc6 $1 { [%csl Gb4] } 10. O-O Be6 11. Nh4 Nb4 $1 { [%csl Gd5] Thanks to this knight Black keeps a good control over d5. } 12. Nf5 Bxf5 13. exf5 d5 14. Bg5 e4 15. a5 { [%cal Ga1a4] ;Ponkratov,P (2601) -Sarana,A (2587) RUS-chT Sochi 2018 (8.1) 1/2-1/2 An interesting idea now would be } 15... Rc8 { intending to answer } 16. Ra4 { [%cal Gg5f6] with } 16... b5 $1 { as after } 17. axb6 Qxb6 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. Nxd5 Nxd5 20. Qxd5 e3 $13 { Black obtains more than enough compensation for the pawn in the form of active play. } ) 9... b5 $1 { This advance is always good to give an active development and chances of counterplay for Black on the queenside. } 10. a4 { A natural reaction and the most played nowadays, but it doesn't pose any problems for Black. } ( { In one game White went for a more active set-up: } 10. Bg5 Nbd7 11. Nh4 h6 12. Be3 ( { In case of } 12. Bxf6 Nxf6 13. Nf5 Be6 14. Ne3 Rc8 { the pressure on the c-file makes it hard for White to exploit the outpost on d5. For example: } 15. a3 Rc5 $1 16. Qe2 Qd7 $15 { [%cal Gf8c8] and I already prefer Black's position. } ) 12... Nb6 13. Bxb6 Qxb6 14. Nf5 Bxf5 $2 { This is a positional mistake as Black can't avoid the blockade on the light squares. } ( { Correct was } 14... Ra7 $1 { and if } 15. Ne3 Be6 { [%cal Ga7c7,Gf8c8] Black has a playable position. } ) 15. exf5 Rac8 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. Bxd5 $14 { [%csl Gd5] ; Balogh,C (2638) -Kanakaris,G (2359) GRE-chT 45th 2017 (2.9) 1/2-1/2 The Bd5 is better than its counterpart on e7 as it supports ideas on the kingside. White has the better practical chances here, but the game eventually ended in a draw. } ) ( 10. Nd5 { was seen in an encounter between two strong GMs. When I first analyzed this line in 2018 still there were only a few games with 7.Nf3 and this was the game with the highest average rating. } 10... Bb7 { Increasing the pressure in the center. } 11. Nxe7+ { White decides to take the bishop pair, but from a strategic point of view I think this exchange favors Black since he exchanges a bad bishop for a strong knight. } ( 11. Nxf6+ { was perhaps more logical. } 11... Bxf6 12. Re1 Be7 13. Nd2 { [%cal Gd2f1,Gf1e3] White prepares to maneuver another knight to d5, but Black can exploit the time spent in this maneuver to create counterplay: } 13... Nd7 14. Nf1 Nc5 $1 { [%csl Ye4] Now White is forced to protect e4 before continuing the maneuver. } 15. c3 ( 15. f3 { seems strategically bad for many reasons, but it also has a concrete problem. Black has a strong idea } 15... d5 $1 16. exd5 Bxd5 17. Rxe5 Be6 18. Qxd8 Rfxd8 $36 { [%cal Ga8c8,Ge7f6] with strong initiative for the pawn. } ) 15... Qd7 16. Qc2 { White seems finally ready for Ne3, but Black can break through with } 16... f5 $1 17. exf5 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Rxf5 $15 { [%cal Gd7b7,Ga8f8] when the advantage is with Black in view of the initiative coming on the kingside. } ) 11... Qxe7 12. Nh4 Qe6 $1 { A nice multi-purpose move: Black anticipates Nf5 and avoids the pin on g5, and the queen is well placed to support the advance d6-d5. } 13. Re1 ( 13. Nf5 d5 $1 { gives active play for Black. } ) 13... Nbd7 { Black has a good and harmonious development. } 14. Qe2 ( { In case of } 14. Nf5 d5 15. Bh3 { Black simply plays } 15... Kh8 $1 { avoiding the discovered check. } ) 14... Rac8 15. c3 Rc4 $1 16. f3 ( 16. Qc2 Rfc8 { [%cal Yb5b4,Yd6d5] looks also unpleasant for White. } ) 16... d5 $36 { Hammer,J (2662) -Hansen,E (2629) Saint Louis Fall-A 2018 (1) 0-1 From this point Black took the initiative and won a nice game. } ) 10... b4 11. Nd5 { When I analyzed this line in 2018 there were only three games in this position. Now this number has increased a little (12 games) , but practice has shown that } 11... a5 $1 { is enough to keep the queenside pawns safe and gives a good game for Black. } 12. Nh4 ( { In another game White tried to improve the plan of maneuvering the knight to f5 with } 12. Nxe7+ Qxe7 13. Nh4 { but the idea is so harmless that Black doesn't even need to avoid it. } 13... Nc6 14. Nf5 $2 Bxf5 15. exf5 d5 $1 { The d5-pawn is obviously protected by tactical reasons, so Black simply has a strong pawn center. After } 16. c4 bxc3 17. bxc3 { [%cal Gc1a3] } 17... Rfd8 18. Ba3 Qc7 19. Rb1 e4 $17 { [%csl Ye5][%cal Gc6e5,Gc7e5] ;Gadimbayli,A (2460) -Yilmaz,M (2607) Moscow Aeroflot op-A 2020 (1) 0-1 Black had a clear advantage. } ) 12... Nxd5 { Now we can make this exchange in better circumstances: } 13. Qxd5 Ra6 $1 { [%csl Yd6][%cal Ga6c6] An important point on Black's 11th move: the rook not only helps in the defense of d6, it also can be maneuvered to c6 in order to put pressure on c2. This position has occurred in a recent game that went } 14. Nf5 Qc7 15. Be3 ( 15. Bd2 $5 { [%cal Yc2c3] might be an improvement for White. } ) 15... Be6 16. Qd2 Rc8 17. Rfc1 Rc6 18. c3 bxc3 19. Rxc3 Bf8 20. Rac1 Qd8 $11 { Livaic,L (2563) -Santos Latasa,J (2648) EU-ch 22nd Terme Catez 2022 (5) 0-1 The position is equal, but I like Black's chances in view of the bad bishop on g2 and the unstable position of White's knight. Black eventually exploited his better coordination and managed to win. } *
