1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. g3 e5 7. Nde2 { The main line. As we've seen in 7.Nb3 and 7.Nf3, White often faces some problems in finding a good square for this knight. Retreating it to e2 makes that task relatively easier, as White has two main plans: g3-g4 and Ng3 or a quick Nd5 followed by Nec3. } 7... Be7 8. Bg2 ( 8. a4 { as usual allows Black to establish good control over d5 by means of the maneuver Nc6-b4. } 8... Nc6 $1 ( 8... b6 $5 { [%cal Gc8b7,Gb8d7,Gd7c5] is also possible, aiming a quick development of the queenside. } ) 9. Bg2 Nb4 10. O-O Be6 11. b3 { [%cal Gc1a3] White wants to get rid of the annoying knight by means of Ba3. } ( 11. Nd5 $6 { is imprecise due to } 11... Nfxd5 $1 12. exd5 Bf5 $36 { and Black takes the initiative. } ) 11... Rc8 $5 { The most ambitious option, keeping the tension. } ( 11... d5 { is a more direct path to equalize: } 12. exd5 Nfxd5 13. Ba3 Nxc3 14. Nxc3 { Ghaem Maghami,E (2599) -Vachier Lagrave,M (2716) Olympiad-38 Dresden 2008 (2) 1/2-1/2 The safest now is } 14... Rc8 15. Bxb4 Bxb4 16. Nd5 Bxd5 17. Bxd5 Qe7 $11 { [%cal Ge8g8] with a very balanced game. } ) 12. Ba3 Qb6 13. Qd2 { [%cal Ya4a5] Creating the threat a4-a5, so Black should play } 13... a5 $1 { [%csl Gb4] reinforcing the knight. Giri finishes his analysis here saying that a possible plan for Black is to prepare the advance d6-d5. Let's see how the game could develop from here: } 14. Rac1 O-O 15. Nb5 { [%cal Yc2c3] White threatens c2-c3 and seems to have an advantage, but } 15... d5 $1 { is a very strong reply. As the analysis shows, the ensuing complications are not worse for Black: } 16. c3 { năo săo piores para as pretas. } ( 16. Bxb4 Bxb4 17. c3 Bc5 18. exd5 Rcd8 19. c4 e4 $1 20. Qf4 Bg4 $36 { [%cal Gf8e8,Ye4e3] gives a strong initiative for Black. } ) ( { The safest is } 16. exd5 Bxd5 17. Bxd5 Nbxd5 18. Bxe7 Nxe7 $11 { with equality. } ) 16... Nxe4 $1 17. Bxe4 dxe4 18. cxb4 e3 $1 19. Qxe3 ( { Safer is } 19. fxe3 { but after } 19... axb4 20. Rxc8 Rxc8 21. Bxb4 Rd8 $1 { Black has a strong attack. For example: } 22. Qe1 $2 Bxb4 23. Qxb4 Qxe3+ 24. Rf2 Rd1+ 25. Kg2 Bd5+ 26. Kh3 Qxf2 $19 ) 19... Qxe3 20. fxe3 axb4 21. Bb2 f6 $1 { [%csl Gb3] A curious position: Black has only one pawn for the piece but is about to get a second one. On the other hand, White's minor pieces are passive and limited by the enemy structure. } 22. Rxc8 Rxc8 23. Rc1 $2 { seems a natural continuation, but after } 23... Rd8 $17 { [%csl Rb3][%cal Gd8d2] White is already in trouble. } ) 8... b5 $1 { Black has many options, but I like this quick advance. As we can see, in almost all lines of 6.g3 Black should play b7-b5 as quickly as possible, and in this case, we can go for it even before castling. } 9. Nd5 { [%cal Ge2c3] This became the main line in the last years, vacating the c3-square to improve the Ne2 as soon as possible. } ( 9. a4 { is harmless. } 9... b4 10. Nd5 a5 $1 { [%csl Gc3,Re2] Now White struggles to improve the Ne2 and Black achieves a comfortable game. } ( { It's also possible to play } 10... Nxd5 11. Qxd5 Ra7 12. Be3 Be6 $1 { [%csl Ge2] as White still has the problem of the passive knight on e2. } ) 11. Nxe7 Qxe7 12. c4 O-O 13. O-O Na6 14. b3 Nc5 15. f3 { Wen,Y (2604) -Tran,T (2524) Asian Continental op 17th 2018 (3) 1/2-1/2 with a balanced position. An interesting way of mobilizing Black's pieces here would be } 15... Be6 16. Be3 Rac8 { [%cal Gc5b3] } 17. Rc1 Nfd7 $15 { [%cal Gd7b6,Yf7f5] and he could have developed play on both flanks, combining the pressure on the queenside with the breakthrough f7-f5 to open lines on the kingside. } ) ( 9. h3 { [%cal Ge2g3,Yg3g4] used to be very popular, accelerating the plan g4-Ng3. However, in this move order, Black has an interesting plan: } 9... Nbd7 $1 { The reason why it's more precise to start developing the knight soon becomes clear. } 10. g4 b4 $1 11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 ( 12. Qxd5 Rb8 $15 { [%cal Gc8b7,Ge8g8,Gd7f6] is already easier for Black. } ) 12... a5 $1 { [%cal Gc8a6] The point of keeping the bishop on c8: now we can develop it more actively via a6, and instead of playing Bb7-a6 we did Nbd7-Ba6, which is much better. } 13. O-O { This seems very natural as White can answer Ba6 with Re1 followed by Ng3. However, Black has different plans here: } 13... h5 $1 { drastically changing the character of the position! In practice, this idea is very strong, as White has to deal with an unexpected attack on the kingside. } 14. gxh5 { White has to go into the complications. } ( { The attempt of playing solid with } 14. Ng3 $2 { is bad due to } 14... hxg4 15. hxg4 Bg5 $1 { and Black develops a winning attack. The following variation is very instructive: } 16. Ne4 Bxc1 17. Nxd6+ Kf8 18. Qxc1 Nf6 19. Nxc8 Nxg4 $19 { [%csl Rc8][%cal Gd8h4] and Black wins. } ) 14... Rxh5 { [%csl Rg1,Rh3] } 15. Nd4 $2 { Despite looking like a clever idea, this only helps Black. } ( 15. Ng3 $15 { was a better option, keeping the knight close to the kingside. Nevertheless, Black's position is already more pleasant. } ) 15... Nf6 16. Nc6 Qc7 17. Qf3 Bf5 $15 { [%csl Rg1][%cal Gc7d7] ;Alekseev,E (2708) -Dominguez Perez,L (2708) Biel GM 41st 2008 (8) 0-1 Black developed strong pressure on the kingside and won a nice game, which became a model against this move order with 9.h3 and 10.g4. } ) ( { In case of } 9. O-O { I consider } 9... Nbd7 $1 { the most precise. The point is to answer Nd5 with Nxd5 when it's not so easy for White to recapture with the queen. } 10. h3 { Preparing the typical plan g4-Ng3. } ( 10. a4 { only helps Black: } 10... b4 11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 a5 $1 { [%cal Gc8a6] A thematic idea after exchanging knights on d5 is to develop the bishop actively via a6. } 13. c3 Rb8 14. Be3 Ba6 15. Re1 O-O $17 { Deepan Chakkravarthy,J (2466) -Bruzon Batista,L (2679) Dubai op 18th 2016 (7) 0-1 with a clear advantage for Black. } ) ( 10. Nd5 { directly is also harmless: } 10... Nxd5 11. Qxd5 Rb8 $11 { [%cal Ge8g8,Gd7f6,Gc8e6,Gd8c7] ; Shvayger,Y (2332) -Bulmaga,I (2449) Online Olym Div2 B rapid 2020 (7.3) 0-1 Black can mobilize her pieces very easily and achieves a good development in the next moves. } ) 10... Bb7 11. g4 Nc5 12. Ng3 O-O 13. Nf5 $5 { It White wants to play actively it has to be done right now. } ( 13. Re1 { preparing the knight's jump allows Black to play } 13... g6 $1 { and if } 14. Bh6 Re8 15. Qd2 Nfd7 $13 { [%cal Ga8c8,Gc5e6,Ge7g5] we have nice chances of counterplay using the dark squares. This is a drawback of this plan g4-Ng3: If White is not able to create active ideas in order to justify the inferior structure, Black can develop strong play in the dark squares in the long run. } ) 13... Rb8 $5 { This simple move threatens to take on e4. Despite the knight looking beautiful on f5, White lacks a clear way of increasing the pressure. } ( 13... Ncxe4 $2 { loses a piece: } 14. g5 $1 Nxc3 15. Nxe7+ Qxe7 16. gxf6 Qxf6 17. bxc3 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 $18 { Kotter,R (2364) -Womacka,M (2440) Bundesliga 1516 2015 (5.7) 1/2-1/2 } ) 14. Re1 ( 14. Bg5 { was seen in one game. It went } 14... b4 15. Nxe7+ Qxe7 16. Nd5 Bxd5 17. exd5 h6 18. Be3 Nfd7 19. b3 f5 $1 20. gxf5 Rxf5 { and Black is at least fine. } 21. Qg4 { Pap,M (2491) -Womacka,M (2436) Arber op 6th 2017 (6) 1-0 In the game Black retreated the rook to defend the h6 pawn, but } 21... Rbf8 $1 { would be even stronger, as if } 22. Bxh6 $2 e4 $17 { [%cal Gd7e5] allows Black to develop a strong attack. } ) 14... b4 $1 15. Nd5 Nxd5 16. exd5 Bc8 $1 { Exchanging both White's knights seems a good idea, as the bishop pair doesn't look dangerous in this position. } 17. Nxe7+ ( 17. Ng3 $2 { is a positional mistake as it allows } 17... Bg5 $17 { [%csl Rg2,Gg5] getting rid of Black's worst piece and leaving White with a bad bishop. } ) 17... Qxe7 18. Be3 Nd7 19. f4 { White should try to open the game for the bishops, but Black can reply actively with } 19... f5 $5 20. g5 h6 $5 21. h4 hxg5 22. hxg5 Qf7 $11 { [%csl Gh5][%cal Gf8e8,Gd7f8,Gf8g6,Ya6a5]  with a double-edged game and chances for both sides. Both sides have to watch the h5-square and Black can fight for the e-file with Re8, after which the maneuver Nf8-g6 can be considered. The counterplay on the queenside with a6-a5 is always there as well. } ) 9... Nbd7 $1 { Black keeps the tension and brings the second knight to help in the fight for the d5-square. } ( { The difference is that now in case of } 9... Nxd5 10. Qxd5 Ra7 11. Be3 Rb7 12. Qd3 $1 { [%cal Ge2c3,Gc3d5] the knight can be easily improved via c3-d5. } ) 10. Nec3 { In this position Black has achieved good results with } 10... Nb6 $1 { [%csl Gd5] with the clear goal of exchanging all the knights, thus reducing the importance of the outpost. } ( 10... Bb7 11. a4 $40 { Carlsen,M (2876) -Grischuk,A (2781) Norway Chess 3rd 2015 (5) 1-0 gave a small pressure for White in some games. } ) ( { But } 10... Nxd5 $5 { is Giri's recommendation in his course and may be a playable alternative. } ) 11. Nxe7 { The most played. } ( { In one game White tried to be creative with } 11. Nxb6 Qxb6 12. a4 b4 13. a5 $6 { but this doesn't bring any advantage. } 13... Qc7 14. Na2 $6 { Hammer,J (2680) -Ragger, M (2689) NOR-chT 1516 2015 (9.4) 0-1A possible improvement for Black now would be } ( { The lesser evil was } 14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. Qxd5 Rb8 { [%csl Rc2] though Black has a pleasant game already. } ) 14... Rb8 { as if } 15. Bd2 { we have the strong reply } 15... d5 $1 { with a very active position. For example: } 16. exd5 Bg4 $1 17. f3 ( { Objectively better is } 17. Qc1 Qc4 $1 18. f3 Qxd5 19. O-O Be6 $17 { with an obvious advantage for Black. } ) 17... Bf5 $19 { [%csl Gc2,Gd5,Re1] and White's position is simply horrible. } ) ( 11. Nxf6+ { was played by Giri once. } 11... Bxf6 12. O-O O-O 13. b3 { [%cal Gc1a3] White plans to activate the bishop via a3. The drawback of this move is to leave the Nc3 unprotected, which allows Black to develop pressure on the c-file. } 13... Qc7 14. Qd2 $5 Be6 15. Ba3 ( { In another game White opted for the most solid } 15. Bb2 { Vitiugov,N (2730) -Sarana, A (2613) RUS-ch 71st Satka 2018 (2) 1/ 2-1/2 but in this case Black has no problems to mobilize his pieces and get a good game. } 15... Rfc8 $5 { In the game Black has brought the other rook to c8, but that allowed White to look for initiative on the queenside later by means of a2-a4. } 16. Rfc1 h6 17. h4 Qc5 $11 { [%cal Ya6a5,Ya5a4,Gf6d8,Gd8b6] Here Black can consider a5-a4 to put some pressure on the queenside, and another idea to keep in mind is Bd8-b6, activating the bishop. Also, the pressure on the c-file makes it hard for White to consider any active idea. } ) 15... Rfc8 $1 { Black's counterplay is enough to keep the balance here. For example: } 16. Nd1 a5 $1 17. Ne3 ( 17. Bxd6 $2 { leads to material losses: } 17... Qd7 { [%csl Rd6][%cal Gd7d2] } 18. Qd3 Nc4 $17 ) 17... b4 18. Bb2 Nd7 $11 19. Rfd1 $2 ( 19. Rad1 Ra6 { [%cal Ga6c6] } ) 19... Bg5 $17 { and Black is already better. } ) 11... Qxe7 12. Bg5 ( 12. a4 { was tried by Anand in a rapid game. } 12... b4 13. a5 $2 { This is just a blunder. } ( { Better was } 13. Na2 a5 14. c3 bxc3 15. Nxc3 Ba6 16. Nb5 O-O $11 { but it's White who plays for equality here. } ) 13... bxc3 14. axb6 cxb2 15. Bxb2 Rb8 $15 { [%csl Gb6] ;Anand,V (2759) -Grischuk,A (2766) Leuven GCT rapid 2018 (7) 0-1 and Black simply wins a pawn. } ) ( 12. Be3 { Salgado Lopez,I (2615) -Asis Gargatagli,H (2487) ESP-ch 80th Linares 2015 (6) 1/2-1/2 is also harmless, but has an interesting point. } 12... Qc7 $1 { [%cal Gb6c4] The most precise way of reorganizing Black's pieces, threatening Nc4.A possible variation now would be } ( { White's idea is provoking } 12... Nc4 { to answer } 13. Bg5 $1 { that's why the queen goes to c7, avoiding the pin in advance. } ) 13. a4 b4 14. Bxb6 Qxb6 15. Nd5 Nxd5 16. Qxd5 Rb8 17. O-O Be6 18. Qd2 O-O $11 { and Black has no problems. } ) 12... O-O { Remember to complete the development first. } ( 12... h6 { seems a natural reaction, but allowed White to achieve a small advantage in one game: } 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. a4 $1 bxa4 ( { Now } 14... b4 $2 { is bad because the queen is misplaced on f6: } 15. Nd5 Nxd5 $2 16. Qxd5 Ra7 17. Qc6+ Bd7 18. Qb6 $16 { [%csl Ra7,Rb4] winning a pawn. } ) 15. Nxa4 Nxa4 16. Rxa4 { [%csl Ga6,Gd6] ;Giri, A (2784) -Wojtaszek,R (2723) Qatar Masters op 2015 (3) 1-0 The engine says the position is objectively equal. However, in practice, White has an easier game in view of the two weaknesses in Black's camp and eventually exploits this advantage with nice technique. } ) 13. O-O ( 13. Qf3 { was an attempt by Karjakin but didn't work. } 13... Be6 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Qxf6 gxf6 { Black can compensate for the damaged structure with active play. The game went } 16. O-O-O b4 $1 17. Nd5 $6 ( 17. Ne2 { was safer. After } 17... Rfd8 18. b3 a5 19. Kb2 Kf8 $11 { [%cal Gf8e7] the endgame is equal, but I even prefer Black's practical chances. } ) 17... Nxd5 $1 18. exd5 Bf5 { [%csl Gc2] } 19. f4 Rfc8 20. Rd2 Rc5 $17 { [%csl Rc2][%cal Ga8c8,Ya6a5,Ya5a4] ;Karjakin,S (2781) -Vachier Lagrave,M (2796) Norway Chess 5th 2017 (9) 1/2-1/2 Black is clearly playing for the advantage already. } ) ( 13. a4 { now is pointless as Black is already castled. } 13... b4 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Nd5 Nxd5 16. Qxd5 { Gu,T (2171) -Wang,J (2365) CHN-ch (Women) 2018 (10) 0-1 } 16... Bg4 $5 { and Black has a good game. } ) 13... h6 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 { Black has already solved the opening problems. } 15. a4 b4 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. Qxd5 { Now we should remember } 17... Be6 $1 { a key idea. Black sacrifices the d6-pawn but obtains very active play in return. Also, White is unable to organize the pieces in order to exploit the material advantage. } 18. Qxd6 a5 19. Qb6 ( { It's not easy to make use of the pawn: } 19. Qd2 Rac8 20. Rac1 Rfd8 21. Qe3 Qe7 { Black's position is already easier. For example: } 22. f4 $5 ( { In case of } 22. Qb6 Qc5 $1 23. Qxc5 Rxc5 $15 { [%cal Gd8d2,Gd8c8] Black should regain the pawn with better chances in the endgame. } ) 22... Bd7 $1 23. b3 Bg4 $1 { [%cal Gc8c3] Despite the pawn advantage White is in trouble here. } 24. c3 bxc3 25. Rxc3 Qb4 $1 26. Rxc8 Rxc8 27. fxe5 Rc3 28. Qf4 Be6 $19 { [%csl Ra4,Rb3] Black will regain the two pawns and more. } ) 19... Rfc8 { The most precise. } ( 19... Rfb8 { was played in one game, but helps White to improve the queen. Nevertheless, after } 20. Qe3 Rc8 21. Rfc1 Qe7 22. Bf1 Bc4 $1 23. c3 Bxf1 24. Kxf1 bxc3 25. Rxc3 Qb4 $13 { Wen,Y (2581) -Sjugirov,S (2663) CHN-RUS Summit Men 11th 2018 (1.4) 1/2-1/2 Black's counterplay is still enough to keep the balance. } ) 20. Rfc1 Qe7 21. Qe3 ( 21. h3 Qc5 $1 { was the threat, as now Black regains the pawn by force after } 22. Qxc5 Rxc5 23. Bf1 Rac8 { [%csl Rc2,Rh3] } ) 21... Rc5 { Black's plan is simple and good: to put as much pressure as possible on c2, making it impossible for White to make any progress. } 22. Bf1 ( 22. c3 { doesn't work: } 22... Rac8 23. cxb4 Rxc1+ 24. Rxc1 Rxc1+ 25. Qxc1 Qxb4 26. Qc2 Qe1+ 27. Bf1 Bh3 28. Qc4 Bxf1 29. Qxf1 Qxe4 $11 ) 22... Rac8 23. Ba6 ( 23. Bd3 { seems a nice idea to free White's pieces from defending c2. However, Black has } 23... Bc4 $1 { as after exchanging bishops the rooks get access to the seventh rank. } 24. Rd1 ( 24. Bxc4 Rxc4 25. c3 Qc7 { and Black regains the pawn. } ) 24... Bxd3 25. cxd3 Rc2 { The pressure on the seventh rank offers enough compensation for the pawn. For example: } 26. d4 $5 ( 26. Rab1 Qe6 { [%cal Ge6b3] looks even a bit dangerous for White. } ) 26... exd4 27. Qxd4 R8c4 $1 28. Qd8+ Qxd8 29. Rxd8+ Kh7 $11 { [%csl Rb2,Re4] } ) ( 23. c3 Qc7 { [%csl Rc3] } 24. Ba6 { seems a clever idea, but Black has the strong reply } 24... bxc3 $1 25. bxc3 ( 25. Bxc8 $2 cxb2 $19 ) 25... Ra8 26. Bb5 Rc8 27. Ra3 { and now comes the typical exchange } 27... Bc4 $1 28. Bxc4 Rxc4 $11 { [%csl Ga4,Gc3,Ge4] when White's pieces are passive and tied to defensive roles. } ) 23... R8c6 { Just remember to keep the c7 square available for the queen. } 24. Bb5 Rc8 25. Ba6 $11 { Navara,D (2745) -Wojtaszek,R (2744) Gashimov Memorial 5th 2018 (3) 1/2-1/2 Without seeing a clear plan to make progress, White went for the repetition. } *
