1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. a4 { A perfectly playable sideline. White takes serious prophylactic measures against b7-b5 and can consider cramping the enemy queenside with a4-a5 in the future. Another point is to make a useful move and wait for a slight definition of Black's development. There are many ways to face this move, but I like } 6... g6 $5 { heading towards Sicilian Dragon positions. A nice point is that the inclusion of a4/a6 in practice deprives White of going for aggressive lines with 0-0-0, and the variations with 0-0 usually don't pose serious problems for Black. } ( 6... e5 { is the most played and leads to typical Najdorf positions. White replies with } 7. Nf3 { [%emt 0:00:10] with the typical positional battle for the d5-square. } ) 7. Be2 ( 7. g3 { is another option that can be considered against the Dragon, but it is usually harmless for Black, and the inclusion of a4/a6 here doesn't improve White's chances. } 7... Bg7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O Nc6 10. Nde2 ( 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. e5 $6 { seems an interesting try, but actually leads to an inferior position for White. } 11... dxe5 12. Bxc6 Rb8 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 14. Re1 e6 $11 { [%csl Yb2][%cal Gf6d5,Gc8b7] ; Ghinda,M (2450) -Istratescu,A (2470) ROM-chT Romania 1993 (1) 0-1 Black is totally fine and managed to develop an unpleasant pressure on the queenside. } ) 10... Rb8 { [%cal Gb7b5] Practice has shown that the quick counterplay on the queenside gives excellent chances for Black. Now the game transposes to the 6. g3 variation of the Sicilian Dragon. } 11. Nd5 { A common plan in such positions: White prepares to limit the Bg7 with c2-c3, and the exchange on d5 leaves Black with a target on e7 after exd5. } ( 11. h3 { is the second most played, but gives an extra tempo for Black. } 11... b5 12. axb5 axb5 13. Bg5 $5 { A move that was tried by Judit Polgar and other GMs. } ( { In case of } 13. Be3 { I like } 13... e6 $5 { [%csl Yd5][%cal Gb5b4] a move which was seen only in three games, but looks very interesting. Black controls the d5-square and b5-b4 becomes a very annoying threat. In the game, he tried to solve the issue by means of } 14. Nf4 { but after } 14... b4 $1 15. Na4 { Stanojoski,Z (2506) -Wells,P (2504) Olympiad-36 Mallorca 2004 (14) 0-1 Black could have achieved an advantage with } 15... Ba6 16. Re1 Bb5 $15 { [%csl Ra4][%cal Gf8d8,Gf6d7,Gd8c7] It's very easy to continue the mobilization of Black's forces, and the knight stuck on a4 soon forces White to make some concession. } ) ( 13. Nd5 { is similar to 11.Nd5 and should be answered in the same way: } 13... Nd7 $1 { [%csl Yb2] } 14. c3 { Now Black has } 14... e6 $1 { [%csl Gd5] kicking the knight to a less favourable square. } 15. Ne3 Qc7 16. Nd4 b4 $1 17. Nxc6 Qxc6 18. Bd2 { Alekseev,E (2708) -Svidler,P (2738) Moscow Tal Memorial Blitz 2008 (23) 1/2-1/2 Now something like } 18... Ba6 19. Re1 bxc3 20. Bxc3 Bxc3 21. bxc3 Ne5 $15 { leaves Black with a small but pleasant advantage. } ) 13... h6 14. Be3 b4 15. Nd5 Nd7 $1 { [%csl Yb2,Gd5][%cal Ye7e6] This retreat is a typical and important way of facing White's plan: Black gains one tempo by attacking b2 and prepares e7-e6, as the white knight lacks a decent square. } 16. Qc1 { [%csl Gh6] The main idea behind 13.Bg5: White provokes h7-h6 in order to win a tempo later with either Qd2 or Qc1. } ( 16. Nd4 $2 { seems a natural reply, but is actually a serious - though typical - blunder: } 16... Bxd4 $1 17. Bxd4 e6 $1 { and after any knight's move Black plays e6-e5 in the next, winning a piece. } ) 16... Kh7 17. Rd1 { Polgar,J (2709) -Mamedov,R (2628) TUR-chT Konya 2012 (1) 1-0 Here it's possible to improve Black's play by means of } 17... e6 18. Ndf4 Nb6 $17 { [%cal Gb6c4] and Black's position seems already better, as the threat of Nc4 is very unpleasant. } ) 11... b5 ( { Now in case of } 11... Nd7 { White can play } 12. c3 b5 13. axb5 axb5 14. Nd4 $14 { with some pressure. } ) 12. axb5 axb5 13. Bg5 ( { If } 13. c3 b4 $13 { Black has nice counterplay. } ) 13... Nd7 $1 { [%csl Gb2] This retreat works better than two moves ago as now it comes with tempo. } 14. Qc1 ( { Black is ok after } 14. c3 h6 15. Be3 e6 16. Nb4 $5 Nxb4 17. cxb4 Ne5 $11 { [%cal Ge5c4] } ) 14... Re8 $1 { A nice prophylactic move, overprotecting e7 and preventing the exchange of the strong dark-squared bishop with Bh6. } 15. Rd1 b4 $1 { Another good move, as if White tries to limit the bishop with c2-c3 now it leads to the creation of a weakness on the queenside. } 16. Ra2 Nc5 17. Be3 { Zivkovic,S (2309) -Todorovic,G (2470) Belgrade Winter op 2008 (6) 0-1Here Black missed a strong continuation to take the initiative: } ( 17. b3 { is more solid, but Black has a good game after } 17... Ba6 18. Qd2 Bxe2 19. Qxe2 Ne6 $11 { [%cal Ge6d4] } ) 17... Ba6 $1 18. Qd2 b3 $1 19. cxb3 Nxb3 20. Qc2 Bxe2 21. Qxe2 e6 22. Nc3 Ncd4 23. Qd3 Rb4 $15 { [%cal Gd8b8, Gb3c5] and Black keeps an unpleasant pressure on the queenside. } ) 7... Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. Be3 { A natural development for this bishop, as after the eventual advance a4-a5 it is well placed on e3 to keep the enemy queenside cramped. } ( 9. Bg5 { is another possible set-up. The bishop looks more active on g5, but it doesn't create serious problems for Black. } 9... Nc6 10. Nb3 Be6 11. Re1 ( 11. Kh1 { [%cal Yf2f4] is a more aggressive plan, but Black's kingside is always solid enough. } 11... Rc8 12. f4 Na5 { The typical reaction for Black is to answer f4-f5 with Bc4. } 13. Nxa5 ( { The direct } 13. f5 $6 { allows a thematic strong reply: } 13... Bxb3 14. cxb3 Rxc3 $1 { [%cal Gf6e4] The exchange sacrifice followed by Nxe4 gives excellent compensation for Black. White tried to avoid this by means of } 15. Bxf6 { but after } 15... Rxb3 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 $17 { Kasimdzhanov,R (2595) -Kramnik,V (2751) Hoogovens 5' blitz 1999 (10) 0-1 he didn't have enough compensation for the pawn. } ) 13... Qxa5 14. Bd3 { [%csl Gd3][%cal Yf4f5] With the bishop on d3 White renews the idea of f4-f5 and reduces the power of the sacrifice Rxc3. } 14... Rfe8 $1 { [%csl Ge7] Black has other natural moves, but I like very much this prophylactic measure, as with the e7-pawn protected in advance we avoid ideas like Nd5 or Bxf6 followed by Nd5. } 15. f5 Bd7 { [%csl Yb4,Yc5,Ye5][%cal Gd7c6, Gf6d7] ;Thorhallsson,T (2470) -Petursson,M (2550) ISL-chT Iceland 1994 1/2-1/2 it was possible to exchange bishops with Bc4, but the maneuver Bd7-c6 allows Black to put pressure on e4. Black still has a solid position on the kingside and White struggles to make progress. After maneuvering the bishop to c6 it's possible to exploit the weakened squares on White's camp by means of Nd7-e5, Nd7-c5 or Qb4, with a promising game. } ) ( { If } 11. f4 { Black can exploit the fact that the king remains on g1 with } 11... b5 $1 { with a good game. For example: } 12. axb5 axb5 13. Rxa8 Qb6+ $1 14. Kh1 Rxa8 $15 { [%cal Gb5b4] I already prefer Black's position here. } ) 11... Rc8 12. Bf1 { [%cal Gc3d5,Ge1e8,Gg5d8] White plans to continue with Nd5 and get some pressure in the center. Black has an effective way of neutralizing this plan, but it is important to remember the next moves: } 12... Nd7 $1 { [%csl Yb2,Gg7] Delaying the jump of the knight in view of the pressure on b2. } 13. Qd2 Re8 $1 { [%csl Gg7] Besides overprotecting the e7-pawn, this move allows Black to keep the strong dark-squared bishop in the game by preventing Bh6. } 14. Rad1 Na5 { After preventing White's ideas by means of strong prophylactic moves, Black is ready to take the initiative on the queenside. } 15. Nd4 Nc4 $1 16. Nxe6 fxe6 17. Bxc4 Rxc4 18. Qd3 Qc8 $1 { [%csl Ye6][%cal Gc8c1] The queen looks more natural on c7, but from here it keeps an eye on the e6-pawn. } 19. Qh3 Nc5 $17 { [%csl Ra4,Rc3,Re4][%cal Gc8c1] ;Onischuk, V (2612) -Nepomniachtchi,I (2705) Wch Rapid Berlin 2015 (8) 0-1 Black is much better and soon won material. An instructive example of how to handle such positions. } ) 9... Nc6 10. Qd2 { The most logical, keeping White's options flexible. } ( 10. f4 { is the second most played. } 10... Bd7 ( 10... Qb6 $2 { is a good resource for Black in the normal Dragon but in this case the inclusion of a4/ a6 favors White in view of the strong reply } 11. a5 $36 ) 11. Nb3 $1 { A strong and typical prophylactic move, as Black aimed to continue with Nxd4 and Bc6, so White keeps the knights in order to preserve the space advantage. As strange as it may look, here I recommend } 11... Be6 $5 { moving the bishop again. Although it seems that Black has wasted one tempo, the bishop is better placed on e6 and prevents White from cramping the queenside with a4-a5. The analysis shows that despite the loss of one tempo, Black has a playable position: } 12. Bf3 ( { In case of } 12. f5 $2 { Black has the strong response } 12... gxf5 $1 13. exf5 Bxb3 $1 14. cxb3 d5 $17 { [%cal Gd5d4,Gf6d5] with strong play in the center. } ) 12... Nd7 $14 { [%csl Gg7][%cal Gd7b6,Gb6c4] A logical novelty, activating the Bg7 and preparing the typical maneuver Nb6-c4. } 13. Rb1 Nb6 14. Nd4 ( 14. Be2 Nc4 15. Bxc4 Bxc4 16. Rf2 Rc8 17. Nd2 Nb4 $11 { seems fine for Black. } ) 14... Nc4 15. Bf2 ( 15. Nxc6 { leads to massive simplification: } 15... Nxe3 $1 16. Nxd8 Nxd1 17. Nxe6 Nxc3 18. Nxf8 Nxb1 19. Rxb1 Kxf8 20. c3 $11 ) 15... Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Bxd4+ 17. Qxd4 Qb6 $11 { Black is fine in this typical Sicilian endgame. Indeed, the pressure on the c-file and the more flexible structure even offer chances of playing for an advantage. } ) ( 10. Nb3 { direct makes little sense, as after } 10... Be6 11. f4 { we have an improved version of the line seen above, as the bishop went to e6 in one move. In fact, this move order transposes to the classic Sicilian Dragon. } 11... Rc8 12. Kh1 { A natural follow-up after advancing the f-pawn. } ( { In case of } 12. Bf3 { we can play } 12... Nd7 $1 { [%cal Gd7b6,Gb6c4] with the same ideas seen in the previous variation. } ) ( 12. Qd2 { was played against Carlsen, but it led to an easier game for Black after } 12... Na5 13. Nxa5 Qxa5 14. Bf3 Qb4 15. Rfb1 Ng4 $1 16. Bxg4 Bxg4 $17 { Smeets,J (2545) -Carlsen,M (2567) Gausdal Classic 2004 (9) 0-1 with strong initiative on the queenside. } ) ( 12. f5 $2 { again is bad due to } 12... gxf5 $1 13. exf5 Bxb3 $1 14. cxb3 d5 $17 { [%cal Yd5d4, Gf6d5] } ) 12... Na5 { Black equalizes without problems and has a promising play on the queenside. } 13. Nxa5 ( 13. f5 { is still harmless: } 13... Bc4 14. Bd3 Nxb3 15. cxb3 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 Qa5 $11 { Gurevich,V (2469) -Naumann,A (2532) Bundesliga 1819 2018 (11.6) 1/2-1/2 } ) ( { Another option is to bring the knight back to the center: } 13. Nd4 Bc4 14. Bd3 { Now many games continue with } 14... e5 $5 { an interesting idea. After } 15. fxe5 dxe5 16. Nf3 Re8 $11 { the position is balanced. Black has firm control in the center and the Bg7 is not so bad as it may look. In the middlegame, it keeps the kingside safe and supports ideas using the d4-square, and in the endgame, we can activate it via either h6 or f8. } ) 13... Qxa5 14. Bd3 ( 14. Bf3 $6 { is the most played, but after } 14... Nd7 $1 { [%cal Gd7b6,Gb6c4] the bishop looks misplaced on f3 in view of the maneuver Nb6-c4. } 15. Bd2 Qc7 16. Be2 { White played this way in two games to avoid b7-b5, but it seems a sad admission of the previous mistake. } 16... Bc4 $15 { Varas,C (2263) -Diaz Herrero,A (2212) Bilbao op 9th 2016 (4) 1/2-1/2 Black has a good position and can increase the pressure on the queenside with Qc5 followed by b7-b5, or to force a favorable endgame with Bxe2 followed by Qc4. } ) 14... Bc4 { The position is balanced. A possible continuation would be } 15. Qe2 Qb4 16. Rfb1 e6 17. a5 d5 18. Ra4 Bxd3 19. cxd3 Qe7 $11 ) ( 10. Kh1 { is a useful move, but has the drawback of allowing } 10... d5 $5 { a typical advance that seems enough to equalize. } ( { It's also possible to play } 10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Be6 { [%cal Ga8c8] aiming to keep more pieces on the board. } ) 11. Nxd5 ( 11. exd5 Nb4 $1 { is an important detail, after which Black even has an easier game in my opinion. } ) ( { Black also has a good game in case of } 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. e5 Nd7 13. f4 a5 $1 { [%cal Gc8a6,Ye7e6,Gd8e7] with the nice positional idea of exchanging the light-squared bishops. After the exchange, we can play e7-e6 and get a favourable structure. } ) 11... Nxd5 12. exd5 Qxd5 13. Bf3 { This move seemingly secures a superior structure for White. However, after } 13... Qd6 $14 14. Nxc6 bxc6 { Black has enough counterplay thanks to the unpleasant pressure on White's queenside. For example: } 15. c3 ( 15. Qxd6 exd6 16. Bxc6 Rb8 17. Rab1 Bf5 $11 { is at least ok for Black. } ) 15... Rb8 16. Qe2 a5 17. Rfd1 Qc7 $11 { [%csl Yb2,Yc6][%cal Gc8e6,Gc7b7] The weakness on c6 is compensated by the pressure on b2, making the position balanced. } ) 10... Bd7 { Black's most common plan is to mobilize the queenside and prepare the maneuver Na5-c4. } ( { In my 2018 Najdorf Database I recommended } 10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Be6 { as the right path to solve Black's problems. However, now I'm not sure about that assessment. White can keep gaining space with } 12. a5 $1 { [%csl Yb6] } 12... Rc8 { and now Vitiugov showed an interesting new idea: } 13. Ra4 $14 { [%csl Yc4][%cal Gf1a1,Gd4b6,Ga4b4]  ; Vitiugov,N (2726) -Duda,J (2731) Prague Masters 1st 2019 (7.5) 1-0 with the very annoying plan of mobilizing White's rooks on the queenside by using the a-file. Also, with this move, White prevents the bishop's exchange on c4. That worked out very well in the game, which makes me think that maybe Black still has some problems to solve after 10...Nxd4 and 11. ..Be6. } ) 11. Rfd1 ( 11. f3 { is the second most played, keeping White's rooks flexible. } 11... Rc8 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 13. a5 $1 { This is the alternative if White doesn't want to transpose to the main line with Rfd1. However, here we can exploit the fact that the rook is not on d1 yet in our favor : } 13... e6 $1 { [%cal Yd6d5] White is simply unable to avoid the advance d6-d5. } 14. Rfd1 ( 14. Bd4 Qe7 15. Rfd1 d5 16. e5 Nd7 17. Qe3 f6 18. exf6 Bxf6 19. Bxf6 Qxf6 $11 { is also balanced. } ) 14... d5 15. exd5 Nxd5 16. Nxd5 exd5 $1 ( { But not } 16... Bxd5 $2 { due to } 17. c4 $16 { and White starts the advance of the queenside majority. } ) 17. Bd4 { Karthikeyan,M (2623) -Raja,H (2459) MPL Indian Chess Tour N3 rapid 2022 (6) 1-0 Here Black can continue with } 17... Bxd4+ 18. Qxd4 Re8 19. Bf1 Qc7 $11 { [%cal Ge8e6,Gc8e8] with a playable position. White has no way of increasing the pressure on d5, and the open lines secure active play for our pieces. } ) ( 11. Nb3 { was seen in some games. Although White avoids the exchange on d4 and prepares the advance a4-a5, Black can solve his problems with } 11... Na5 12. Nxa5 ( 12. f3 $6 { was played by Nakamura once, but after } 12... Nxb3 13. cxb3 Qa5 $1 { [%cal Gf8c8,Gd7e6] Black can put some pressure on the doubled pawns. } ) 12... Qxa5 13. Rfd1 Rfc8 $1 { A precise reply which avoids any idea connected to Nd5. } 14. Bd4 Be6 { I already prefer Black's position here. We can increase the pressure on the c-file with Rc6-Rfc8, exchange bishops on c4 or create some practical problems for White with Qb4. Perhaps this was the reason that made White change the character of the game with } 15. Bxf6 $5 exf6 $1 ( 15... Bxf6 $2 { would fall into a positional trap: } 16. Nd5 Qxd2 17. Nxf6+ Kg7 18. Nh5+ $1 gxh5 19. Rxd2 $14 { with a slightly better endgame for White. } ) 16. Bd3 f5 $5 { Black could have kept the tension as well, but this is a direct way to equalize. } 17. exf5 Bxc3 18. bxc3 Bxf5 19. Bxf5 Qxf5 $11 { Movsesian,S (2653) -Dominguez Perez,L (2732) China Elite Mind blitz 2016 (4) 1/2-1/2 } ) 11... Rc8 12. Nxc6 { I think this is the most precise move order for White. } ( { The reason is because in the case of } 12. f3 { we can follow the aforementioned plan with } 12... Na5 { when in three games White reacted with } 13. Nd5 ( 13. b3 $4 { is not possible due to } 13... e5 $19 { [%csl Rd4] when the pawn has taken the only available square for the knight. } ) ( 13. Nb3 { is suggested by the engine. Here I like } 13... Re8 $1 { Movsesian,S (2695) -Dominguez Perez,L (2695) Sarajevo Bosnia-A 38th 2008 (5) 1/2-1/2 a nice move that anticipates ideas with Nxa5 followed by Nd5. The threat of Nc4 is still there, and the exchange on a5 only helps Black to continue mobilizing his pieces. } ) 13... Re8 $14 { Once more this prophylactic move is very useful and prepares interesting ideas for Black. } ( 13... Nc4 $2 { reveals White's idea: } 14. Bxc4 Rxc4 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. b3 Rc8 17. c4 $16 { and the structure gives a pleasant space advantage for White. } ) 14. Bf1 { Surprisingly, White doesn't have too many useful moves here. } ( { If } 14. b3 $6 { Black has the nice response } 14... Nxd5 15. exd5 Rc5 $1 { [%csl Rd5] when White is basically forced to sacrifice the d5-pawn, since } 16. c4 $2 { loses on the spot in view of } 16... Bxd4 17. Qxd4 Nxb3 $19 ) 14... Nxd5 15. exd5 { Now we can exploit the position of the rook on e8 by means of } 15... e5 $1 16. dxe6 Bxe6 { [%cal Ge8e1,Gc8c1,Gg7a1] when the isolated pawn is easily compensated by the open lines and activity of Black's pieces. For example: } 17. b3 d5 18. Bf2 Nc6 19. Rac1 ( 19. Nxe6 Rxe6 20. Rab1 Rd6 $11 { is also balanced. } ) 19... Nxd4 20. Bxd4 Bxd4+ 21. Qxd4 Qa5 $11 { with a similar position as in the variation 11.f3. White is unable to increase the pressure on d5, and the active position of Black's heavy pieces makes the position balanced. } ) ( 12. Nb3 $5 { is a subtle idea. Here Black should play } 12... Be6 { just improving the bishop. } ( { The point is that if } 12... Na5 $6 { the difference is that compared to the variation 11.Nb3 White already has the rook on d1, but Black has the wrong rook on c8. Then } 13. Nxa5 Qxa5 14. Nd5 $5 { looks more annoying. } ) 13. a5 $5 { This advance looks good now, but Black has the nice reply } 13... Nd7 $1 { [%csl Ra5] when the threat on a5 is very real. The engine already suggests sacrificing a pawn with } ( 13... Bxb3 14. Bb6 $1 { is an important detail. } ) 14. Nd5 $5 Bxb2 15. Rab1 Bg7 16. c4 $44 { White probably has good compensation for the pawn here, but not more. } ) 12... Bxc6 13. f3 { The structure gives a bit more freedom for White and keeps the enemy pawn breaks in the center and on the queenside under control. On the other hand, Black keeps a solid position and can organize the pieces without problems. An important difference is that with the bishop on c6 White can't develop a pressure on the queenside so easily, compared to the notes of 10... Nxd4. } 13... Nd7 14. a5 { [%csl Ya5,Ya6,Gb6,Yb7] The most natural, restricting the enemy queenside. } ( 14. Bd4 { was played in some games, but now Black has the option of } 14... Qa5 $5 { [%csl Ya5] avoiding the advance of the a-pawn. } 15. Bxg7 ( { Whenever we consider Qa5 in such positions it's important to remember that } 15. Nd5 $2 { is a typical resource for White. Fortunately, in this case, it is simply bad due to } 15... Bxd4+ 16. Qxd4 Bxd5 $19 { [%cal Rc8c2] } ) 15... Kxg7 16. Qd4+ Qe5 { Mohammad,M (2350) -Bu,X (2680) Asia-chT 16th 2010 (1) 1/2-1/2 Now if } 17. Qxe5+ Nxe5 18. a5 g5 $11 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Yf7f5] White managed to advance the pawn to a5, but Black also established a strong outpost for the knight on e5 and soon opened the kingside with nice counterplay. } ) 14... Qc7 15. Bd4 { The bishop's exchange aims to weaken the position of Black's king and prevent any chance of counterplay on the queenside in advance. } ( 15. Ra3 $5 { [%cal Yb2b4] was seen in one game, preparing the advance of the queenside pawns. Here Black found an interesting way of dealing with White's plan: } 15... Be5 $1 16. b4 Nf6 $1 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Ye7e6,Yd6d5] The bishop assumes an active role on e5, pointing for both flanks and preparing Black's counterplay in the center with e6-d5. } 17. Bb6 Qd7 18. Rb3 { Once more, the player with black pieces went for a surprising positional operation: } 18... Bxc3 $5 19. Rxc3 Bb5 $1 { Black gave up his important dark-squared bishop. On the other hand, now he is able to exploit the c-file and some exposed squares on the queenside, while White is still far from creating real threats on the kingside. } 20. Bd4 Bxe2 21. Qxe2 Rxc3 22. Bxc3 Rc8 23. Be1 $6 { Too optimistic. } ( { Perhaps it was already time to look for equality with } 23. Bxf6 exf6 24. Qd3 Rc6 $11 ) 23... Qe6 $15 { [%csl Yc4][%cal Gf6d7,Gd7e5] ;Efimenko,Z (2651) -Kovchan,A (2585) UKR-ch 85th Rivne 2016 (5) 0-1 Black already has the better chances and managed to win a nice game. } ) 15... Bxd4+ 16. Qxd4 Nf6 17. Rd2 { [%cal Gc3d5] Now White's plan is to change the structure by means of Nd5. } 17... Rfd8 18. Nd5 ( 18. Bc4 { was seen in two games. The most direct way of solving Black's problems now is } 18... Bxe4 $5 19. Bxf7+ ( 19. Nxe4 Qxc4 20. Nxf6+ exf6 21. Qxf6 Qc5+ 22. Kh1 Qe5 { is also fine for Black. } ) 19... Kxf7 20. Nxe4 Qc4 $11 { and Black has everything under control. } ) ( 18. Qe3 { Karjakin,S (2753) -Najer,E (2670) Wch Blitz St Petersburg 2018 (2) 1-0 was played by Karjakin. The drawback of this move is that the queen is not attacking f6 anymore, so we can play } 18... e6 $11 { [%csl Yd5] getting d5 under control. Without Nd5, it is very hard to suggest an useful plan for White. } ) 18... Bxd5 19. exd5 Qc5 $5 { Black should force this exchange sooner or later as the white queen is very strong in the center. } 20. c4 { Zhang,X (2361) -Xu,T (2188) CHN-chT Torch Real Estate Cup 2008 (10) 1-0 } ( 20. c3 { keeps the possibility of maneuvering the rook via d4-b4, but Black can take the chance of liberating the position a bit with } 20... e6 $5 21. dxe6 fxe6 $13 { and here we also have some counterplay in the center. } ) 20... Qxd4+ 21. Rxd4 { [%cal Gb2b4] White's plan in this structure is to keep the space advantage and slowly advance the queenside majority. This plan requires careful preparation, but it can be very unpleasant. The best way of avoiding problems for Black is to look for active play first. That can be achieved by opening the queenside before White achieves a solid set-up. } 21... Rc7 22. b4 ( { Postponing the advance of the b-pawn doesn't improve White's chances, as after something like } 22. Ra3 Rb8 23. Re3 b6 24. axb6 Rxb6 25. b3 Kf8 $15 { [%cal Gf6d7,Gd7c5,Gc7c5,Gc5a5] in practice I even prefer Black's position. } ) 22... Rb8 23. Rd2 Nd7 24. Kf2 b6 $1 { The open b-file gives enough counterplay for Black. } 25. axb6 Rxb6 26. Rb2 Rcb7 27. Rab1 Nc5 ( 27... a5 $5 28. b5 Ra7 $11 { [%cal Gb6b8,Gd7b6,Gb8a8] also can be considered. } ) 28. Ke3 Na4 29. Rb3 Nc5 $11 *
