1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. f4 { This is an interesting option for aggressive players who look for a sharp fight against the Najdorf but at the same time aim to avoid the long theoretical discussions of more popular lines like the English Attack or 6.Bg5. It has been used with success in the past by creative attacking players like Smirin and Ivanchuk, so we should not underestimate White's chances. } 6... e5 { Black has other playable options but I like the typical Najdorf reaction, fighting for the center. } 7. Nf3 ( 7. Nf5 $6 { seems more active, but the knight is not stable on f5 and White is not fully developed to play like this. } 7... Nc6 8. Bc4 ( 8. Bd3 $2 { is bad as after } 8... Bxf5 $1 9. exf5 Qb6 { Black has a quick and active development. One game went } 10. Qf3 O-O-O $1 11. Qf2 { Broekmeulen,J (2429) -Zwahr,P (2360) Neckar op-A 18th 2014 (8) 1/2-1/2 Now } 11... Qa5 12. Bd2 d5 $36 { [%cal Yf8b4] would give a dangerous initiative for Black. } ) ( { If } 8. fxe5 $2 Nxe4 $1 { is a very strong reply. } 9. Nxg7+ Bxg7 10. Nxe4 { Broekmeulen,J (2346) -Giri,A (2523) NBSB-chA Roosendaal rapid 2009 (5) 0-1 Now Black could have achieved an advantage by means of } 10... Qh4+ $1 11. Nf2 dxe5 { For example: } 12. g3 Qe7 13. Bg2 O-O 14. O-O f5 $15 { [%csl Ge5,Gf5] and Black has a comfortable game thanks to the central pawns. } ) 8... g6 9. fxe5 ( { In case of } 9. Ng3 { we can play } 9... Bg4 10. Be2 Bxe2 11. Ngxe2 Qb6 $1 { and White still faces some problems of development. } ) 9... Nxe5 10. Ne3 Bg7 11. O-O O-O 12. Bb3 { [%csl Ye4,Ge5,Gg7] We have a typical Najdorf structure: Black gets an isolated pawn on d6, but the knight also has a firm outpost on e5 and the e4-pawn is also potentially weak. I think this is even a slightly improved version for Black, as the bishop is already well placed on g7. } 12... Be6 $1 13. Ned5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 { Monpeurt,C (2175) -Haussernot,C (2198) FRA-ch (Women) 2018 (4) 1-0 Despite the result, Black is totally fine here. The active } 14... Ng4 $40 { [%csl Yg7][%cal Gd8b6,Gd8h4] would give her a dangerous initiative. } ) ( 7. Nb3 $5 { is a playable alternative seen in some recent games, mainly of Fedoseev. Honestly, besides being a less studied option I don't see the advantage of this move. The knight is hardly better on b3 than f3 and the advance f2-f4 is already a slight commitment of White's position. } 7... Nc6 { Black has more than one way of developing here, but I like this move, as the knight doesn't stand in the way of the bishop and we can always consider exf4 to get the outpost on e5. This was played by Giri and is also the first choice of the engine. } 8. Be2 ( { The attempt of restricting Black's position with } 8. f5 $5 { can be met by the typical active response } 8... d5 $1 { Now one game followed a very forced path: } 9. Bg5 Bb4 $5 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Qxd5 Qxd5 12. exd5 Ne7 13. O-O-O Nxf5 14. Ne4 { [%csl Rf6][%cal Ga2a3] White seemingly has some pressure, but Black found a very precise reply now: } 14... Nd6 $1 15. Nxf6+ Ke7 { [%csl Rf6] It turns out that now it's White who needs to find the right moves to not lose material: } 16. a3 $1 Bxa3 17. Nh5 Bb4 18. c3 Bg4 $1 19. Re1 f6 20. Ng3 Rac8 { Shuvalova,P (2504) -Khubukshanov,E (2342) Cheliabinsk Variation-A 2022 (9) 0-1 The rook comes just in time to keep the bishop in the game. The position is dynamically balanced, but I like Black's chances in view of the bishop pair and the passed pawn in the center. } ) ( 8. Bd3 { Daggupati,B (2486) -Brodsky,D (2484) Saint Louis Congress GM 2022 (7) 1-0 was seen in a recent game. Here we can play like in the main line: } 8... exf4 9. Bxf4 Be7 { Now } 10. Qd2 { [%cal Ge1c1] aims a more active development but after something like } 10... O-O 11. O-O-O Ne5 12. Kb1 b5 13. a3 Bg4 14. Rde1 Rb8 $13 { [%cal Ge5c4,Yb5b4] Black's chances don't look worse to me. } ) 8... Be7 9. f5 { White is better prepared for this advance now. } ( 9. O-O O-O 10. Kh1 { is a more common continuation, which transposes to 6.Be2. } ) 9... b5 $1 { [%csl Ye4][%cal Gc8b7] Now Black can develop pressure on e4. } 10. Bg5 { Khanin,S (2521) -Chigaev,M (2639) Speed Chess GP1 blitz 2021 (5) 0-1 Black has a nice position and can continue in natural way: } 10... O-O 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Nd5 Bb7 13. O-O { and here } 13... Ne7 $1 { is a nice idea to remove the blockade on d5. In case of } 14. Nxf6+ gxf6 $11 { [%cal Yd6d5] The doubled pawns on the kingside are not a problem, and Black is about to free the position with d6-d5. } ) 7... Nbd7 8. a4 { In first place White prevents the advance b7-b5. } ( { In case of a careless development like } 8. Bd3 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Kh1 b5 $1 { [%cal Gc8b7] Black achieves an active set-up, which is usually good enough to solve the opening problems. } 11. a3 ( { In one game White tried to ignore the threat of b5-b4 with } 11. Qe1 { but after } 11... Bb7 12. fxe5 dxe5 13. Bg5 Nc5 $15 { [%csl Rd3,Re4][%cal Yb5b4,Gd8c7] ;Cigan,S (2370) -Ftacnik,L (2580) AUT-chT2S 9596 1995 0-1 Black has an easier game. } ) ( 11. a4 $5 { is a typical reaction to the advance of the b-pawn, but is harmless here. } 11... b4 12. Ne2 { Ponkratov,P (2603) -Kokarev,D (2612) Voronezh op-A 14th 2010 (6) 0-1 } 12... Nc5 13. Ng3 Qc7 { [%cal Gf8e8,Gc8b7] Black also has a good position here, for example: } 14. Be3 Re8 15. fxe5 dxe5 16. Qe2 g6 $11 { [%csl Yf5] } ) 11... Bb7 12. Qe1 Re8 $1 { [%cal Ge8e1] The rook is always well placed on e8 in this line, as the threat of exf4, opening the e-file, forces White to release the tension in the center. } 13. fxe5 ( 13. Bd2 exf4 14. Bxf4 Bf8 $15 { [%csl Re4][%cal Yd6d5,Gd7c5] is better for Black. } ) 13... dxe5 14. Bg5 ( 14. Qg3 { was tried in some games, but it is not really dangerous as Black has enough resources to keep the kingside safe. } 14... Rc8 15. Bh6 $2 { This is actually a serious mistake. } 15... Nh5 16. Qh3 { This position has occurred in two games. In both cases, Black missed a brilliant idea now: } 16... Rc6 $3 17. Be3 Nf4 $1 18. Bxf4 exf4 $19 { [%cal Gc6h6,Gd7f6,Ge7d6] It turns out that it is Black who launches a crushing attack on the kingside here. } ) 14... h6 15. Be3 { [%cal Gf3h4,Gh4f5] White plans to maneuver the knight via h4-f5 in order to threaten a dangerous sacrifice on h6. Black can avoid this idea by means of } 15... Bf8 $14 16. Nh4 g6 { with a good game. We always have resources to keep the kingside safe, for example: } 17. Rd1 Rc8 18. Nf3 Qe7 19. Qh4 Nh5 $5 20. Qxe7 ( 20. Qe1 $2 Nc5 $17 { is already better for Black. } ) 20... Rxe7 $15 { [%cal Gh5f4,Gh5f6] I prefer Black's chances in the endgame. } ) ( { I had to face this variation in my first official game with the Najdorf. My opponent tried a different plan with } 8. Qe2 Be7 9. Be3 { [%cal Ge1c1] which seems an ambitious plan at first sight, but it is not clear how White is going to develop the attack on the kingside. } 9... O-O ( { Maybe it would be a bit more precise to keep the king in the center for a while and play } 9... b5 10. O-O-O Qc7 { [%cal Ga8c8,Gc8b7] with a quick mobilization on the queenside. } ) 10. O-O-O Qa5 11. Kb1 b5 12. g4 $2 { This is a thematic sacrifice to open the g-file, but it backfires simply because Black is not forced to take the pawn. Instead, I replied } 12... b4 $1 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. exd5 $2 ( 14. Rxd5 { was better, but after } 14... Qc7 { [%cal Gd7f6] } 15. fxe5 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 dxe5 $17 { [%cal Gc8e6,Gf8c8] Black's prospects look excellent. } ) 14... Nf6 $1 { [%csl Rd5,Rg4][%cal Gf6g4,Gf6d5] The initiative is already with Black. My opponent tried to complicate matters by means of } 15. fxe5 Nxd5 16. Nd4 $2 { but I found the strong blow } 16... Bxg4 $19 { [%cal Gd5e3] ;Rodrigues,E (2241) -Quintiliano Pinto,R (2355) BRA-ch sf1 80th 2013 (6) 0-1 winning material, and soon scored my first win in the Najdorf. } ) ( 8. Bc4 $6 b5 { also leads to a good position for Black. } 9. Bb3 ( { In case of } 9. Bd5 { we should not hurry on taking the bishop. } 9... Rb8 { is more precise, and if } 10. Ng5 { now } 10... Nxd5 11. Qxd5 Qe7 { as in the next moves Black is able to drive back the enemy pieces. One game went } 12. O-O h6 13. Nf3 b4 $1 14. Ne2 Nf6 15. Qd3 Qc7 $15 { [%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] ;Popov,I (2539) -Edouard,R (2472) Wch U18 Kemer 2007 (9) 1/2-1/2 and Black had an advantage. } ) 9... Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Kh1 Bb7 { [%cal Yb5b4,Gd7c5] I like Black's position here. The threat of b5-b4 seems very unpleasant, and Black can improve the pressure on e4 with Nc5. The Bb3 also doesn't look useful, despite having an open diagonal. The following variation is very logical: } 12. fxe5 dxe5 13. Qe2 Nc5 14. Bg5 ( 14. Rd1 Qc7 15. Nd5 $2 { is even worse, as after } 15... Nxd5 16. Bxd5 Rad8 $17 { White has problems to keep the center under control. } ) 14... Nfxe4 15. Nxe4 Nxe4 16. Rad1 Qc7 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 { White can regain the pawn now with } 18. Bd5 { but after } 18... Nf6 19. Bxb7 Qxb7 20. Qxe5 Rfe8 $15 { Black has more active pieces and is the safer king in the long run, with better practical chances. } ) 8... Be7 9. Bd3 { This is the main line. } ( { However, } 9. Bc4 $5 { is an interesting and tricky alternative. Here I suggest } 9... Qa5 $5 { as the queen can be useful on a5 sometimes. } 10. Qe2 ( 10. O-O $4 Qc5+ $19 { is the tactical point. } ) ( 10. Bd2 { looks natural, but now Black exploits the bishop move with } 10... exf4 { that seems enough to equalize. } 11. Qe2 Ne5 12. Nd5 Qd8 { Now White played in a careless way: } 13. Nxe7 $2 Qxe7 14. Bxf4 { and after } 14... Nxc4 15. Qxc4 d5 $17 { Fernandez Cardoso,A (2473) -Corrales Jimenez,F (2578) Carlos Torre Memorial op 23rd 2011 (6) 0-1 Black wins a pawn. } ) 10... O-O 11. O-O exf4 $1 { It's better to follow the same path as in the main line. } ( { In my 2018 Najdorf database I recommended } 11... b5 $6 { and after the active reply } 12. Nd5 $1 { to continue with } 12... bxc4 ( { But not } 12... Nxd5 13. Bxd5 Bb7 $2 { as White has the powerful idea } 14. Bxb7 Qb6+ 15. Nd4 $3 Qxb7 16. Nf5 $40 { [%cal Ga1a3,Ga3g3] with a strong attack coming on the kingside. } ) 13. Nxe7+ Kh8 { The problem is that it's possible to improve White's play now with } 14. Nf5 $1 ( { I've only analysed } 14. Qxc4 Qb6+ 15. Kh1 a5 $44 { [%cal Gc8a6] when Black gets enough compensation for the pawn. } ) 14... Bb7 15. Ng5 h6 16. Ra3 $18 { [%cal Ga3h3] White's attack is already decisive. } ) 12. Bxf4 Ne5 { [%csl Gc4] The difference compared to the main line is that White managed to develop the light-squared bishop more actively, keeping pressure on the kingside. Nevertheless, Black can continue the development with either Be6 or Bg4, with good chances of equalizing. } 13. Bb3 Be6 { Exchanging bishops is the best way of neutralizing the pressure on f7. At first sight, it might look a bit risky, but the analysis shows that Black has enough resources to keep the position under control. } 14. Nd4 ( 14. Bxe6 fxe6 15. Ng5 { [%csl Re6] looks dangerous, but Black has } 15... Qc5+ $1 16. Kh1 Qc8 { [%cal Yh7h6,Gf6d7] threatening to consolidate with h6 followed by Nfd7. White has nothing better than } 17. Bxe5 dxe5 { but the doubled pawns are not really weak. Actually, they control a lot of important squares in the center and create strong points for Black's pieces. For example: } 18. Nf3 Qc7 19. Rad1 Rac8 20. Rd3 Qa5 21. Rfd1 Rc6 $17 { [%cal Gf8c8,Ge7b4] and Black is already better. } ) ( 14. Kh1 $5 { was played against me in a recent game. I had missed this move in my earlier preparations somehow, but it makes a lot of sense, as in many lines we can use the check to improve the queen with time. } 14... Ng6 { After some thought I concluded that I needed to prepare the advance d6-d5. } 15. Be3 { Martins,C (2219) -Quintiliano Pinto,R (2509) Caioba op 7th 2023 (3) 0-1 } ( { In case of } 15. Bd2 { Black can't advance the d-pawn, but it is possible to play } 15... Bxb3 16. cxb3 Qh5 $5 { with a decent position. For example: } 17. Rad1 Rfe8 18. Bg5 Rad8 19. h3 h6 20. Bxf6 Bxf6 21. Nd5 Be5 $11 ) 15... Bxb3 { In my game I advanced the d-pawn immediately, but careful analysis showed that it was a mistake. Instead, a previous game went } 16. cxb3 d5 $5 { which seems more precise. The game followed in a very concrete way: } 17. e5 Ne4 18. Bd4 Nxc3 19. bxc3 Nf4 20. Qe3 Ne6 21. Bb6 Bc5 $1 22. Bxa5 Bxe3 23. Rad1 b6 24. Bb4 Rfd8 25. Bd6 Rac8 $11 { Schwabeneder,F (2377) -Seyb,A (2420) AUT-chT 1516 2015 (1.2) 1/ 2-1/2 with an equal endgame. } ) 14... Qb6 $14 ( 14... Bxb3 $6 15. cxb3 $36 { [%cal Gd4f5] leaves Black under pressure on the kingside. } ) 15. Qd2 ( { If } 15. Be3 { Black has the nice reply } 15... Nfg4 $1 { when the position seems a bit confused, but is balanced. For example: } 16. Nxe6 Nxe3 17. Nxf8 Nxf1+ 18. Kxf1 Rxf8 19. Nd5 Qd8 $11 ) ( 15. a5 $5 Qxd4+ 16. Be3 { seems a clever trap, but again we have a nice resource: } 16... Bc4 $1 17. Qe1 Nd3 $1 { and Black is ok. } 18. Qe2 Ne5 19. Bxd4 Bxe2 20. Nxe2 Nc6 21. Rf4 Nd7 $11 { [%cal Ge7f6] with a balanced game. } ) 15... Bc4 $1 { An important detail. } ( { If Black immediately goes for } 15... Bxb3 16. cxb3 Nc6 17. Be3 Nxd4 18. Bxd4 Qxb3 { White has the strong idea } 19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. Rxf6 $1 gxf6 21. Nd5 $40 { [%csl Rg8][%cal Ga1a3,Gd5f6,Gd2h6] with promising attacking chances. } ) 16. Rfe1 Bxb3 17. cxb3 Nc6 $1 { This idea works nicely now as the rook is not on the f-file. } 18. Be3 Nxd4 19. Bxd4 Qxb3 20. Re3 Qe6 { White has enough compensation for the pawn, but not more than that. For example: } 21. Rg3 ( { Or } 21. Rf1 Ng4 22. Rg3 Ne5 23. Nd5 Bh4 24. Rh3 Bd8 $11 ) 21... Nh5 22. Rh3 Nf6 23. Rg3 $11 ( { I should note that } 23. Qg5 $2 { allows a brilliant resource: } 23... h6 $1 24. Rxh6 $2 Ne8 $19 { [%csl Rg5,Rh6] and Black wins! } ) ) 9... O-O 10. O-O exf4 $1 { An important move to remember. The releasing of the tension in the center gives a free game for Black's pieces, and it's possible to use the open e-file to put pressure on e4. The arising structure is very typical and resembles some lines of 6.Be2 in which White plays f2-f4. Although White also gets some open lines and active prospects for the pieces, the advance of the f-pawn makes the white king more vulnerable. The d6-pawn is not a serious weakness here, as Black has enough pieces to keep it safe. Finally, after exf4 we get a nice outpost for the knight on e5, although in this particular position it usually goes to c5 in order to increase the pressure on e4. } 11. Kh1 { The most solid, preparing the recapture on f4. } ( 11. Bxf4 { direct allows } 11... Qb6+ $5 { grabbing a pawn, although White probably achieves enough compensation for it. } ( 11... Nc5 { [%cal Gc8e6,Gc8g4] also can be considered, like in the main line. } ) 12. Kh1 Qxb2 13. Qe1 { [%cal Ge1g3,Ge1h4,Gc3d5] White prepares ideas with Nd5 and the queen is ready to take an active role on the kingside via either g3 or h4. } ( 13. Qd2 { doesn't pose serious problems for Black. } 13... Qb6 14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. exd5 Nc5 16. Rae1 Qd8 17. h3 Bd7 18. a5 { Adams,M (2640) -Van Wely,L (2560) Garmisch Partenkirchen rapid 1994 (12) 1-0 A natural continuation now would be } 18... Re8 { with a good game for Black. For example: } 19. Nd4 Nxd3 20. cxd3 Bf6 $17 ) ( 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. exd5 Nc5 $1 { [%cal Gc5d3] Getting rid of the light-squared bishop is an important measure to reduce the attacking potential of White's position. White probably should force a draw with Rb1-Ra1 now, as after } 15. Qe2 Nxd3 16. Qxd3 Qb4 $1 { Leko,P (2605) -Gelfand,B (2685) Belgrade Investbank 1995 (10) 0-1 Black brings the queen back and has nice prospects of consolidating the position. } ) 13... Qb6 14. Nd5 ( 14. Bg5 { was harmless for Black: } 14... Nc5 15. Qh4 Nxd3 16. cxd3 Qa5 $5 17. Ne2 h6 18. Bd2 Qd8 19. Qe1 Bd7 $11 { Navara,D (2656) -Maksimenko,A (2505) Bundesliga 0708 2007 (11.1) 1/2-1/2 Black has a solid position and remains a pawn up. } ) 14... Nxd5 15. exd5 Qd8 16. c4 { The most played, vacating c2 in order to keep the bishop in an active diagonal. } ( 16. Qg3 Nc5 $1 { avoids any problem for Black. } 17. Rae1 Nxd3 18. cxd3 Bf5 $17 { De Firmian,N (2580) -Van Wely,L (2570) Akureyri 1994 1/2-1/2 } ) ( { I've faced } 16. Qe4 { in one game, but here we can use the knight to disturb White's position a little bit: } 16... Nf6 17. Qd4 Nh5 $1 18. Bd2 Bf6 19. Qe4 g6 20. Rab1 { Cadilhac,I (2260) -Quintiliano Pinto,R (2435) Barueri op 3rd 2019 (4) 1/2-1/2 with a balanced game. } ) 16... Nc5 17. Bc2 Bg4 { Black managed to develop the pieces to good squares and has good chances of consolidating the position. } 18. Qg3 ( 18. Ra3 $5 { Sax,G (2535) -Votava,J (2395) Lazne Bohdanec 1995 (5) 1/2-1/2 is a creative idea seen in one game. } 18... Bh5 $1 { [%cal Gh5g6] Instead of exchanging on f3, that would help White to double rooks on the f-file, it makes more sense to get rid of the Bc2. For example: } 19. Qg3 Bg6 20. Bxg6 fxg6 $1 { [%cal Gf8f7,Gd8d7,Ga8f8] and Black keeps mobilizing the pieces, with a good game. } ) 18... Bh5 $1 { [%cal Gh5g6] For some reason this move was only seen in one game, but it seems the most effective way of avoiding any initiative by White on the kingside. } 19. Rae1 ( { The tactical idea } 19. Bxh7+ $2 Kxh7 20. Qh3 g6 21. g4 { fails in view of } 21... Qd7 $19 ) 19... Bg6 $1 20. Bxg6 fxg6 $1 { The correct recapture, activating the rook and keeping the kingside closed. } 21. Bg5 $2 { White overlooked a simple tactical detail. } ( 21. Rxe7 Qxe7 22. Bxd6 { would be better, although after } 22... Qe2 $1 23. Re1 Qxc4 24. Bxf8 Rxf8 $15 { Black still has an advantage. } ) 21... Rxf3 $1 22. Qxf3 Bxg5 $19 { Panchanathan,M (2436) -Saravanan,V (2393) IND-ch 39th Nagpur 2002 (11) 0-1 } ) 11... Nc5 12. Bxf4 Bg4 { [%cal Gg4h5,Gh5g6] Black develops in a natural and active way. The maneuver Bg4-h5-g6 is a thematic idea in this line, as it reinforces the kingside and keeps the pressure on e4. } 13. Qd2 { The main continuation, preparing to complete the centralization of White's forces with Rae1 and unpinning the knight to consider Nd4-f5 at some point. } ( 13. Qe1 { also can be considered. Here I like } 13... Rc8 $1 { an important prophylactic move, placing the rook on an useful file and preventing the activation of White's light-squared bishop. } 14. Nd4 ( 14. Bc4 $2 Ncxe4 $1 { [%cal Gc8c4] is the tactical detail. } ) ( { Black had no problems after } 14. Qg3 Bh5 15. Be3 Bg6 16. Bd4 Re8 17. Rae1 { Sherzer,A (2465) -Wolff,P (2590) New York op 1994 (8) 0-1 Now he could have started a nice regrouping by means of } 17... Ne6 $1 18. Bg1 Nh5 $1 { [%cal Gh5f4] with a good position. } ) 14... Qb6 $1 { [%csl Rd4][%cal Gc5d3,Gb6b2]  Suddenly White faces many direct threats. } 15. Be2 Bxe2 16. Qxe2 Rfe8 { [%csl Ye4][%cal Ge8e1] } 17. Nf5 { Here Anand decided to go into the complications with } 17... Qxb2 $1 { Polgar,J (2630) -Anand,V (2720) Buenos Aires Sicilian 1994 (6) 0-1 and ended up winning a brilliant game.The position is objectively equal, but it is White who needs to find the precise moves. Judit failed to see the correct path, which was } ( 17... Bf8 $5 { was a safer option. } ) 18. Qf3 Nb3 19. Qg3 $1 Bf8 20. Nh6+ Kh8 21. Nxf7+ Kg8 22. Nh6+ $11 ) ( 13. Be3 Rc8 14. a5 $6 { was played against me once but seems a bit dubious, as the a5-pawn requires constant attention by White. } 14... Bh5 15. Qe1 Re8 $1 { [%csl Gc8, Ge8][%cal Ge8e1,Gc8c1] It's important to remember of developing both rooks actively. } 16. Qg3 Bg6 17. Bd4 Nh5 ( 17... d5 $36 { was even stronger. } ) 18. Qf2 Bf6 $5 { Black has a good game, and after } 19. Nd2 Bxd4 20. Qxd4 Nf6 { [%csl Ye4][%cal Gf6g4,Gg4e5] ;Cubas,J (2474) -Quintiliano Pinto,R (2378) American Continental 10th 2014 (8) 1-0 I even had the better chances, despite the final result. } ) 13... Rc8 14. Be3 { Now White prepares either the maneuver Be3-d4 or Nd4-f5 without allowing exchanges with Ne6. } ( 14. Nd4 { [%cal Yh2h3, Gd4f5] is also an option, and works better now as Qb6 is not so good as after 13.Qe1. However, Black can face this plan with the energetic reply } 14... d5 $1 { taking the initiative first. } 15. e5 ( { If } 15. exd5 Nxd3 16. Qxd3 Nxd5 { [%csl Ge7,Gg4] I like Black's chances. } ) 15... Nfe4 $1 16. Bxe4 ( 16. Nxe4 $6 { is imprecise as after } 16... dxe4 $1 17. Bc4 Nd3 $36 { Lanc,A (2322) -Aczel,G (2548) SVK-chT1W 1617 2016 (3.1) 0-1 White is under pressure. } ) 16... Nxe4 17. Nxe4 dxe4 { [%csl Ge4] An interesting detail in this position is that the e4-pawn is not so White as it may look, and in many lines Black keeps it defended by means of tactical resources. } 18. Rae1 ( { If } 18. Rfe1 f5 $1 19. exf6 Bxf6 { Black's position is becoming very active. White has nothing better than } 20. Rxe4 Qd5 21. Rae1 { but now we can exploit the bad placement of White's forces by means of } 21... Bh4 $1 22. g3 Bf6 { [%cal Gf6d4,Gg4f3] and White has to deal with unpleasant threats. The following variation is a nice illustration of the dangers of White's position: } 23. Kg1 Rce8 $1 24. Rxe8 Bxd4+ 25. R8e3 g5 $1 26. Bxg5 $2 Bh3 $3 27. Bf4 Rxf4 $1 28. gxf4 Bxe3+ $19 ) ( 18. h3 { Mazur,S (2362) -Cerveny,M (2380) Prievidza 2009 (3) 1-0 was tried in one game. The simplest way of improving Black's play now is } 18... Bc5 $1 19. Be3 Bh5 20. Nf5 Bxe3 21. Qxe3 Rxc2 22. Qxe4 Rxb2 { [%cal Gh5g6] with a more or less balanced position. } ) 18... Bh5 $1 { [%cal Gh5g6] A nice maneuver, which basically forces White to take the e4-pawn. } 19. Rxe4 ( 19. Nf5 Bg6 20. Nd6 e3 $1 { [%cal Gc8c2] seems fine for Black. } ) 19... Bg6 20. Re2 ( { Or } 20. Ree1 Bxc2 $1 21. Nxc2 Qxd2 22. Bxd2 Rxc2 $11 ) 20... Bc5 21. Nf3 ( { In case of } 21. c3 { Black regains the pawn with a small advantage after } 21... Bxd4 22. cxd4 Rc2 23. Qe3 Rxe2 24. Qxe2 Qxd4 $15 ) 21... Ba7 $44 { [%cal Gg6b1,Ga7g1] Black has the bishop pair and active pieces, which provide very good compensation for the pawn. For example: } 22. Qc1 ( 22. Rc1 $2 Qxd2 23. Rxd2 Rc4 $17 { [%cal Gc4a4,Gc4f4] } ) ( 22. c3 $2 Bd3 $19 { [%csl Re2,Rf1] } ) 22... Qa5 $1 { Black is already regaining the pawn by force. } 23. Rfe1 ( 23. b3 $2 Bd3 $19 { is the threat. } ) 23... Qxa4 24. c3 Rfe8 $15 { I prefer Black's chances here in view of the bishop pair and the more exposed position of White's king. } ) 14... Nxd3 { The simplest path to equalize. } ( { In another game I played the natural } 14... Bh5 $6 { but after } 15. Nd4 Bg6 16. Nf5 Re8 17. Rae1 $14 { [%cal Ge3d4] ;Cubas,J (2469) -Quintiliano Pinto,R (2484) Brasilia Terraviva op 2017 (6) 1/2-1/2 White has a more comfortable game. } ) 15. Qxd3 ( 15. cxd3 { seems the most natural reaction, reinforcing the center. However, after } 15... d5 $1 { Black is already playing for an advantage: } 16. e5 Bxf3 $1 17. exf6 ( 17. Bd4 $2 { seems a good intermediate, but Black has a even stronger reply: } 17... Ne4 $1 18. dxe4 Bxe4 19. Nxe4 dxe4 20. Qe3 { Warakomski,T (2490) -Nyzhnyk,I (2637) EU-ch rapid Warsaw 2012 (8) 1/2-1/2 Now } 20... Rc4 $19 { [%csl Ra4,Rd4][%cal Gd8d5,Gd5c6] would have given a decisive advantage for Black. } ) 17... Bxf6 18. Rxf3 d4 { Black regains the piece with a superior structure. } 19. Ne4 dxe3 20. Nxf6+ Qxf6 $1 21. Rxe3 { Van der Weide,K (2454) -Shneider,A (2501) Cappelle op 18th 2002 (4) 1/ 2-1/2 After something natural like } 21... h6 $15 { Black keeps good practical chances in the endgame in view of his superior structure and the exposed nature of White's king. } ) 15... Be6 { [%csl Yc4,Ge6,Ge7] Black has the bishop pair and a very solid position. } 16. Nd5 $5 { Trying to force a favourable change in the pawn structure. } ( 16. Rfd1 { is more flexible, but doesn't improve White's position. We can continue with an useful move like } 16... Re8 $14 { and Black has a good position. For example: } 17. a5 ( { But not } 17. Bf4 $2 Ng4 $17 { [%cal Gd8b6] } ) 17... Qc7 $11 { [%cal Gc7c4, Gf6d7,Gd7e5,Gd7c5] with ideas like Qc4, forcing a comfortable endgame, or Nd7-e5/Nd7-c5, playing for the initiative. In any case, Black's chances are not worse. } ) 16... Bxd5 $1 { Keeping the bishop pair was also an option, but the knight can be very useful in such structures. } 17. exd5 { Agora as pretas forçaram um final confortável por meio de } 17... Qc7 18. c3 Qc4 $1 { [%csl Gd3,Gd5] White is unable to avoid the queen's exchange. } 19. Rfd1 Rfe8 $11 { Dominguez Perez,L (2479) -Sadvakasov,D (2487) Guillermo Garcia Memorial-A 07th 1999 (4) 1/ 2-1/2 The position is objectively equal but in practice Black has a small pressure, typical of Sicilian endgames. } *
