1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. h4 { The first time I saw this move in a tournament game I thought "So, no they are just trying any move against the Najdorf?" Well, the answer is: yes, nowadays everything is possible with a strong engine and good preparation. White players keep trying to find ideas in the most popular variations, but the fight was also extended to less - or not at all! - exploited lines. That surely makes the life of Najdorf players more difficult, as we need to keep updated and prepared to face literally any 6th move by White. Fortunately, in our favour we have the fact that the Najdorf is the best Sicilian. But talking from an objective point of view, the advance of the h-pawn is totally playable and leads to interesting positions. } 6... e5 { Let's face the flank attack with action in the center, in the best Najdorf style. } ( 6... e6 { now is not good in view of } 7. g4 $1 { transposing to the Keres Attack. } ) ( 6... Nc6 $5 { is a playable alternative. } ) 7. Nb3 ( 7. Nf5 $5 { doesn't work well like in the 6.a3 line, but is an interesting practical try. } 7... d5 $1 { The typical reaction. } 8. Qf3 ( 8. Bg5 $2 { is the right continuation in the 6.a3 line, but here is a mistake: } 8... d4 9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. Nb1 Bxf5 11. exf5 Qd5 12. Qd3 Nc6 $17 { [%cal Gc6b4,Ye5e4] and White has many problems to deal with. } ) 8... d4 9. Nd5 Nxd5 10. exd5 Bxf5 $1 { Black solves his problems very easily with this exchange. } 11. Qxf5 Nd7 12. c3 { Preventing annoying checks on b4/a5 and trying to open the game for the bishops. I like how Black played in the following game: } 12... g6 ( 12... Rc8 $5 { is Giri's recommendation, but I think White can keep the tension with } 13. Bd3 { and Black has to play g7-g6 sooner or later anyway. } ) 13. Qh3 dxc3 14. bxc3 h5 $1 { It's important to prevent the advance h4-h5, after which White would have strong pressure on the h-file. } 15. Be2 { Durarbayli,V (2522) -Sarana,A (2689) Lindores Abbey Blitz Tal Memorial 2021 (15.18) 0-1 } 15... Bd6 { Black has a solid position and nice play on the dark squares. A common plan in this structure is to make use of the kingside majority. A possible continuation would be } 16. Rb1 Qc7 17. O-O f5 18. c4 Nc5 19. Qg3 Kf7 $11 { with a double-edged game and chances for both sides. } ) 7... Be7 { Giri's recommendation. } ( { In my 2018 Najdorf databases I gave } 7... Be6 { when the most critical variation was } 8. f4 b5 $5 9. f5 Bc8 { [%csl Ge4][%cal Yc8b7] } 10. g4 $1 Bb7 11. Bg2 b4 12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. exd5 a5 { and analyzed some variations that seemingly could give good counterplay for Black. Nevertheless, this position has been tested in tournament practice a few times since then. In two recent games White played } 14. Be3 $1 { a strong developing move that takes b6 away from the queen, an important source of counterplay in many lines. Next White can start a nice regrouping with Nd2-e4, consolidating a pleasant space advantage. I tried to insist a bit in this position but honestly couldn't find a satisfactory way of solving Black's problems, so let's stick to Giri's move. } ) 8. Bg5 { White has two ways of giving a sense to the h4-pawn. This is the positional approach and the most played. The position resembles the variation 6.Be2 e5 7.Nb3 Be7 8.Bg5, with the difference that White played h2-h4 instead of Be2. } ( 8. Be2 { has the goal of keeping advancing on the kingside with g2-g4. } 8... Be6 9. f4 { White waits for Be6 to make this move. Here we are going to follow Giri's recommendation as well, who suggests to look for a complicated game with } ( 9. g4 { is answered by } 9... d5 $1 { which solves Black's opening problems easily. } 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Bxd5 12. Rh3 Nc6 { Black is fine, as } 13. Rd3 $2 { can be met by } 13... Nb4 14. Rd2 $2 Bxh4 $19 { [%cal Gd8f6, Gd8b6] and White is in serious trouble. } ) 9... b5 $5 10. g4 $1 { The best option to keep increasing the tension on the kingside. } ( 10. fxe5 dxe5 11. Qxd8+ Bxd8 { is a balanced endgame, but looks fine for Black. } 12. Bf3 $6 ( 12. Nc5 { is better, when Black can reply } 12... Nc6 $13 { [%csl Yd4][%cal Gd8a5,Gc6d4, Gd8b6] ignoring the exchange on e6 and looking for active play. } ) 12... Nbd7 13. Bd2 Rc8 14. O-O-O { Martinez Alcantara,J (2598) -So,W (2772) Chess.com Rapid Wk1 Swiss 2022 (9) 1/2-1/2 Now } 14... b4 $1 { would give a clear advantage for Black. For example: } 15. Nd5 a5 16. Nxf6+ Nxf6 17. Kb1 Bb6 $17 { The difference of activity between both sides minor pieces is evident. The simplest plan now is to continue with 0-0 followed by doubling rooks on the c-file, when the pressure on the queenside seems very unpleasant for White. } ) ( { In case of } 10. f5 Bd7 { [%csl Re4][%cal Yb5b4] White has no time to continue with g4-g5. } 11. g4 b4 $1 { White is about to lose control as there is no way of defending both e4 and h4. The lesser evil seems to be } 12. g5 { but after } 12... bxc3 13. gxf6 Bxf6 14. Qxd6 Bc6 $1 15. Qxd8+ Bxd8 { Black has an active game. For example: } 16. Bd3 g6 $36 { with initiative. } ) 10... b4 $1 { We have no option but to strike before White's pawn storm on the kingside becomes really dangerous. } 11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 { Now we have to choose whether we enter the complications of grabbing the h4-pawn or not. I suggest } 12... Bc8 { which is the most played by now and seems relatively safer. } ( { Giri also examines } 12... Bxh4+ $5 { I must say that this move seems totally playable and a nice practical try, but requires careful analysis. } ) 13. g5 O-O { The arising position is complex and offers chances for both sides. } 14. Be3 ( 14. a3 $5 { was seen in a recent game and looks interesting. } 14... bxa3 15. Rxa3 a5 16. O-O { Moranda,W (2622) -Huschenbeth,N (2608) POL-chT Ekstraliga 2021 (3.5) 1/2-1/2 Black can continue developing normally with } 16... Nd7 { [%cal Ya5a4,Yf7f6,Ye5f4] considering ideas like a5-a4, f7-f6 or exf4, playing in both flanks. } 17. f5 { looks dangerous, but always can be met by } 17... f6 $1 { when White has to be very concrete to justify the advances on the kingside. The best line according to the engine is } 18. g6 hxg6 19. Bd3 $1 { but Black has enough resources to keep the control on the kingside. For example: } 19... Qe8 { [%cal Yg6g5] } 20. fxg6 f5 $1 21. Rxf5 Qxg6+ 22. Rg5 $1 Qf7 23. Rg2 e4 $1 24. Bxe4 Ne5 $13 { [%cal Gc8g4,Ge7h4] with a complex game, but Black is active and has nice counterplay. The engine keeps saying it's 0.00, but anything is possible in such a tense position. } ) ( 14. Qd3 $6 { [%cal Yf4f5] was tried in one game. I assume the idea is to play f4-f5, but the queen is exposed on d3 and allows Black to take the initiative first: } 14... a5 $1 15. a4 { Priyanka,K (2202) -Ibadov,D (2288) Paracin Winter IM 2022 (5) 1-0 Black had a strong continuation now: } 15... bxa3 16. Rxa3 a4 $1 { Threatening to win a piece with Ba6. The best reply is } 17. Nd2 { but after } 17... exf4 18. Nc4 Nd7 19. Bxf4 Ba6 $36 { [%cal Ga8c8] The initiative is with Black. } ) 14... a5 $1 { Black can postpone the development and keep advancing on the queenside. } 15. Bd3 ( 15. a4 $5 bxa3 16. Rxa3 { Priyanka,K (2202) -Stankovic,M (2201) Paracin Orbis IM 01 2022 (4) 1/ 2-1/2 is an interesting idea, but now it's not clear where White is going to hide the king. Here Black could have played } 16... a4 { [%csl Ye5][%cal Gc8f5,Gb8d7, Ye5f4,Gd7e5] followed by a normal development with Bf5-Nd7 as suggested by Giri. Although the engine evaluates the position as equal I think in practice it can be harder for White, since the lack of a safe place for the king might become a serious problem sometimes. A possible continuation would be } 17. O-O Nd7 18. c4 ( 18. f5 { is always answered by } 18... f6 $1 ) 18... exf4 19. Bxf4 Ne5 20. Nd4 Qb6 21. Qd2 Bd7 $11 { [%cal Ga8b8,Yf7f6] Black's position seems fine. It's possible to exploit White's weaknesses on both sides by means of either Rab8 to attack b2 or f7-f6 trying to open lines on the kingside. } ) 15... f5 $1 { A typical defensive resource in such positions, as if White doesn't take the chance of opening the kingside now, later it won't be possible to force a breakthrough by normal means. Giri ends up his analysis here by evaluating the position as double-edged. Nevertheless, we can go a bit further: } 16. gxf6 { Without this exchange I don't see how White can make progress on the kingside later. } ( { For example: } 16. a4 bxa3 17. Rxa3 a4 18. O-O Bb7 { [%csl Rb3,Rd5] The knight already has to go to an unfavorable square. } 19. Nc1 { The d5-pawn is defended by tactical means, but Black continues with } 19... Nd7 $1 { with a good development. It should be noted that } 20. fxe5 $6 Nxe5 21. Bxf5 { wins a pawn, but Black has a strong idea } 21... Bc8 $1 { with active play and excellent compensation. For example: } 22. Be4 { The exchange of the light-squared bishops would leave many exposed squares in White's camp. Still, after } 22... Bg4 23. Rxf8+ Qxf8 { [%cal Ge5f3] Black gets the bishop pair and nice chances, since } 24. Qf1 $2 Bf3 $19 { is even worse. } ) 16... Bxf6 17. fxe5 Bxe5 18. Qh5 $1 { White has no option but to play for an attack in order to compensate for the many strategic commitments made so far. } 18... g6 19. Rg1 Bg7 20. Bxg6 ( 20. Rxg6 $5 { also can be considered. } 20... hxg6 21. Bxg6 { Now Black defends with } 21... Rf6 $1 22. Qh7+ Kf8 { and White only manages to create new threats by means of } 23. Kd2 $1 ( { But not } 23. O-O-O $2 Qe7 $19 { [%csl Re3] and the bishop hanging on e3 makes a lot of difference. } ) 23... Qe7 24. Re1 Qe5 $1 { [%csl Rd5][%cal Gc8f5] Although the position seems super sharp, the result is a draw after } 25. Bd4 Qf4+ 26. Be3 Qe5 27. Bd4 $11 ) 20... hxg6 21. Rxg6 { [%cal Ge1c1] If White has time to bring the other rook to the attack it's game over, so Black also needs to play in the most energetic way possible. } 21... Qe7 22. Kd2 Rf5 23. Qh6 Kf8 $1 ( { But not } 23... Rxd5+ $4 24. Bd4 $18 { [%cal Ga1g1] and White wins. } ) 24. Rxg7 $1 Qxg7 25. Qxd6+ Kf7 26. Rg1 { White is a rook down now but finally managed to bring the last piece to the attack. } 26... Qf6 27. Qg3 Rxd5+ 28. Kc1 Be6 { The position remains complex. White's attack is strong enough to regain some material, but that also leads to simplification. The engine prefers White a little bit in view of the variation } 29. Qg8+ Ke7 30. Qh7+ Bf7 31. Bg5 { forcing Black to return the rook. However, after } 31... Rxg5 32. hxg5 Qe6 { [%csl Ge3] } 33. Kb1 a4 $1 34. Nc1 Qg6 35. Qh8 Bg8 $13 { [%csl Ga8,Gb8][%cal Gb8d7,Gb8c6] Black seemingly is finally able to develop the queenside. The position remains unclear, but in practice, I don't think Black's chances should be worse. } ) 8... Be6 9. Bxf6 { Like in the 6.Be2 order, White's goal is to disturb Black's coordination and establish quick control over d5. } ( 9. Qd3 { was played by Caruana in a rapid game, but I don't think it poses serious problems for Black. } 9... Nbd7 { [%csl Gd7,Ge6,Gf6,Yg5] Whenever Black is able to play Be6 and Nbd7 that kind of makes White's Bg5 pointless. } 10. O-O-O { Caruana,F (2822) -Supi,L (2577) PRO League Stage rapid 2020 (7) 1/2-1/2 } 10... b5 $1 { This advance was already possible and good. } 11. Kb1 ( 11. a3 h6 12. Bxf6 Nxf6 { seems comfortable for Black. } ) 11... h6 12. Bxf6 ( 12. Bc1 $2 b4 13. Nd5 a5 $1 { already gives a dangerous initiative for Black on the queenside. For example: } 14. Nd2 O-O 15. Nc4 Nxd5 16. exd5 Bg4 17. f3 Nc5 $1 18. Qe3 Bf5 $17 { [%cal Ya5a4,Yb4b3] Black's attack seems very dangerous. } ) 12... Nxf6 13. Nd5 { Now the engine likes } 13... O-O $5 ( 13... Bxd5 14. exd5 Qb6 15. f3 Rc8 { also looks good for Black. } ) 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. Qxd6 Qc8 $5 { Playing for the compensation as Black has an easy development exploiting the open files. } ( { A simple path to equalize is } 15... Bxb3 16. axb3 Bxh4 $11 ) 16. Be2 { A possible continuation now is } 16... Ra7 $44 { [%cal Ga7c7] when Black has nice compensation. The pawn is not so worthy here and Black can develop promising play on the queenside. } ) 9... Bxf6 10. g3 { [%csl Yg3,Yh4][%cal Gf1h3] Reinforcing h4 and creating the idea of Bh3 to exchange Black's good bishop. Also, the kingside structure restricts the dark-squared bishop and deprives Black from improving it via g5, a typical idea in such positions. } 10... Be7 { [%cal Gb8d7] Preparing to develop the knight to d7, from where it can go either to f6 or b6 and help in the battle for the d5-square. } 11. Qd3 { The queen seems better placed here than on d2 in order to answer Nd7-f6 with Nd5, as the e4-pawn is protected. } ( 11. Bh3 { is also natural, but Black can simply leave the bishop on e6 and wait for the exchange. } 11... O-O 12. Bxe6 ( { Another game went } 12. Nd5 Nd7 13. Qd3 Nb6 14. O-O-O $2 { but after } 14... Nxd5 15. exd5 Bxh3 16. Rxh3 Qd7 17. Rh2 a5 $1 { Black has a clear advantage. } 18. Nd2 b5 19. Kb1 f5 20. f3 Bf6 $17 { Haznedaroglu,K (2472) -Yilmaz, M (2624) TUR-chT Ankara 2018 (3.6) 1/2-1/2 with promising chances of combining the activity of the Bf6 with actions on the queenside. } ) 12... fxe6 { [%csl Yd5] Now Black has good control over d5. White can try to put some pressure on e6 with } 13. Qg4 { but this isn't enough to create any problem. } 13... Rf6 14. O-O-O Nc6 { As the d5-square is under control Black can develop the knight more actively. } 15. f4 b5 $15 { Yip,C (2423) -Mishra,A (2370) Charlotte CCCSA Spring GM 2021 (2) 1-0 Despite the final result, Black's position is already better. It's much easier to keep developing Black's play on the queenside. For example: } 16. Kb1 b4 17. Ne2 a5 { [%cal Gd8b6,Ya5a4] Maybe White's best continuation now is } 18. fxe5 Nxe5 19. Qh3 { [%cal Gb3d4] trying to bring the knight back to the game. Still, after } 19... a4 20. Nbd4 Qc8 $1 { Black's initiative on the queenside looks very dangerous. } 21. Nf4 $2 { loses on the spot due to } 21... a3 $19 ) ( 11. Qd2 { was seen in some games, but the queen is worse on d2. } 11... Nd7 12. O-O-O Nf6 { An interesting detail is that Black doesn't need to rush to castle in this position. Instead, It's better to keep mobilizing our queenside. } 13. f4 b5 $1 14. f5 $2 ( 14. Bh3 { was tried in another game, but now } 14... O-O $1 { is good. The game went } 15. fxe5 dxe5 16. Qxd8 Raxd8 17. Rxd8 Rxd8 18. Bxe6 fxe6 { [%csl Ye5,Ye6,Ge7] but the resulting endgame is easier for Black. The doubled pawns are actually good: they control many squares in the center. Also, in the long run our bishop tends to be very strong. } 19. a3 Rc8 { [%cal Ge7a3] } 20. Kd2 { Deac,B (2609) -Rodshtein,M (2673) EU-ch 20th Skopje 2019 (5) 0-1 Black won in an instructive way. However, } 20... Bd8 $15 { was even more precise: Black prepares ideas like a5-b4, the bishop can be activated via b6 and the e7-square is vacated for the king. White has a difficult defense ahead. } ) ( 14. Bd3 $5 { Martinez Alcantara,J (2598) -Giri,A (2772) Chess.com Rapid Wk1 Swiss 2022 (3) 0-1 was an interesting try seen in a rapid game. In the game Giri played 0-0 immediately, but that could have allowed f4-f5 followed by g3-g4, when White sacrifices a pawn for promising attacking chances on the kingside. Instead, more precise would've been } 14... h5 $1 { fixing the kingside and making it hard for White to keep advancing the pawns. A possible continuation would be } 15. Kb1 O-O 16. f5 { but know we can play } 16... Bc4 $1 { and Black has the position under control. In case of } 17. g4 $5 hxg4 18. h5 { there is the typical defensive idea } 18... Kh7 $1 { when } 19. h6 { is always answered by } 19... g6 $17 { and the king is totally safe. Otherwise, Black can keep developing the play on the queenside by means of Rb8-a5-b4 or to break in the center with d6-d5. Another idea with the king on h7 is Rh8-Kg8, a strange but typical defensive regrouping. } ) 14... Bd7 { [%cal Gd7c6] Here we can see the main point of delaying 0-0: with the king on e8 the advance of White's pawns on the kingside is not so threatening. As White has released the tension in the center with f4-f5 Black has a solid position and can put pressure on e4. This position has occurred in one game and Black played in a very instructive way: } 15. Qd3 Rc8 16. Kb1 O-O 17. Nd2 Bc6 18. Bg2 Qb6 19. Bf3 { [%cal Yg3g4] } 19... h5 $1 { Making it hard for White to continue advancing on the kingside. } 20. Qe2 { Now Black developed his own attack on the queenside with } 20... a5 $1 21. Nd5 Bxd5 22. exd5 a4 23. Bxh5 a3 $19 { Esipenko,A (2620) -Matlakov,M (2697) RUS-chT Sochi 2019 (9. 2) 0-1 and Black's attack came first. } ) 11... Nd7 12. O-O-O b5 $1 { [%csl Gd7] Here Giri recommends to keep the knight on d7 for a while, as White has an improved version of Esipenko-Matlakov with the queen on d3. } 13. f4 { Now we can play in a very concrete way with } ( 13. a3 { was played against me in an online game recently. It seems that White's idea is to wait for } 13... Nf6 { and now play } 14. f4 { but Black still has a good game after } 14... O-O 15. f5 Bd7 16. Be2 $2 { This is too slow as Black has the strong reply } ( 16. Qf3 $5 { is suggested by the engine, with the variation } 16... h5 $1 17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. Rxd5 Qc7 $13 { [%cal Gf8c8,Ya6a5] leading to a complex game. } ) 16... a5 $1 { [%cal Yb5b4] ; Kevlishvili,R (2529) -Quintiliano Pinto,R (2509) Julius Baer Play In rapid 2023 (3.60) 1/2-1/2 with nice counterplay. My opponent didn't play in the best way and I had a big advantage, but the game eventually ended in a draw. The engine says White has nothing better than } 17. Nxb5 { but after the simple } 17... Bxb5 18. Qxb5 Nxe4 { [%csl Rf2,Rg3][%cal Ga8b8,Ya5a4,Gd8c7] I like Black's position. } ) 13... b4 $1 14. Nd5 Bxd5 $1 { Black parts with the bishop pair, but it was important to get rid of the strong knight. Now we can count with a5-a4 to get counterplay on the queenside. } 15. Qxd5 O-O 16. Qb7 $5 { A curious suggestion by the engine to deal with a5-a4. } ( { The analysis shows that the text should lead to a draw, so I decided to investigate other options for White. } 16. fxe5 { was seen in one game. } 16... Nxe5 17. Nd4 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gb3d4] White brings his knight back to the center, but Black is also happy with an outpost on e5. } 17... Qc7 18. Nf5 Rfd8 { Albornoz Cabrera,C (2577) -Quirhuayo Chumbe,G (2296) Online Olym Div Top-D rapid 2020 (2.5) 0-1 Here it's possible to improve White's play with } 19. Ne3 { directly. Nevertheless, after } 19... a5 20. Qd2 Bf8 21. Nd5 Qc5 { Black's position is very solid. The knight seems strong on d5, but White has no way of taking advantage of that. After something like } 22. Be2 Rdb8 23. Kb1 ( 23. h5 { directly can be risky in view of } 23... b3 $1 ) 23... a4 24. h5 b3 25. cxb3 ( 25. h6 $2 bxa2+ 26. Ka1 g6 $17 { is better for Black. } ) 25... axb3 26. a3 Ra4 $13 { Black is active enough to keep the balance, although the position is tense and double-edged. } ) ( 16. Nd2 $2 { was tried in one game, but the plan of regrouping White's pieces on the light squares seems too slow. } 16... Nf6 17. Qb3 Qc7 18. Kb1 a5 19. Bc4 a4 20. Qd3 { Kevlishvili,R (2536) -Perez,R (2362) Hollywood Masters op 2022 (4) 1-0 Maybe } 20... Ra5 $5 { is an improvement for Black. The difference is that if } 21. Rhf1 { like in the game, Black shouldn't worry about the pressure on f7 and can continue developing the pressure on the queenside with } 21... Rc5 { It's a bit surprising but White's position is already unpleasant here. For example: } 22. fxe5 dxe5 23. Qe2 { [%cal Yg3g4] } 23... h5 $1 24. b3 Qc6 $1 { [%csl Ge4] Another strong move, tying the knight to the defense of e4. White is passive and struggles to find a plan here, and after } 25. Rde1 Rd8 26. Rf3 ( 26. Nf3 { is not possible due to } 26... Nxe4 $1 27. Qxe4 Rd1+ $19 ) 26... g6 27. Rd3 Rc8 28. Nf3 a3 $17 { [%cal Gc5c4] Black has a clear advantage. The sacrifice on c4 is a very strong idea to consider in the next moves, despite not being possible by now due to Nxc4. } ) ( { In another game White tried } 16. Bh3 Nf6 17. Qc6 Qb8 18. Na5 $2 { but after } 18... Ra7 $1 { Black took the initiative. } 19. Qc4 Qb6 20. Nc6 Rc7 21. Nxe7+ Rxe7 22. Rhe1 { Sreyas,P (2145) -Arjun Sidharth,S (1681) IND-ch U15 47th 2022 (5) 1-0 Now the simple } 22... Rfe8 { [%csl Re4] probably would have led to material gains for Black. For example: } 23. Bf1 ( 23. fxe5 Rxe5 24. Qd4 { isn't better due to } 24... Qa5 $1 25. Kb1 d5 $19 ) 23... exf4 24. gxf4 a5 25. Bg2 d5 26. Qd4 Qxd4 27. Rxd4 dxe4 $19 ) 16... a5 17. Bb5 ( 17. Bh3 { is another option. Now Black needs to solve the problems by means of concrete play: } 17... a4 $1 ( { It's important to remember that in case of } 17... Nb6 $2 18. fxe5 $16 { Black can't force repetition like in the main line as the queen escapes via b5 } ) 18. Bxd7 ( 18. Qxd7 axb3 19. Qxd8 Rfxd8 20. axb3 exf4 21. gxf4 Bxh4 $11 ) 18... Rb8 19. Qa7 axb3 20. cxb3 { Here Black can choose between repeating moves with Rb8-a8 or keep the game going with } 20... exf4 21. gxf4 Bxh4 $11 { with a dynamically balanced game, but the opposite colored bishops offer chances for both sides. } ) 17... Nb6 ( 17... a4 $6 { doesn't work well with the bishop on b5: } 18. Qxd7 axb3 19. axb3 Ra1+ 20. Kd2 Rxd1+ 21. Rxd1 Qb6 22. f5 $16 ) 18. fxe5 { This leads to repetition, but the threat a5-a4 was too annoying for White. } 18... Rb8 19. Qc6 Rc8 20. Qb7 Rb8 21. Qa6 Ra8 $11 *
