1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bd3 { In my opinion White's most interesting alternative option against the Najdorf. I remember that when I started playing the Najdorf such a move was considered simply harmless, and we expected to equalize against it by simple and natural moves. However, after a nice win by Nakamura against Vachier Lagrave in 2017 many ideas were found for White and this line became a little bit popular. The main point is to keep the e2-square available for the knight against e7-e5. The bishop seems a bit pointless on d3, but White intends to solve this matter by means of a knight jump to d5, changing the structure and opening the b1-h7 diagonal. } 6... e5 { Once more let's examine the most Najdorf move. } ( { In 2018 I had recommended } 6... g6 { but after making a deeper analysis I've changed my opinion. Practice has shown that White can continue normally with Be3-f3-Qd2, and even with the bishop on d3 the position still seems promising. } ) ( { As well noted by Giri, if you are looking for a Dragon set-up against this line maybe it's better to start with } 6... Nbd7 $5 { waiting for } 7. O-O { then play } 7... g6 ) ( 6... e6 { is also possible, but leads to another kind of game with the Scheveningen structure. } ) 7. Nde2 { The knight might look a bit limited on e2, but it can go to g3 in the future. } ( 7. Nb3 { or } ) ( 7. Nf3 { can be played, but in both cases, it's hard to find a reason to have the bishop on d3 instead of e2. } ) ( 7. Nf5 $5 { was seen in a few games. In many similar positions Black reacts with d6-d5, but here } 7... Bxf5 $1 { is the right move. } ( 7... d5 $2 { leaves Black in trouble after } 8. Nxd5 Nxd5 9. exd5 Qxd5 10. Qg4 $1 { [%csl Rc8,Rg7][%cal Gf5g7,Gg4c8] } 10... Bxf5 11. Qxf5 $16 ) 8. exf5 d5 9. Bg5 { Now Black needs to be careful in order to keep the center under control. } 9... Bb4 10. O-O Bxc3 $5 { A very concrete decision, but I prefer to give the bishop pair than keep waiting for Bxf6, which leaves Black with doubled pawns on the kingside. } 11. bxc3 O-O 12. c4 ( { In another game White played } 12. Qb1 { trying to put a quick pressure on the enemy camp, but after } 12... b6 13. Rd1 Nbd7 14. c4 Qc7 15. cxd5 Nxd5 16. Qb3 Nc3 17. Re1 b5 18. f6 g6 $1 19. Re3 Rac8 $11 { Vaishali,R (2414) -Berdnyk,M (2308) Online Olym KO Stage rapid 2021 (1.21) 1/2-1/2 Black keeps everything under control. } ) 12... e4 $5 ( { Also possible was } 12... dxc4 13. Bxc4 Nc6 $11 { with an equal game, as the bishop pair doesn't look so dangerous here. } ) 13. Be2 d4 14. Rb1 Nc6 $5 { Martins,B (2248) -Represa Perez,M (2151) Guimaraes 2nd 2018 (6) 0-1 An interesting pawn sacrifice. } 15. Rxb7 Re8 $44 { [%csl Gd4,Ge4,Yf5][%cal Gd8c8, Gc6a5] The strong center takes a lot of space from White and gives Black enough compensation. Ideas like Qc8 and Na5 can be unpleasant, and the f5-pwan is always hanging. } ) 7... Be7 8. O-O Be6 $5 { This move order has been played by Najdorf specialists like Wojtaszek, Giri and Dominguez and seems good enough. } ( 8... O-O { is the most played. Many games continue with } 9. Ng3 Be6 { and now White plays } 10. Nd5 $1 { Provoking a transformation in the pawn structure in order to activate the Bd3. The tactical point is that } 10... Nxd5 11. exd5 Bxd5 12. Bxh7+ Kxh7 13. Qxd5 $14 { is slightly better for White. The text aims to prevent such ideas. } ) 9. f4 { White has to change plans now, but this advance seems good with the bishop on e6. } ( { The main point of this move order is that if } 9. Ng3 { instead of transposing we can play } 9... Nc6 $1 { and suddenly White has to find another idea. } 10. a3 { has been seen in most of the games. } ( { Now if } 10. Nd5 { we can accept the pawn: } 10... Nxd5 11. exd5 Bxd5 { as Bxh7 is not check. White has nothing better than } 12. Bxa6 { Although Bxg2 is tempting and also playable, I think } 12... Nd4 $5 { [%cal Gd5c6] followed by Bc6 is simpler. I like Black's position, as the exchange of a rook pawn for a central one seems a good deal for us. A possible continuation would be } 13. Bb5+ $5 Bc6 14. Bxc6+ bxc6 15. c3 Ne6 16. Nf5 Bf8 $1 { [%cal Yg7g6,Yf7f5,Gf8g7] Next we can continue our development with g6-Bg7 and eventually f7-f5, with a promising game. } ) ( 10. Nh5 { is the second most played. Although getting rid of the Ng3 makes sense, I don't see how this could pose any problem for Black. } 10... Nxh5 11. Qxh5 Nb4 $5 { [%csl Yc2,Yd3] A nice practical idea, grabbing the bishop pair. } 12. Rd1 Qd7 13. Qe2 Rc8 14. a3 Nxd3 15. Qxd3 O-O $11 { [%cal Gc8c6,Gf8c8,Yb7b5,Yf7f5] ; Adams, M (2694) -Giri,A (2780) EU-chT 22nd Batumi 2019 (4.2) 1/2-1/2 Black has already equalized. A common plan in such positions is to play Rc6, as besides overprotecting the d6-pawn we can increase the pressure on the c-file, making it hard for White to play Nd5. Other typical ideas are the expansion on the queenside with b7-b5 and the pawn break f7-f5, opening lines for the bishops and loosening White's control in the center. } ) ( 10. f4 { doesn't work well with the knight on g3. The following game by Leinier Dominguez is an instructive example of how to play as Black: } 10... exf4 11. Rxf4 g6 $1 { [%csl Gg3] A typical and strong move that leaves the white knight out of play on g3. } 12. Be3 { Moiseenko,V (2526) -Dominguez Perez,L (2758) Wch Blitz Moscow 2019 (13) 0-1 In the game Black opted for a more aggressive plan with h5-h4 that also worked well. However, after something simple like } 12... O-O 13. Qe2 Ne5 14. h3 Rc8 15. Rff1 Nfd7 $15 { [%cal Ge7g5,Ge7f6,Gf6g7,Yb7b5,Gd7c5] he also has a comfortable position, with the same typical plans seen in the main line. The biggest difference is that White's position always seems a bit strange and uncomfortable with the passive knight on g3. } ) ( 10. Bg5 $6 { Kantans,T (2490) -Bjerre,J (2529) Bundesliga 1920 2019 (9.5) 0-1 is a provocative move which was seen in one game. Objectively speaking White's idea is just a bluff. The best way of refuting it is by going into the complications: } 10... Nxe4 $1 11. Ngxe4 ( 11. Bxe7 Nxc3 $17 ) 11... Bxg5 12. Bc4 $1 Be7 13. Bxe6 fxe6 14. Qg4 { [%csl Ge6, Gg7] At first sight looks like White has a lot of activity for the pawn, but Black has a surprisingly strong plan in this position: } 14... Nd4 $1 15. Qxg7 Kd7 $1 { [%cal Gd8f8,Gh8g8,Gd7c7] Black can exploit the open files on the kingside in active way, while the king finds a safe place on c7. A possible variation is } 16. f4 Qf8 $1 17. Qg3 Rg8 18. Qh3 Qf5 $1 19. Qe3 Raf8 { Black has basically all the pieces actively developed. Even after something like } 20. Ng3 Qg4 21. fxe5 d5 $15 { [%cal Ge7c5,Gd4c2,Yh7h5,Yh5h4] the pressure on the kingside remains, and White needs to worry about many unpleasant threats. } ) ( 10. a4 $6 { was played by Niemann, but seems harmless. After } 10... Nb4 11. Re1 O-O 12. Bg5 Rc8 13. Qd2 $6 h6 14. Be3 Ng4 $15 { Niemann,H (2688) -Wojtaszek,R (2708) FTX Road to Miami Prelim 2022 (14) 0-1 Black has a comfortable game. } ) ( { Finally, } 10. Nf5 $2 { was tried in one game, but after } 10... Bxf5 11. exf5 d5 { [%csl Gd5,Ge5] the strong pawn center gives a clear advantage for Black. } 12. Bg5 { Karthikeyan,M (2611) -Raja,H (2447) El Prat de Llobregat op-A 1st 2019 (5) 0-1 The best way of consolidating Black's advantage now was } 12... h6 13. Bh4 Qd7 $17 { [%cal Ga8d8] followed by Rd8, 0-0 and Rfe8, with a clearly better position. } ) 10... Rc8 ( { Here } 10... O-O { is also possible, threatening to free Black's game by means of d6-d5. A nice difference is that if } 11. Nd5 { now we can go for } 11... Nxd5 12. exd5 Bxd5 13. Bxh7+ Kxh7 14. Qxd5 { [%csl Gc6] ;Wang,Y (2294) -Ning,K (2327) CHN-ch (Women) 2021 (8) 0-1 since we already have the knight developed on c6, with an improved version of other lines. After } 14... f5 $11 { [%cal Gd8b6,Gd8e8, Ga8c8] Black continues with an active development and has at least equal chances. } ) 11. Re1 { This position has occurred in two online games. White goes for a maneuvering game, maybe aiming to bring the knight back to the game via f1. Black has many possible plans here, but I like } 11... g6 $14 { taking control over f5. This is an important measure, since we want to advance d6-d5 at some point, so it's good to avoid Nf5. } 12. h3 ( { In case of } 12. Nf1 d5 $1 { Black gets a free game. } 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 Qxd5 15. Ne3 Qd7 16. Nc4 Qc7 17. Bh6 f6 $11 { [%cal Ge8f7,Ge7f8] The king's issue can be easily solved by means of either Kf7 or Bf8 in the next move, with a safe position. } ) 12... O-O 13. Bh6 Re8 14. Qd2 Nd4 $5 { While Black keeps making natural moves, White struggles to find a useful plan here. } 15. Nce2 ( 15. Rad1 $2 Bxh3 $1 { is the threat. } ) 15... Nxe2+ 16. Nxe2 d5 $11 { and Black has equalized without problems. } ) 9... exf4 10. Nxf4 Nc6 { [%csl Ye5,Yf4][%cal Gc6e5] Again we have this typical Najdorf structure. White managed to solve the problem of the e2-knight, which is active on f4. On the other hand, Black's position is solid as usual and our knights also have a nice outpost on e5. } 11. Be3 ( 11. Nxe6 { is not dangerous. Despite getting the bishop pair, with this exchange White improves Black's structure in the center. } 11... fxe6 12. Bc4 ( 12. Qf3 { [%csl Re6][%cal Gf3h3] was played by Paravyan with the idea of pressing the e6-pawn from h3. } 12... Ne5 13. Qh3 Qd7 { Paravyan,D (2629) -Yilmaz,M (2607) Gibraltar Masters 18th 2020 (10) 1/2-1/ 2 In the game White continued the development with Be3, but then Black had enough time to mobilize his pieces with 0-0 and Rae8, with an equal game. The most principled to increase the pressure on e6 would be } 14. Ne2 O-O 15. Nf4 { but Black has more than one adequate way of facing this idea. I like } 15... Bd8 $1 { sacrificing the pawn to get active play. } 16. Qxe6+ $6 { seems even risky for White due to } 16... Qxe6 17. Nxe6 Bb6+ 18. Kh1 Rfe8 19. Nf4 Rac8 $36 { [%csl Re4][%cal Ge5d3,Gc8c2,Ge5g4]  when Black's initiative already seems unpleasant. } ) 12... Qd7 13. a4 { Avoiding b7-b5 and securing a square for the bishop on the a2-g8 diagonal. } ( 13. Na4 $2 { fails because of a tactical detail: } 13... b5 14. Nb6 Qa7 $19 { [%csl Rb6,Rg1][%cal Ga7g1] } ) ( 13. a3 { Moussard,J (2686) -Palac,M (2516) Zagreb Peace 2022 (1) 1-0 was seen in a recent game and worked out well for White. In the game, Black tried to exploit White's move in a principled way by accelerating the play on the queenside with Ne5-Rc8-b5. However, it's maybe safer to play in the same way as after 13.a4 with } 13... O-O 14. Kh1 Ne5 15. Ba2 Rae8 $11 { [%cal Ge7d8,Gf6g4] when despite White having some pressure with the bishops, Black's position is always solid. A good idea to relieve this pressure could be to force exchanges along the f-file by means of Nfg4. } ) ( 13. Bf4 { is harmless as after } 13... b5 14. Bb3 Na5 $11 { [%csl Gb3] ;Stany,G (2525) -Gopal, G (2594) Biel MTO op 52nd 2019 (3) 1/2-1/2 Black manages to get rid of the light-squared bishop, making his position considerably safer. } ) 13... O-O { [%cal Ga8e8,Ge7d8,Gg8h8] According to Giri, Black has a solid position and is able to keep all the important points well defended. One possible plan mentioned by him is to mobilize our pieces with Rae8-Bd8 after the prophylactic Kh8. } ( 13... Rc8 { was played in a recent game and also solved Black's problems. } 14. Ba2 O-O 15. Bf4 Kh8 16. Qe2 { [%cal Ga1d1] White aims to establish a permanent pressure on d6, but Black comes first with a nice thematic maneuver: } 16... Bd8 $1 17. Rad1 Bb6+ 18. Kh1 Bd4 $11 { [%csl Yd4][%cal Ge7d8,Gd8b6,Gb6d4,Gd4e5] ;Adams,M (2696) -Brkic,A (2611) GER CupT Baden Baden 2022 (2.1) 1/2-1/2 The bishop ends its journey on e5, giving a very solid position for Black. } ) 14. Bf4 { Looking for ideas for White this seems the best way of keeping d6 under pressure, thus preventing Black from improving the bishop via d8. } ( 14. Kh1 { is another natural move. An interesting plan for Black now is to double rooks on the f-file. That secures the control over the file and can lead to exchanges which relieve the position. After } 14... Rf7 15. Qe2 Raf8 16. Be3 Bd8 17. Rad1 Qe7 $11 { [%cal Gd8a5,Gc6e5,Ga5b4,Gb4c5] Black has mobilized the pieces and keeps a solid position. The knight always has the e5-square, and the maneuver Ba5-b4-c5 is a good idea to keep in mind, as we either exchange or improve our worst piece. } ) 14... Rad8 { [%cal Yd6d5] Now Black focuses on preparing the advance d6-d5. } 15. Bb3 ( 15. Qe2 d5 16. Rad1 $2 { seems strong, but is a serious mistake in view of } 16... Nd4 $1 17. Rxd4 Bc5 $19 { and Black wins. } ) 15... Kh8 { The last preparatory move for the advance. } 16. Be3 $5 { [%cal Ge3b6] White tries to make the advance of the d-pawn harder, but since the bishop is not attacking d6 anymore we can go back to the original regrouping: } 16... Rde8 $1 { [%cal Ge7d8] } 17. Kh1 ( 17. Bf4 Rd8 $11 ) 17... Bd8 18. Bf4 Bc7 19. Qd3 Qf7 20. Rad1 Ne5 $11 { Black manages to reach the desired set-up just in time, with a solid and safe position. } ) ( 11. b3 $5 { is a less exploited but interesting alternative. The bishop is at least not worse on b2 than on e3, and it can support attacking ideas on the kingside. } 11... O-O 12. Bb2 Ne5 13. Qe1 Rc8 14. Rd1 Re8 15. h3 { This is the set-up aimed by White: his pieces are developed harmoniously and he can start a maneuvering game to improve his position and invade the enemy camp. I like how Black-faced this plan in the following game by Ivan Saric, a renowned Najdorf expert: } 15... Bf8 { The bishop should go to g7 in order to protect the kingside and make opposition to White's Bb2. } 16. Kh1 b5 17. Nce2 ( { If } 17. Nxe6 Nxd3 $1 { is a nice intermediate. } 18. Rxd3 Rxe6 19. Rdf3 Rc7 $11 ) 17... Bd7 $1 { [%csl Re4][%cal Ge6d7,Gd7c6] Now he improves the light-squared bishop and prevents tactical ideas on the d-file created by White's last move. } 18. Qg3 Bc6 19. Nd5 Bxd5 20. exd5 g6 $11 { [%cal Gf8g7] ;Van Foreest,J (2688) -Saric,I (2653) Zagreb GCT Rapid 2021 (4) 1/2-1/2 Black has achieved a comfortable equality already. } ) 11... Ne5 $1 { [%csl Gc4] It's important to remember this move before castling in order to avoid Bc4. } ( 11... O-O $2 { now leaves Black in trouble as } 12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. Bc4 Qd7 $2 14. Na4 $18 { is an improved version for White, with the bishop on e3 and the black king already on g8. } ) 12. a4 { [%cal Ya4a5] The most logical plan, gaining space and cramping Black's queenside. } ( 12. Kh1 { is an useful move that can be played at any moment. Objectively it doesn't change much, as White has to make the plans seen in the main line at some point. } 12... O-O 13. a4 ( { In one game White tried to play without the advance a4-a5: } 13. Bd4 Nfd7 14. Qe2 Bg5 15. Ncd5 Re8 16. Nxe6 $6 { I think White went for this exchange because he was worried about ideas on the e-file after Bxd5, but this only improves Black's structure in the center. } 16... fxe6 17. Ne3 Qe7 18. Ng4 Nxg4 19. Qxg4 Bf6 { Black has no problems here. After } 20. c3 Bxd4 21. cxd4 Nf6 22. Qh3 e5 { [%csl Ge4] ;Perunovic,M (2541) -Ter Sahakyan,S (2615) EU-chT 23rd Terme Catez 2021 (8.4) 0-1 the structure was fixed in a way that offers slightly better practical chances for Black. He skillfully exploited the small superiority of the knight over the bad bishop to score a nice win. } ) 13... Rc8 14. a5 { The position is very similar to the main line and Black can go for the same regrouping with } 14... Nfd7 15. h3 Re8 $11 { [%cal Ge7f8,Ge7g5,Ge5c4,Yg7g6] with a balanced game. Black always a solid position thanks to the Ne5. The bishop can be improved either via g5 or Bf8-g6-Bg7, and Nc4 is another possibility. White also has a good position and firm control over d5, but it is hard to find a plan to make progress. } ) 12... O-O { Black has an easy plan here: regrouping with Nfd7-Bg5, reinforcing the reinforcing the control on the outpost and activating the dark-squared bishop. } 13. Bd4 ( { If } 13. a5 { we can play like in the main line with } 13... Nfd7 $14 { postponing Rc8. } ( 13... Rc8 { was played by Cheparinov, another strong Najdorf specialist. The game went } 14. Bd4 Nfd7 15. Ncd5 Bg5 { Sasikiran,K (2675) -Cheparinov,I (2670) ESP-chT CECLUB Honor 2019 (4.2) 1/2-1/2 Here } 16. c3 $5 { [%cal Gd3c2] intending Bc2 could give some pressure for White. That's why saving the tempo of Rc8 might be useful. } ) 14. Ncd5 { White aims the same set-up as played by Sasikiran, which is very logical. } 14... Bg5 15. Bd4 ( { Now in case of } 15. c3 { Black can exploit the x-ray of the bishops with } 15... Bxd5 $5 16. Nxd5 Bxe3+ 17. Nxe3 { with a roughly equal position thanks to the strong outpost on e5. A possible continuation could be } 17... Qg5 18. Nd5 Nxd3 19. Qxd3 Rae8 { [%cal Gd7c5] } 20. b4 Ne5 21. Qe2 Qd8 $11 { with a balanced game. } ) 15... Nc5 $5 { We get this extra idea by postponing Rc8. Now White is not able to play c3-Bc2 and it's very hard to find another useful idea. Next we can play Rc8, and it's always possible to consider some exchanges in order to simplify the position. After all, the knight remains solid on e5 giving stability for Black's play. } ) 13... Nfd7 { Maybe it's more precise to start the regrouping immediately, without playing Rc8. } 14. Ncd5 Bg5 15. c3 { [%cal Gd3c2] Intending to keep the light-squared bishop in the game. } 15... Bxf4 16. Rxf4 ( { In case of } 16. Nxf4 { we can force further exchanges with } 16... Nxd3 17. Qxd3 Ne5 18. Qg3 ( { One game went } 18. Bxe5 dxe5 19. Qxd8 Raxd8 20. Nxe6 fxe6 21. Rfd1 $11 { Juhasz,A (2379) -Karthik,V (2491) Budapest Vezerkepzo GM 11 2021 (1) 1/2-1/2 Despite the doubled pawns on the e-file the endgame is equal. } ) 18... Qe7 19. a5 Rae8 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Yf7f6] Black's position is quite solid. Maybe it is a little bit passive, but it is hard to find a good plan for White as long as the knight remains firmly on e5. The next step could be to reinforce the knight with f7-f6, but Black can play more actively according to White's next moves. For example: } 20. Nd5 Bxd5 21. exd5 { Now we can play } 21... f5 $1 { directly. If } 22. Rae1 f4 $1 23. Qh3 ( 23. Rxf4 $2 Rxf4 24. Qxf4 Nf3+ $19 ) 23... Qc7 24. b4 Qc4 $11 { and Black is ok. } ) 16... Qg5 { [%cal Ga8e8,Ge6d5] Now the rook can go directly to e8, where it will be well placed in case of an exchange on d5. This is a good reason to keep it on a8 for a while. Giri ends his analysis here evaluating the position as equal, but we can go a bit further to confirm this assessment. } 17. Bc2 { Keeping the bishops seems a reasonable idea. } ( 17. a5 { allows more exchanges, which tends to make Black's task easier: } 17... Nxd3 18. Qxd3 Ne5 ( 18... Bxd5 19. Rf5 $1 ) 19. Bxe5 Qxe5 20. Raf1 Rfe8 21. c4 ( 21. Nc7 $2 Qc5+ ) 21... Rac8 22. b3 Bxd5 23. exd5 Rc7 $11 { Black keeps the control in the endgame without problems. } ) ( 17. Rf1 Bxd5 18. Rf5 ( 18. exd5 Nxd3 19. Qxd3 Qxd5 $15 ) 18... Qh6 19. exd5 g6 20. Rf1 Rae8 $11 { [%cal Yf7f5,Gd7f6] looks also fine for Black. } ) 17... Bxd5 ( { Black can also just keep mobilizing the pieces with } 17... Rae8 ) 18. Rf5 Qh6 19. exd5 g6 20. Rf2 f5 21. h3 Rae8 $11 { [%cal Ge8e7,Gd7f6] The position is dynamically balanced. The structure resembles some Najdorf lines and offers chances for both sides. Although White has the bishop pair and a queenside majority, our knights have firm and active outposts on e5/e4. The kingside majority has a lot of potential and Black can develop active play on the e-file, so the game tends to develop in a double-edged fight. } *
