1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Rg1 { [%csl Gg1][%cal Yg2g4] This move has always existed and was even played by Fischer, but never became fashionable at the high level. However, in the last years it has been seen in games of creative players like Nepo and Van Foreest. White obviously wants to play g2-g4 by any means. Honestly, I don't think it's a dangerous move, but as usual, it's good not to be caught off guard. } 6... e5 { Facing White's operation on the flank in a classical way, with an energetic reaction in the center. } ( { Nevertheless, Black has many playable options against this line. } 6... b5 { is the second most played. } ) ( 6... g6 { or } ) ( 6... Nc6 { are also possible, and even } ) ( 6... h5 $5 { can be considered, preventing g2-g4 and keeping some flexibility. } ) 7. Nb3 Be6 { [%cal Yd6d5] White doesn't have a good way of avoiding d6-d5 and a quick transposition to the endgame. } ( { In his course Giri also analyses } 7... h5 $5 { as a fighting option, keeping more pieces in the game. } ) 8. g4 ( { In an online game Fedoseev played } 8. Bg5 { but after } 8... Nbd7 { [%csl Gg1] It's hard to find a point for the white rook on g1. } 9. Be2 ( 9. g4 $5 Rc8 10. Qf3 b5 11. O-O-O h6 12. Bd2 Nb6 { also looks good for Black. I still don't know what is White's plan here. } ) 9... Rc8 10. Nd5 Bxd5 11. exd5 Be7 12. Be3 Nb6 13. Bxb6 Qxb6 $17 { Fedoseev,V (2688) -Durarbayli,V (2612) Speed Chess Q1 blitz 2022 (11) 0-1 Black's position is already very good. } ) ( 8. f4 $5 { was a move that surprised me in an online game, played by the creative Spanish GM Vallejo Pons. Indeed, it is a very rare line, though approved by the engine. After studying it better, my suggestion is } 8... Nc6 { keeping the tension. } ( { In the game I played } 8... exf4 { immediately, which allowed White to demonstrate his idea in an instructive way. } 9. Bxf4 Nc6 10. Qe2 Be7 11. g4 $1 Nd7 12. g5 $1 Nce5 13. O-O-O $16 { Vallejo Pons,F (2706) -Quintiliano Pinto,R (2509) Aimchess Play In op rapid 2023 (5) 1-0 Basically White achieved a much improved version of one of the lines analyzed in the first database after 6.Be3 e5 7.Nb3 Be6 8.h3. Instead of h3-g4 he played Rg1-g4-g5, which makes the attack on the kingside much faster. White's position is already much better, and my opponent won very convincingly. } ) 9. g4 ( 9. f5 $2 { is too hasty. Black has the strong reply } 9... Bxb3 10. axb3 d5 $1 11. exd5 Nd4 $36 { [%csl Yd5,Yf5][%cal Gf8c5,Gf8b4] with strong initiative. } ) 9... exf4 $5 { Black is better prepared to relieve the tension in the center with one more piece developed. } 10. g5 ( 10. Bxf4 $6 d5 $15 { is already a bit better for Black. } ) 10... Nd7 11. Bxf4 h6 $1 { Not the only playable option, but the most concrete. } 12. Qd2 ( { Both } 12. h4 hxg5 13. hxg5 Nde5 14. Be2 Qb6 $15 { and } ) ( 12. gxh6 Qh4+ $1 13. Bg3 Qxh6 $15 { look more pleasant for Black. } ) 12... hxg5 13. Bxg5 Nde5 $5 14. Rg3 ( 14. Bxd8 $2 Nf3+ 15. Kd1 Nxd2 $19 { [%csl Rh2] } ) 14... Be7 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 { The position is equal. For example: } 16. O-O-O O-O-O 17. Rxg7 Qh4 18. Rg2 Bh3 19. Rg3 Bxf1 20. Rxf1 Qxh2 $11 ) 8... d5 { The simplest path to equalize. } ( 8... h6 $5 { is another option. } ) 9. exd5 ( 9. g5 { is another way of going to the endgame, but seems harmless. } 9... Nxe4 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 12. Bg2 ( 12. Be3 { looks active, but is actually an inferior move order for White. } 12... Kc7 13. Bg2 { Black has a good thematic idea in this position: } 13... h6 $1 14. gxh6 ( { Or } 14. h4 hxg5 15. hxg5 Rh4 $5 { and White still has some work to regain the pawn. } ) 14... g6 $1 { [%csl Yh2][%cal Gf8h6]  ;Prasad,D (2465) -Sasikiran,K (2569) IND-ch 39th Nagpur 2002 (4) 0-1 Black has a superior structure now and better chances in the endgame. The position is still objectively equal, but in practice, only Black can play for an advantage. } ) 12... Kc7 13. Bxe4 Nc6 14. Be3 ( 14. f4 $5 { seems more active, but after } 14... g6 { Black keeps a solid position. For example: } 15. fxe5 h6 $1 16. h4 Nxe5 17. Bf4 Bd6 18. Nc5 Bf5 $1 19. O-O-O Bxe4 20. Nxe4 Nd3+ $1 21. Rxd3 Bxf4+ $11 ) 14... Rd8 { [%cal Gd8d1] In the end it is White who can't castle. } 15. Nc5 ( 15. c3 { was played in three games but doesn't look very useful. In this case Black can go to the typical plan of breaking on the kingside: } 15... g6 $1 { [%cal Yh7h6] } 16. h4 h6 $11 { with a good game. } ) ( 15. Rd1 Rxd1+ 16. Kxd1 h6 $1 17. gxh6 g6 $15 { [%cal Gf8h6] ;Gueting,J-Juhnke,K (2305) Oberliga Nord W 9495 1994 (3.4) 1/2-1/2 also left Black with better chances in the endgame. } ) 15... Bxc5 16. Bxc5 { Landa,K (2542) -Nevostrujev,V (2466) RUS-chT 06th 1999 (2) 1/2-1/2 The endgame is pretty equal, but the game goes on. I like the following variation: } 16... Bd5 $5 17. Bxd5 ( 17. Bd3 b6 18. Be3 Nb4 $11 { is ok for Black. } ) 17... Rxd5 18. Be3 Rhd8 $11 { [%cal Yf7f5,Gc6e7,Ge7f5,Gc6d4,Gc7d7, Gd7e6] when Black can try some ideas like Ne7 (d4) -f5, or bringing the king to e6 followed by the advance of the kingside pawns. The most likely result still should be a draw, but we can keep playing. } ) 9... Nxd5 10. Nxd5 ( { In some recent games White tried a little surprise with } 10. Bg5 $5 { Although it is in fact a creative attempt, Black has the simple and solid reply } 10... f6 $1 ( { If } 10... Qxg5 11. Nxd5 Qd8 12. Bg2 $14 { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gd1e2,Ge1c1] White might get some pressure after Qe2 and 0-0-0. } ) 11. Nxd5 Qxd5 12. Qxd5 Bxd5 13. Be3 { [%csl Yf6] White's goal was to provoke the advance of the f-pawn, intending to exploit the light squares or to create tension on the kingside with g4-g5. However, it's hard to imagine Black facing serious problems in such a solid position. } 13... Nc6 14. O-O-O O-O-O 15. Bb6 Rd6 { Here Nepo played } 16. g5 $5 ( { Another game went } 16. Rg3 { [%cal Gg3d3] but Black avoids any problem with } 16... Be6 { Dastan,B (2572) -Banikas,H (2592) EU-chT 23rd Terme Catez 2021 (3.10) 1/2-1/2 exchanging one pair of rooks. White