uing complications, but they don't work out in White's favour: } 16. Bc4 Bxc4 17. Nxc4 Rxd1+ 18. Rxd1 b5 $1 19. Bb6+ Kc8 20. Na5 $1 Nd4 $1 21. Bxd4 exd4 22. Rxd4 Bc5 23. Rf4 Rf8 $15 { and it's Black who keeps the best practical chances in this endgame. } ) 15... g6 $1 ( 15... h6 { directly was not good due to } 16. g6 $1 { when the bishop is suddenly well placed to avoid f7-f5. } ) 16. f4 $2 ( { It was still possible to correct the previous mistake with } 16. Bg4 { although after } 16... h6 17. h4 hxg5 18. hxg5 Rh4 $11 { Black has a very comfortable game. } ) 16... h6 $1 { Now Black simplifies into a better endgame: } 17. fxe5 hxg5 18. Bxg5 Bh6 $1 19. Bxh6 Rxh6 20. Bg2 Bxg2 21. Rxd8 Kxd8 22. Rxg2 Nxe5 $15 { [%csl Gf7,Rh2] ; Belousov,D (2340) -Antipov,M (2457) Chigorin Memorial 20th 2012 (9) 0-1 The weakness on h2 and the passed pawn on the f-file were enough to win the game. } ) 14... Rd6 15. Rg3 { [%cal Gg3d3] White's most promising plan according to the engine. For some mysterious reason, I missed this idea when analyzing the Najdorf databases in 2018. } ( 15. Bc5 { only leads to a repetition. } 15... Rd8 ( 15... Rd7 { is also playable. } 16. Bxf8 Rxf8 17. Nc5 Rdd8 $11 ) 16. Bb6 $11 ) ( 15. c4 { is a bit unnecessary, as it doesn't bring any advantage for White and commits some squares. } 15... Be4 16. Rxd6 Bxd6 17. Nd2 Bg6 { [%cal Gg6b1] Thanks to the advance of the c-pawn the bishop has a beautiful diagonal now. } 18. a3 Bc7 19. Bxc7 Kxc7 20. Rg3 { Bizopoulos,A (2150) -Klimov,A (2451) Wch U18 Vung Tau 2008 (10) 0-1 Black showed great technique to exploit his small advantage in this endgame. Here I like } 20... f6 $15 { [%csl Yd4][%cal Gg6f7,Gc6d4] simply consolidating Black's position. } ) ( 15. g5 { was tried by Wesley So in an online game. Black can equalize without problems with } 15... Be6 { anticipating the check on h3. } 16. Rxd6 ( { Black is also fine in case of } 16. Bg2 Rxd1+ 17. Rxd1 Be7 18. h4 h6 $1 19. Be3 hxg5 20. hxg5 { Krishnan,V (2306) -Cervantes Landeiro,T (2280) Saint Louis 1000 IM 2nd 2022 (1) 1-0 Now } 20... Kc7 { would be simple and good. For example: } 21. Nc5 Bf5 $11 ) 16... Bxd6 17. Nc5 { So,W (2770) -Duda,J (2743) Chess. com Speed blitz 2020 (2.15) 1/2-1/2 Although Black keeps a solid position after exchanging on c5, it's also possible to play } 17... Bf5 { For example: } 18. Bc4 Bg6 19. h4 ( 19. Bd5 Bc7 20. Bxc7 Kxc7 $11 ) ( { If } 19. Rd1 $2 Be7 { [%csl Rg5] it's White who faces some problems after } 20. Rg1 Nd4 $36 ) 19... h6 20. Be2 hxg5 21. hxg5 Bf5 $11 ) ( 15. a3 { avoids Nb4, but allows Black to equalize in a very concrete way: } 15... Bxb3 $5 { Black gives up the bishop pair but forces a lot of exchanges. } ( 15... Be7 { is a playable alternative. } ) 16. Rxd6 ( { If } 16. cxb3 Nd4 $1 { White has no time to save the bishop pair. } 17. Bxd4 exd4 $11 ) 16... Bxd6 17. cxb3 Bc7 18. Be3 Nd4 { The strong play on the dark squares offers enough compensation for the bishop pair, so White decided to go for a drawish position with } 19. Bxd4 exd4 $11 { Van Foreest,J (2605) -Sasikiran,K (2661) Sitges Sunway op 3rd 2016 (4) 1/2-1/2 } ) 15... Be7 $1 { It's a bit important to remember the right move order. With this move Black completes the development and intends to improve the position by means of either Bg5+ or Bd8, taking control of the d-file from White. } ( { In case of } 15... Be6 { White has } 16. Nc5 Rxd1+ 17. Kxd1 Bxc5 18. Bxc5 { [%csl Gc5,Gf1] ;Can,I (2423) -Souhardo,B (2357) Cattolica Grandiscacchi op 2nd 2022 (3) 1-0 when the position is objectively equal, but in practice the bishop pair can be very annoying in many endgames. } ) 16. g5 { The most natural reply, taking away some squares from the bishop. } ( 16. Rgd3 $2 { is well met by } 16... Nb4 $1 17. Rc3+ Bc6 18. Rxd6 Bxd6 $17 { [%cal Gb4a2, Gb4d5] and White suddenly loses material. } ) ( 16. Rc3 { Osswald,L (2122) -Stillger,B (2250) Oberliga NRW 1617 2016 (5.6) 1/2-1/2 was seen in one game. The simplest path now is } 16... Bg5+ $5 17. Kb1 Bd8 $1 18. Bc5 Rd7 $11 { [%cal Gd8c7, Gd5e6] when Black can continue with Bc7-Be6, exchanging one pair of rooks and relieving the pressure. } ) 16... Be6 $1 { Another precise move, avoiding any check or pin and exchanging one pair of rooks. } 17. Bg2 { The most natural. } ( 17. a4 { Chen,R (2242) -Woodward,A (2330) Richardson DCC 04 2022 (4) 1/2-1/2 was tried in a recent game, but doesn't change the evaluation. Black can follow the same typical plan here: } 17... h6 18. gxh6 Rxd1+ 19. Kxd1 Rxh6 20. Rxg7 Rxh2 $11 ) ( 17. Re1 { avoids the rook's exchange but doesn't improve White's chances. } 17... Kb8 18. Bc5 Rd7 19. Bxe7 Rxe7 20. Bg2 Rc8 $1 { A good move, avoiding the creation of weaknesses on the queenside. Black is fine here, since } 21. Bxc6 Rxc6 22. Rxe5 { doesn't work due to } 22... Rxc2+ $1 23. Kxc2 Bxb3+ $11 ) 17... Rxd1+ 18. Kxd1 h6 $1 { Once more this pawn break comes at the right moment to liberate Black's play. } 19. gxh6 ( 19. g6 f6 { is solid enough. } ) 19... Rxh6 ( 19... g6 { now can be answered by } 20. Bh3 $1 { and Black will have some work to regain the pawn on h6. } ) 20. Rxg7 Rxh2 $11 { Black has no problems to keep the control in a simplified position like this. } *
