1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. a3 $5 { The history of this move at serious tournament practice is a bit funny. First - Karjakin played it against Giri in the first round of the Tata Steel Masters 2017. The game was an uneventful draw, but somehow the move 6.a3 drew the attention of none other than Magnus Carlsen. The world champion decided to study it deeper and the next day won a very nice game against Wojtaszek, one of the best Najdorf players in the world. Afterward, Karjakin confessed that he had forgotten his laptop battery in Moscow, and 6.a3 was a last-time improvisation! In any case, the little advance of the a-pawn introduces a few subtleties in the position. } 6... e5 { The most critical test of White's move order. } ( 6... e6 { and } ) ( 6... g6 { Perez Ponsa,F (2556) -Quintiliano Pinto,R (2423) American Continental 14th 2018 (4) 1/2-1/2 are also playable, the difference is that both moves allow White to get positions in which the a3-pawn can be very useful. I tried to play in Dragon style once, but after experiencing some serious problems came to the conclusion that it is a bit risky. } ) 7. Nf5 $5 { The only option which offers chances of advantage for White. } ( 7. Nf3 { was how Karjakin played. Compared to the variations 6.Be3 e5 7.Nf3 and 6.Be2 e5 7.Nf3 White has not moved the bishops yet and can develop them directly to the ideal squares c4 and g5. Nevertheless that doesn't look enough to claim an advantage. } 7... Be7 8. Bc4 ( 8. Bg5 { seems harmless. } 8... Be6 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Nd5 { Short,N (2646) -Paravyan,D (2634) Moscow Nutcracker 2018 (3.4) 1-0 Here we can play } 10... Nd7 { with a very similar position as in the line 6.Be2 e5 7.Nf3. } 11. Bc4 Rc8 12. Ba2 { [%csl Ga2] Having the a2-square available for the bishop might look like an improvement for White, but still seems too little to achieve an advantage. } 12... O-O 13. O-O Nb6 14. c3 Nxd5 15. Bxd5 Bxd5 16. Qxd5 { The best continuation to solve Black's problems now is } 16... Qb6 17. Rab1 Rc5 18. Qd3 Rd8 { [%cal Yd6d5,Gb6c6] and White can't avoid the freeing advance d6-d5 for too long. For example: } 19. c4 Qc7 20. Nd2 Bg5 21. Nf3 Be7 22. Nd2 Bg5 $11 ) 8... O-O 9. O-O ( { In one game Anand tried to take control over d5 quickly with } 9. Bg5 Be6 10. Bxf6 { but Black has } 10... Bxc4 $1 { [%csl Gc4] keeping the good bishop. } 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Nd2 Be6 13. Nf1 Nd7 14. Ne3 Nf6 15. O-O Rac8 16. Qd3 Rc6 { [%cal Gf8c8] ;Anand,V (2782) -Nepomniachtchi,I (2729) Wch Rapid Riadh 2017 (12) 1/2-1/2 Black is ok. } ) 9... Be6 $1 { Black continues in the same way as the line 6.Be3 e5 7.Nf3. } 10. Ba2 ( 10. Qd3 $5 { creates the subtle threat of Bxe6-Ng5-Qh3. Black avoids any problem by means of } 10... Qc8 $1 11. Ba2 Nbd7 { with a totally playable position. For example: } 12. Bg5 b5 13. Rfd1 Rb8 $13 { [%cal Yb5b4] with nice counterplay on the queenside. } ) ( { In case of } 10. Bb3 { we can continue with } 10... Nc6 { [%cal Ga8c8,Gc6a5] increasing the pressure on the queenside with Rc8-Na5. At some point, White will be simply forced to make a decision about the bishop. } ) 10... b5 11. Re1 Re8 12. Bg5 Nbd7 { Black had no problems achieving the best set-up possible to fight for the d5-square. } 13. Nd2 Rb8 { [%cal Yb5b4] Now Black prepares to exploit White's 6th move in his favor by opening the b-file. } 14. Bxf6 Nxf6 15. Nf1 b4 $1 { White is able to keep a piece on d5, but the pressure on the queenside makes it hard for him to get any advantage from that. } 16. Nd5 bxa3 17. bxa3 Nxd5 18. Bxd5 Bg5 $1 { [%csl Ye3] ;Karjakin,S (2785) -Giri,A (2773) Tata Steel-A 79th 2017 (1) 1/2-1/2 Another typical move, avoiding the maneuver Ne3-d5. Black can make use of the b and c-files to keep pressure on the enemy queenside, and in any case there is Rb6 to defend the queenside pawns. Karjakin kept trying for a while but was never able to prove an advantage. } ) ( { On the other hand, after either } 7. Nb3 { or } ) ( 7. Nde2 { I don't see how White can make use of 6.a3. Black can simply develop in a natural way and should achieve a good game. } ) 7... d5 $1 { Black keeps playing in principled way, and the position suddenly becomes more tense. } 8. Bg5 $1 d4 9. Bxf6 gxf6 $1 { I prefer this recapture. Black weakens the kingside structure, but keeps a solid position and wins a tempo attacking the Nc3. } ( 9... Qxf6 { was Wojtaszek's reply, allowing } 10. Nd5 { Carlsen,M (2840) -Wojtaszek,R (2750) Tata Steel-A 79th 2017 (2) 1-0 with tempo. In his Najdorf course for Chessable, Giri shows good analysis which proves that } 10... Qc6 $1 { is the correct move to equalize. } ) 10. Nb1 { is the most played, aiming to bring the knight back to the game via d2-c4. } ( 10. Na2 $5 { looks weird, but is an option. White keeps developing normally and the knight can be improved via c1 or b4, from where it has access to d5. Now I suggest the concrete continuation } 10... Bxf5 $5 11. exf5 Qd5 $1 { [%csl Ge4] fighting for the light squares and the control in the center. } 12. Be2 ( 12. Qd3 Nd7 { [%cal Gd7c5] and } ) ( 12. c3 $2 Nc6 { [%cal Ge8c8] only help Black. } ) 12... e4 $1 { It's important do not confuse the move order and remember that the advance comes first. } ( 12... Nc6 13. Bf3 e4 $2 14. Qe2 $16 { leaves Black in trouble. } ) 13. O-O ( 13. f3 { was played in one game, but } 13... e3 $5 { [%csl Ge3,Rf5] gives a strong passed pawn for Black, and White can face problems with the f5-pawn. } 14. Qd3 Nc6 15. c4 $2 { Mekhitarian,K (2569) -Kuzmin,R (2355) Titled Tuesday intern op 08th Mar Early blitz 2022 (10) 1-0 Now the simple } 15... Qd6 { would leave Black with two passed pawns and a clear advantage. For example: } 16. O-O-O O-O-O 17. g3 Ne5 18. Qe4 Qc5 $17 ) 13... Nc6 { [%cal Ge8c8,Gh8g8] Black is about to consolidate a big advantage with 0-0-0 and Rg8, so White needs to play in the most energetic way possible. } 14. Nc3 $1 Qe5 ( { But not } 14... Qxf5 $4 15. Bg4 $18 { [%cal Gc3e4] } ) 15. f4 $1 { Forcing Black to break his beautiful pawn center. } 15... exf3 16. Bxf3 O-O-O $1 17. Ne4 Kb8 $11 { [%csl Ge3,Ge5,Rf5][%cal Yh7h5,Yh5h4,Gf8d6] ; Joeres,S (2201) -Hoffmann,J (2113) GER-chT U20 Braunschweig 2019 (4.5) 0-1 The position is dynamically balanced. Black has excellent control over the dark squares, but White plays on the light squares as well. Still, in practice, I prefer Black's chances. The f5-pawn is always under attack, and the e5 and e3-squares can be useful outposts for out pieces. Also, if the knight leaves e4 we can create attacking threats with Bd6, or advance the h-pawn in order to create problems on the enemy kingside. In one game Black successfully managed to exploit his chances and won. } ) ( 10. Ne2 $6 { seems dubious. The knight is well placed only in case of an exchange on f5, otherwise, it just stays on the way of the bishop. } 10... Qb6 $1 { Of course, now we are not in a hurry to exchange on f5. } 11. Rb1 Be6 $1 { [%cal Ge6a2] Creating the simple yet very annoying threat of Ba2. } 12. Qc1 ( 12. Nc1 Bxa3 $17 ) ( { The attempt of sacrificing an exchange with } 12. Neg3 $2 Ba2 13. Bd3 { fails due to } 13... Bxb1 14. Qxb1 Bxa3 $19 { and Black still grabs a pawn. } ) 12... Nd7 13. Neg3 Nc5 14. f3 { Debashis,D (2279) -Ashwin,J (2478) New Delhi Parsvnath op 6th 2008 (7) 1-0 Black has a clear advantage in view of White's poor coordination. The most direct way of increasing the advantage would be } 14... h5 $1 15. h4 Rg8 $17 { and White's position is very difficult. For example: } 16. Nxh5 $2 Bxf5 17. exf5 O-O-O $19 { [%cal Gg8h8,Gf8h6,Ye5e4] Black soon develops a winning initiative. } ) 10... Bxf5 $1 { Again I suggest this very concrete approach, getting rid of the Nf5 and fighting for the center in order to prevent White from developing play on the light squares. } ( 10... Qb6 { now is answered by } 11. Nd2 $1 { and White gets an active development. } ) 11. exf5 Qd5 { After the exchange Black should fight for the center immediately. } 12. Qd3 { The most played, intending to continue 