1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Nb3 { This weird and hasty knight retreat became a bit popular some years ago, when the creative Polish GM Bartel played it at the top level and obtained good positions against some Najdorf specialists like Gelfand and Wojtaszek. The main point is to keep White's position flexible and wait for a definition of Black's development. Also, the knight move can't be considered a waste of time, as White often retreats it in response to e7-e5 or to avoid exchanges. } 6... e6 { Black has more than one option here, but this is the most played. } ( 6... Nc6 { is also playable, but I prefer to keep the knight flexible on b8. } ) ( { I don't recommend } 6... e5 $6 { against this line, as after } 7. Bg5 { We have a similar position as in one line of the 6.Be2 variation (6.Be2 e5 7.Nb3 Be7 8.Bg5) , but the fact that the bishop is still on f1 basically gives a free tempo for White. The following game show that in an instructive way: } 7... Be7 8. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 9. Qd3 O-O 10. O-O-O Be7 11. Nd5 Bg5+ 12. Kb1 Be6 13. g3 $1 { White finds a nice square for his light-squared bishop. } 13... Nc6 14. h4 Be7 15. Bh3 $1 Bxd5 16. Qxd5 $14 { [%cal Gh3c8] ;Grischuk,A (2737) -Amonatov,F (2620) Wch Rapid Doha 2016 (13) 1-0 and White had a pleasant advantage. } ) ( 6... g6 { can be considered and was played by some GMs, but White has a flexible position and can choose different attacking set-ups. In one of his first games with this line, Bartel showed one possible path: } 7. Be2 Bg7 8. g4 $5 h6 $2 { Avoiding g4-g5, but now Black has problems to castle. } ( 8... Nc6 { was a better try. } ) 9. Be3 Nc6 10. f3 b5 11. Qd2 Be6 12. O-O-O Rc8 13. Kb1 Ne5 14. h4 $36 { Bartel,M (2625) -Artemiev, V (2674) Moscow Aeroflot op-A 15th 2016 (6) 1-0 and White soon had a dangerous attack. } ) ( 6... b5 $2 { is simply bad in view of } 7. a4 $1 b4 8. Nd5 { and Black is already in trouble, for example: } 8... e6 9. Nxf6+ Qxf6 10. Na5 $16 { [%cal Ga5c4,Gc1f4] with a clear advantage for White. } ) 7. g4 $1 { Maybe the most important point of Bartel's idea: White waits for e7-e6, the plays g2-g4 and gets sort of a Keres Attack. } 7... b5 $1 { Black also develops in active way and heads to a complex middlegame. } 8. Bg2 { The most played. } ( 8. a3 { is another option which likely transposes to the main line after } 8... Bb7 9. Bg2 ( { In case of } 9. Qe2 d5 $36 { the initiative is already with Black. } ) 9... Nfd7 $1 10. g5 ) ( { The aggressive continuation } 8. g5 { can be strongly met by } 8... b4 $1 9. Nd5 $5 { is an attempt of complicating the game. } ( { In case of } 9. Na4 Nxe4 10. Bg2 d5 11. Bxe4 { Black only needs to remember the important intermediate } 11... Bd7 $1 { as after } 12. Nac5 dxe4 $11 { we are at least fine. } ) ( 9. gxf6 { is perhaps the best option, but doesn't pose any problem for Black. } 9... bxc3 10. e5 $2 { This attempt of complicating the game simply backfired as after } 10... Bb7 11. Rg1 gxf6 12. bxc3 fxe5 $17 { Bellahcene,B (2493) -Baert,A (2210) Gibraltar Masters 15th 2017 (8) 1-0 Black has a clear pawn up, despite the final result. } ) 9... Nxe4 $1 { The correct capture, after which Black already has an advantage. White's best move now is probably } 10. Be3 { but after } ( { In one game he played } 10. Bg2 $2 exd5 11. Qxd5 { but after } 11... Ra7 $1 { [%csl Ge4] ;Quparadze,G (2477) -Grischuk,A (2764) Wch Rapid Warsaw 2021 (3) 0-1 he realized that the Ne4 is simply untouchable. } 12. Bxe4 Bb7 13. Qd4 Bxe4 14. Qxe4+ Re7 $19 ) ( 10. Nxb4 d5 11. Nd3 Nc6 $17 { is simply better for Black. } ) 10... Nc5 11. Nxb4 Qc7 $15 { [%cal Gc8b7, Gb8d7] Black has a good development and the a promising majority in the center, with better chances. } ) 8... Bb7 9. g5 Nfd7 ( { In one of Bartel's first games in this line } 9... b4 $5 { was tried, but after the strong reply } 10. Nd5 $1 { Black has a difficult choice. The correct continuation now is } 10... exd5 $1 ( { Instead, in the game Black reacted with } 10... Nxd5 11. exd5 e5 { trying to keep the position closed. However, after } 12. a3 $1 { Bartel,M (2625) -Wojtaszek, R (2713) POL-ch Poznan 2016 (5) 1-0 White had a strong initiative and won a nice game. } ) 11. gxf6 dxe4 $13 { The position is weird and hard to evaluate: Black is a pawn up, but soon will have weaknesses on both flanks and worse development. White definitely has nice compensation for the pawn, and in practice I think Black's position is probably more unpleasant. } ) 10. a3 { Despite not being the most popular this looks like the most solid option, securing the stability of the Nc3 before continuing the advance on the kingside. It's also the move that Giri analyses with more attention in his Najdorf course and the engine's top choice. } ( 10. Be3 { was the most played when I first analyzed this line for the 2018 Najdorf Databases. However, after } 10... Ne5 { [%cal Ge5c4] the knight reaches c4 very quickly. } ( 10... b4 $5 { is another option to consider. } ) 11. Qe2 Nc4 12. O-O-O { The position is quite curious: Black has made a lot of moves with the knight, while White kept developing his pieces as fast as possible. However, as we have a solid and flexible structure it's possible to spend all these moves with one piece and still be able to complete the development before White creates any concrete threat. } 12... Nd7 13. f4 Be7 14. h4 ( { White still can't save the bishop by means of } 14. Bd4 { due to } 14... e5 $1 { [%csl Yf4,Yg5] } ) 14... Nxe3 { It's finally time to grab the bishop. } 15. Qxe3 { Obviously, castling short would be super dangerous here, so Black keeps his king in the center for a few more moves. } 15... b4 $1 16. Ne2 a5 $1 { Threatening to take the initiative on the other side. } 17. Nbd4 { [%cal Gd4b5,Yf4f5] } 17... Qb6 18. Rh3 g6 $1 { Another good move, preventing any tension on the kingside. } 19. h5 O-O-O $5 { Salinas Herrera,P (2438) -Debarshi,M (2301) Barcelona Sant Marti op-A 19th 2017 (3) 0-1 Black finally decides to hide the king on the queenside, where White doesn't have too many pieces. The position is objectively equal, but I like the bishop pair and the fact that White's overextended kingside might become weak in the endgames. } ) ( 10. f4 $6 { allows } 10... h6 $1 { a thematic idea for Black in this line. } 11. h4 ( 11. gxh6 Rxh6 $15 { is simply better for Black. } ) ( 11. g6 $5 { is a logical reaction, but Black has the excellent reply } 11... Qh4+ $1 12. Kf1 { Vettese,N (2310) -Yudasin,L (2401) New York Fall GM-B 2022 (1) 1-0 Now } 12... Nc6 $1 { [%csl Ga5] is a necessary improvement, as Black should take care with the threat of Na5. After } 13. gxf7+ Kxf7 $15 { [%cal Gd7f6,Gf8e7] Both kings are a bit exposed, but the difference is that Black can continue developing, with better chances. } ) 11... hxg5 12. hxg5 Rxh1+ 13. Bxh1 b4 14. Ne2 a5 $36 { Smirin,I (2670) -Jumabayev,R (2611) Moscow Aeroflot op-A 16th 2017 (8) 1/2-1/2 and Black took the initiative. } ) ( 10. O-O { seems harmless. Actually, I don't see the point of having so much work to make the advance g2-g4 and next play in a passive way. } 10... Be7 11. f4 b4 $1 { Disturbing the knight seems a good idea always that White has not played a2-a3. Also, in the future, we can continue the expansion on the queenside with a5-a4. } 12. Ne2 Nc6 { Black's position is already easier, in my opinion. We have more than one interesting plan here: to keep advancing on the queenside with a5-a4, undermining the enemy kingside with e6-e5 or to break in the center with Nb6 followed by d6-d5. The main problem for White is that further advances on the kingside only lead to an exposed position of the white king. A possible continuation would be } 13. a3 a5 14. axb4 axb4 15. Rxa8 Qxa8 16. Be3 O-O 17. Ng3 Rd8 18. f5 $5 Nce5 $13 { [%csl Ye4][%cal Gd7c5] with a double-edged game, but I still like Black's chances. } ) ( 10. h4 { is a direct continuation which was played twice by Svidler against Nepo. } 10... b4 $1 { It is good to remember that this move comes before Nc6 in order to prevent White from considering Na4. } 11. Ne2 Nc6 12. f4 ( 12. O-O { was how Svidler played in their second game, at the Russian Championship. } 12... h6 $5 { There is nothing wrong with the normal Be7, but Nepo's move is thematic and also interesting. } 13. g6 $5 { Svidler reacts with an interesting pawn sacrifice, but Black can accept the challenge and keep a playable position. } 13... Qxh4 14. gxf7+ Kxf7 15. a3 { Tying to activate the rook via a3, but Black is not forced to collaborate with this plan. } 15... a5 16. axb4 axb4 17. Rxa8 Bxa8 18. f4 { The only way of justifying the pawn sacrifice, but Black has nothing to fear. } 18... Nf6 19. f5 { Now Black could have kept the tension by means of either exf5 or Ne5, but Nepo opted for the solid } 19... e5 { which nevertheless allows } 20. Rf3 $1 { when White manages to give a "perpetual" on the enemy queen. } 20... d5 21. Rh3 Qg4 22. Rg3 Qh4 23. Rh3 $11 { Svidler,P (2723) -Nepomniachtchi,I (2784) RUS-ch 73rd Moscow 2020 (2) 1/2-1/2 } ) 12... h6 $1 { Again this move comes in a good moment, breaking the kingside structure and exchanging one pair of rooks. } 13. Be3 hxg5 14. hxg5 Rxh1+ 15. Bxh1 a5 { [%cal Ya5a4,Ye6e5] Black already has ideas like a5-a4 or the undermining of the kingside pawns with e6-e5. Svidler tried to solve the position with } 16. Ned4 $6 { but after } 16... Nxd4 17. Nxd4 Nc5 18. Qg4 { [%cal Yg5g6, Gd4e6] } 18... g6 $15 { [%csl Re4][%cal Gd8d7] ;Svidler,P (2723) -Nepomniachtchi,I (2784) Skilling op Prelim rapid 2020 (14) 0-1 The pressure on e4 makes White's position unpleasant. } ) 10... Nc6 { A practical advantage of White's 6th move is that we can develop the knight to c6 more easily. From practical experience, I've learned that in such positions it's important to develop the queenside as quickly as possible in order to create chances of counterplay. The bishop can go to e7 later, as from f8 it even supports the thematic idea h7-h6. } 11. h4 { White usually advances the