 $2 hxg5 18. Bxg5 Be7 $19 { [%cal Ge8c8] } ) 17... gxh4 18. Qxh4 Ne7 $17 { [%cal Gf8g7,Ge8c8,Yh6h5] Black continues with Bg7 and 0-0-0, and White soon faces a lot of problems on the kingside. } ) 16... Be7 17. f5 { White keeps trying to play in a dynamic way. } ( { If } 17. O-O { g7-g5 is not possible anymore, but after } 17... O-O $17 { [%csl Rh4][%cal Gf7h5,Ge7f6,Yb5b4] Black has a clearly better game in view of the many weaknesses on White's camp. } ) 17... Bf6 18. fxe6 Qxe6 { Looks like the advances on the kingside only made White's position worse: besides having a more exposed structure, it is not easy to find a safe place for the white king. For example: } 19. Bf4 $5 ( { Black also has an advantage in case of } 19. Qg6+ Kd8 $1 20. Qg3 N6e5 21. O-O Qg4 $15 ) 19... O-O ( { After } 19... Nxb2 $6 20. Nd5 O-O 21. O-O Nc4 22. Rad1 $44 { White has some compensation for the pawn, but it is probably equal. } ) 20. O-O-O ( { After } 20. O-O $2 Kh8 21. Rad1 Rad8 $19 { [%csl Rb2,Re4,Rh4] it seems unlikely that White can avoid material losses for too long in this position. } ) 20... Bxc3 $1 21. bxc3 N6e5 $15 { I prefer Black's chances here. Maybe White is able to keep the position under control with correct play, but in the long term, the structural weaknesses look very serious and difficult to defend. } *
