1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Qf3 { In this chapter we will examine lines in which White develops the queen early. Although none of these moves is really popular, it's always important to know what to do as Black. This is the most played. } ( 6. Qe2 { seems the most harmless. Perhaps White aims to transpose to some variation of 6.Bg5, but it is not possible because } 6... e5 $1 { is a very good reply. } 7. Nf5 $5 { is the only way of justifying White's previous move. } ( 7. Nb3 { [%csl Ge2] is probably safer, but then it's hard to find a point on White's 6th move. } 7... Be6 8. Bd2 { Another drawback: without the queen on d2 White needs to develop the bishop in that square to avoid the thematic exchange sacrifice on c3 in the next moves. } 8... Nbd7 9. O-O-O { Gormally, D (2477) -Van Delft,M (2393) London Classic op 2017 (9) 1-0 Now by means of natural moves like } 9... b5 $5 10. a3 Rc8 { Black could have obtained a normal and promising position. For example: } 11. Rg1 $6 Qc7 12. g4 d5 $36 ) 7... d5 $1 { As usual, this is the correct reaction when the knight reaches f5. } 8. Bg5 d4 9. O-O-O ( { In case of } 9. Bxf6 gxf6 $1 { Black basically has a much better version of positions seen in the 6.a3 variation. } 10. O-O-O { White tries to keep control by means of tactical resources, but the position is clearly unstable. } 10... Be6 11. Qh5 { Activating the queen and cleaning the path to develop the bishop. } 11... Rg8 $1 { A strong and clever move, aiming to answer Nd5 with Rg5 and Rxf5. } 12. h4 Nd7 { [%cal Gd4c3] } 13. Nd5 Nc5 14. Bc4 Rc8 $17 { [%csl Re4, Rg2][%cal Yb7b5,Ya6a5] White is clearly in trouble here. } ) 9... Nc6 { Next Black wants to play Qa5, getting rid of the pin and taking the initiative. } ( { The direct } 9... Qa5 $2 { is bad due to } 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Qh5 $1 { [%cal Gf5d4] and it's Black who faces unpleasant threats. } 11... dxc3 $2 { is tactically refuted by } 12. Bc4 Qc7 13. Bxf7+ $1 Qxf7 14. Rd8+ $18 ) 10. Qf3 { Although White's position seems very active, it's Black who plays for an advantage here. } ( 10. f4 $2 { looks tempting. This is the most played move but nevertheless leaves White lost after } 10... Qa5 11. fxe5 dxc3 12. exf6 Be6 $1 { It's important to remember this intermediate, which prepares to take on b2 followed by mate. Because of this move, Black has a winning attack. The best attempt to complicate the game is } 13. Rd5 { but it is not enough to save White: } 13... Qxa2 14. bxc3 gxf6 15. Bxf6 Rg8 $19 { [%cal Gg8g6,Ga8c8] ;Sevdimaliyev,U (2331) -Kilic, E (2192) Marmaris Icmeler 2022 (6.4) 0-1 and Black has a decisive attack. } ) 10... Qa5 $1 { Again this is very strong and the analysis shows that the complications work in Black's favour. } ( { My 2018 recommendation was } 10... Bxf5 $5 11. Qxf5 Qc8 $15 { [%csl Gc3,Yf5][%cal Gd4c3] ;Andrenko,I (2227) -Kopasov, E (2014) Chigorin Memorial 20th 2012 (2) 1/2-1/2 which is a simpler way of solving Black's problems and leads to an easier endgame. } ) 11. Bxf6 dxc3 12. Bxg7 Qxa2 $1 { Exposing the enemy king. } 13. bxc3 Bxf5 $1 14. Bxf8 ( 14. Bxh8 $2 Bh6+ { and mate. } ) 14... Be6 { The black king is considerably safer in this position. For example: } 15. Bc5 Rg8 { [%cal Ge6g4] } 16. h3 Rg6 $40 { [%cal Ga8c8,Gc6a5] The rook is well placed on the third rank to both attacking and defensive purposes. The difference between both king's safety is so serious that the engine suggests taking drastic measures with } 17. Kd2 $5 { trying to escape from the enemy queen. However, we can increase the pressure with } 17... O-O-O+ 18. Bd3 Bc4 { and White remains under pressure. It's possible to force exchanges with } 19. Ra1 { but after } 19... Bxd3 20. Rxa2 Bxe4+ 21. Ke3 Bxf3 22. Kxf3 Rd5 $17 { the endgame is clearly better for Black. } ) ( 6. Qd3 $5 { has become the second most played recently and has been tried by many Grandmasters. Seemingly, it became more popular after both Carlsen and Van Foreest used this move to beat Grandelius at the 2021 Tata Steel Masters. } 6... Nbd7 { The most natural and flexible option. } ( { It's important to remember that } 6... e5 $6 7. Nf5 $1 { works out better for White now, as the queen is well placed to support the knight. } ) 7. Be2 ( { In case of } 7. a4 g6 { the difference is that White is deprived of 0-0-0. } 8. Be2 Bg7 9. O-O b6 $1 { [%cal Gc8b7] A nice detail in the move order. Black wants to develop the bishop on b7, but it's important to do it before castling since if } 10. Nc6 Qc7 { [%csl Ye7,Ge8] the e7-pawn is still defended. } 11. Nb4 Bb7 12. Nbd5 { This allows exchanges, but the knight hardly could go to another square from b4. } 12... Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Qd8 { [%cal Ge8g8] Black is ready to castle and has a good game. } 14. Bg5 $2 { just loses a pawn: } 14... Bxd5 $15 { [%csl Rb2] } ) 7... g6 { I like the Dragon set-up against this variation. } 8. Bg5 { Just like in the Dragon, White aims to castle long and look for an attack on the kingside. } ( 8. h4 $5 { was tried in one game. Black has a nice way of facing this plan: } 8... Nc5 $1 9. Qe3 h5 $1 { [%csl Yc1,Yh4] At the same time blocking the h-pawn and preventing White from developing the bishop to g5. White played } 10. Nb3 { but with } 10... Bh6 $1 11. Qd4 Ne6 12. Qd1 Bg7 { Black keeps developing without problems. The way Black solved the opening problems was very instructive: } 13. Be3 Bd7 14. a4 Bc6 15. f3 d5 $1 { The freeing advance forces White to go for an inferior structure. } 16. e5 Ng8 $1 17. f4 Nh6 $1 { [%csl Gf5] The knight gets a nice outpost on f5 now. } 18. Nd4 Nxd4 19. Bxd4 Nf5 $15 { Ponkratov,P (2659) -Ter Sahakyan,S (2607) FIDE Grand Swiss 2021 (11) 1/2-1/ 2 Black's position is already more pleasant. } ) 8... Bg7 9. O-O-O h6 $1 { It's good to force a definition by the bishop. } 10. Bh4 ( 10. Bxf6 { was played in one game. } 10... Bxf6 11. f4 { Ongut,T (2288) -Papadiamandis,E (2286) Budapest FS02 GM 2021 (8) 1-0 Looks like White's idea is to advance on the kingside with g4-h4 etc. However,