nces of attack on the kingside are more or less zero. The following variation is a nice illustration: } 18. h4 a4 19. h5 g5 20. Nf5 b3 $1 21. c3 bxa2+ 22. Ka1 Bf6 $1 23. Nxh6+ Kh8 $19 { [%csl Ra1][%cal Ya4a3] and only the black attack can make progress. } ) 11... e5 $1 { This advance should be remembered as it is the best way of neutralizing White's active ideas. If White had not advanced f2-f4 this move would be just a serious positional mistake. However, with the pawn on f4 we can exploit it to open the e-file and the Bg7 won't be closed for more than one move. } 12. Nb3 ( 12. fxe5 { Sevian,S (2660) -Tran,T (2518) PNWCC Online Masters rapid 2020 (3.4) 1-0 } 12... Nxe5 13. Qd2 Re8 $13 { [%cal Gf6e4] gives nice counterplay for Black. Nxe4 is already a threat. } ) ( 12. Nf3 $5 Nc5 13. Qd2 Be6 { also looks fine for Black. The pressure on d6 is compensated by e4. } ) 12... exf4 13. Qxd6 { Vitiugov,N (2740) -Kamsky,G (2670) RUS-chT Sochi 2018 (5.2) 1/ 2-1/2 Black has a forced path to equalize now starting by } 13... Nxe4 $1 14. Bxd8 ( 14. Qxf4 $2 Nxc3 $19 { [%cal Gg6g5,Gc3e2] } ) 14... Nxd6 15. Be7 Re8 16. Bxd6 Bxc3 17. Bf3 ( 17. bxc3 Rxe2 18. Rhe1 $2 { seems an interesting try but after } 18... Rxe1 19. Rxe1 { Black can hold the pawn with } 19... g5 $1 { as we are able to get rid of the pin on the first rank. For example: } 20. Re8+ Kg7 21. c4 b5 22. c5 Nf6 23. Be5 Bb7 24. Re7 Bxg2 $19 ) 17... Bg7 ( 17... Be5 $2 18. Rhe1 $14 { [%cal Ge1e8] seems unpleasant for Black. } ) 18. Bxf4 Ne5 { Black is able to complete the development here. For example: } 19. Rde1 ( { If } 19. Rhe1 { there is } 19... Bg4 $1 { an important detail, which is only possible because of the white rook on d1. } ) 19... g5 20. Bg3 Rb8 21. Nc5 f5 $13 { [%cal Yb7b6,Yf5f4] The position is a bit tense but balanced. Soon Black can push the knight back with b7-b6 and complete the mobilization of the pieces. } ) 6... g6 $1 { Giri's recommendation. The Dragon set-up works nicely with the queen on f3 as White s