e on e7 with the advance of the kingside pawns. This position resembles some Dragon lines which usually offer an easier game for White. } ) 15. Ba6 $5 { A slightly strange move, but White doesn't have too many options here. The bishop was hanging on c4, and this move wins a tempo. } ( { White loses a piece in case of } 15. Bb3 $2 Nxd4 16. Bxd4 a4 17. Nxf6+ Bxf6 18. Bd5 Bxd4 19. Rxd4 e6 20. Bb7 Rb8 21. Ba6 Qb6 $19 ) ( 15. Nxc6 Bxc6 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17. Kb1 a4 $15 { [%cal Gc6b7] also seems more pleasant for Black. } ) 15... Rb8 16. e5 ( { If } 16. Bc4 { Black is not forced to repeat. With the rook on b8 we can consider } 16... a4 $1 { [%cal Gc6a5,Yb4b3] following the plan on the queenside. White's best reaction is } 17. Nxf6+ Bxf6 18. e5 { but after } 18... Nxd4 19. Bxd4 ( 19. exf6 Bc6 20. Bd5 Bxd5 21. Qxd5 Nb5 $13 { [%cal Ya4a3] is ok for Black. } ) 19... dxe5 20. fxe5 Bg5+ $1 21. Kb1 Qc8 $1 { [%cal Gd7c6] Black manages to coordinate the pieces in a good way. For example: } 22. Qe2 a3 $5 23. b3 Be6 24. Bxe6 Qxe6 25. h4 Bh6 26. g5 Bg7 $11 { [%csl Gg7][%cal Gf8d8] The bishop is back to g7 and keeps the kingside safe. } ) ( 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17. e5 $5 { can be considered. In this case, after } 17... Nxd4 { White can sacrifice the exchange with } 18. exf6 $5 ( { On the other hand, after } 18. Bxd4 $2 dxe5 19. fxe5 Bh4 $17 { [%cal Gd8c7,Ya5a4] Black is better, as seen in a similar position. } ) 18... Bc6 19. Qf2 Bxh1 20. Bxd4 Be4 $15 { [%csl Gd4][%cal Yd6d5] when White has a dangerous dark-squared bishop and can try to create attacking ideas on the kingside. On the other hand, the bishop in e4 is also strong and I think we have enough resources to keep the king safe. For example: } 21. Qh4 $2 Re8 22. g5 ( { Or } 22. fxe7 Qxe7 23. Bf6 Qc7 24. Bd3 Bxd3 25. Rxd3 Rbc8 26. c3 Re6 27. f5 Qc4 $1 28. Rd2 Qf1+ 29. Rd1 Qf4+ $19 { [%csl Yh6] controlling h6. } ) 22... h5 $1 23. gxh6 Kh7 $19 { [%csl Gh7] A typical defensive resource. The king is totally safe on h7 now, and Black can proceed to exploit the material advantage and the chances on the queenside. } ) 16... Nxd5 17. Qxd5 Nxd4 18. Bxd4 ( { But not } 18. Qxd4 $2 a4 $19 { [%cal Gd8a5] and Black has a winning attack. } ) 18... Ra8 { The simplest. } ( 18... Be6 19. Qe4 Bxa2 $5 { is a risky but playable alternative, which requires careful analysis. } ) 19. Bb7 Rb8 20. Ba6 ( { Or } 20. Bc6 Bxc6 21. Qxc6 dxe5 22. Bxe5 Qc8 $11 ) ( { But not } 20. exd6 $2 e6 $1 21. Qf3 Bxd4 22. Rxd4 Qb6 $19 { [%csl Rb7,Rd4] } ) 20... Ra8 $11 *
