1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. b3 { As strange as it may look, all moves seen in this chapter have been tried by strong players against the Najdorf. Honestly, I think very unlikely you to face any of these moves in your next tournament games. On the other hand, in the last years, I've learned that we never know which will be White's next try against the Najdorf, no matter how bizarre the idea looks, so it's better to check them. This move, for instance, has been played by Carlsen and other GMs in online games, so I assume it's at least playable. } ( 6. Nf3 $6 { was played by a few Grandmasters, but I confess it's very hard for me to understand the point of this retreat besides some tricks connected with e4-e5. } 6... Nbd7 { I'm pretty sure this knight makes more sense on d7 than White's on f3, as at least we didn't spend three tempos with the same piece. } ( 6... e5 $2 { [%cal Gf1c4,Gc1g5] is clearly White's dream, as now it's possible to develop the bishops directly to c4 and g5, with an improved version of some lines. } ) ( 6... e6 7. e5 $1 { Andreikin,D (2712) -Karjakin,S (2763) Moscow Tal Memorial blitz 11th 2018 (13) 1/2-1/2 is an unnecessary way of giving logical sense for White's last move, despite not being objectively bad. } ) 7. a4 ( 7. Bc4 $2 b5 $1 { is simply better for Black. } 8. Bd5 Rb8 9. Nd4 Qc7 $15 { [%cal Ye7e6] and continuing with e7-e6 Black will have sort of a Sozin Variation with many extra tempos. } ) ( 7. Be2 e6 8. O-O b5 { [%cal Gc8b7,Gf8e7,Ge8g8,Yb5b4] ;Kheit,W (2223) -Gormally,D (2499) Hastings Masters op 90th 2014 (1) 0-1 also leaves Black with a comfortable development. } ) 7... b6 { It's good to avoid a4-a5. } 8. Bc4 e6 9. O-O Bb7 10. Nd4 { Predke,A (2622) -Bocharov,D (2533) RUS Cup final 2018 (1.3) 0-1 } 10... Qc8 { A good prophylactic measure against sacrifices on e6. } ( { If } 10... Nxe4 $2 11. Nxe4 Bxe4 12. Qe2 $36 { White has a strong initiative for the pawn. deixa as brancas com muita iniciativa pelo peăo. } ) 11. Ba2 Be7 12. f3 O-O 13. Be3 Re8 { Black is fine. The position resembles a Hedgehog position, but White doesn't have the pawn on c4 and the bishop seems passive on a2. Black is able do complete the mobilization of his pieces very easily: } 14. Qd2 ( { If } 14. Qe2 d5 $5 { [%cal Ge8e1] can be considered. } ) 14... Bf8 15. Rad1 Qc7 16. Qf2 Rac8 $11 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Yd6d5,Yb6b5,Gd7e5,Ge5c4] I like Black's position. White can't avoid the typical pawn breaks d6-d5 and b6-b5 forever, the bishop is limited on a2, and the maneuver Ne5-c4 seems a bit annoying. } ) ( 6. Bd2 { is perhaps the most bizarre move I've seen against the Najdorf in recent years. However, as ugly as this bishop move might look, it is playable and there is a point. After } 6... e5 7. Nf5 d5 8. Qf3 { [%cal Ge1c1] White is ready to castle, which is the idea. } 8... d4 9. Nd5 Nxd5 10. exd5 Bxf5 { The simplest. } ( 10... g6 $5 { is a more ambitious option and also playable. } ) ( { But } 10... Qf6 $6 { played by Abdusattorov, is imprecise. } 11. Bd3 Nd7 { [%cal Gd7c5] ;Van Foreest,L (2523) -Abdusattorov,N (2635) Tata Steel-B 82nd 2020 (11) 0-1 Now White could have obtained a better game with } 12. Qe2 $1 Nc5 13. Ng3 Nxd3+ 14. Qxd3 $14 { [%cal Ge1g1,Ga1e1,Yf2f4] followed by 0-0 and Rae1, with strong centralization. Next he could break in the center with f2-f4, and White would get a strong initiative. } ) 11. Qxf5 Nd7 12. h4 $5 { This advance seems the only way of posing practical problems for Black. } ( 12. O-O-O g6 13. Qf3 Bg7 14. h4 h5 { transposes. } ) ( { Otherwise Black continues with g6-Bg7 and 0-0 and is ready to exploit the kingside majority. For example: } 12. c3 g6 13. Qf3 Bg7 14. cxd4 O-O $5 15. Be2 exd4 16. O-O Qb6 { [%cal Gf8e8,Ga8d8,Gd7e5] when I like Black's position. } ) 12... g6 13. Qf3 h5 14. O-O-O Bg7 15. Kb1 ( { White can try to prevent Black from castling with } 15. Bb4 { but } 15... Rc8 16. Kb1 Nc5 { transposes. } ) 15... Nc5 { [%csl Rd5][%cal Ge5e4] A very concrete move, threatening to win the d5-pawn after e5-e4. } ( 15... O-O { is also possible, but White can play } 16. g4 $5 { with a complex game. } ) 16. Bb4 Rc8 17. g4 $5 { It's hard to suggest anything else for White in view of the threat e5-e4. } ( { For example: } 17. c3 { is answered by } 17... e4 $1 18. Qh3 O-O $1 19. cxd4 Qxd5 $17 { [%cal Gg7d4] and Black is already better. } ) 17... e4 $1 { Black replies in active way, increasing the tension. } 18. Qf4 ( 18. Qh3 { seems an interesting option to keep the Rc8 under attack in some lines, but Black has a surprisingly strong continuation here: } 18... O-O $1 19. gxh5 d3 $3 { Suddenly White faces a crushing attack. } 20. c3 Na4 $1 21. Bxf8 Nxc3+ $3 22. bxc3 Qb6+ 23. Bb4 Rxc3 $19 { and Black wins. } ) 18... Qxd5 19. Bg2 O-O 20. Bxc5 ( { But not } 20. gxh5 $2 d3 $1 21. c3 f5 $1 { [%cal Gc5a4] and Black soon develops a winning attack with the same Na4-ideas. } ) 20... Qxc5 21. Bxe4 d3 $1 { Black keeps fighting actively for the initiative. } 22. c3 $8 ( 22. Bxd3 Rc6 { [%cal Rc6b6] gives a winning attack for Black since } 23. c3 { is refuted by } 23... Bxc3 $19 ) 22... Qb6 $1 { [%csl Rc3,Yg7][%cal Gc8c3] The threat of Rxc3 is very dangerous. The best defense seems to be } 23. Qe3 $1 ( 23. Rxd3 Bxc3 24. Rxc3 $5 { is another option. } 24... Rxc3 25. gxh5 Rc4 $13 { with a complex position. } ) 23... Qxe3 24. fxe3 Rc4 $1 25. Bxb7 Rb8 26. Bxa6 Rxc3 27. Bxd3 hxg4 $11 { The endgame seems balanced. Despite being a pawn down Black is very active, and the passed pawn on g4 can be dangerous sometimes. } ) 6... e5 { I believe Black should solve the opening problems easily with typical Najdorf play. } ( 6... Qa5 $5 { also looks interesting. } ) 7. Nde2 { [%cal Yg2g3] As I've seen in some games, White's idea is to retreat the knight to e2 and continue with g2-g3, aiming for positions similar to the 6.g3 variation. } ( { If } 7. Nf3 { I don't see a way of using the move 6.b3 in White's favour. } 7... Be7 8. Bc4 Be6 9. O-O Nbd7 $15 { [%cal Ga8c8] and the pawn on b3 only makes White's queenside more vulnerable. } ) 7... Be6 { [%cal Yd6d5] Black is ready to play d6-d5 and equalize comfortably. } 8. g3 { Carlsen,M (2847) -Svidler,P (2714) Goldmoney Asian Prelim rapid 2021 (4.2) 1-0 } ( 8. f4 $6 { Fries Nielsen,J (2380) -Schlegel, I (2027) EU-ch Online 2300+ Qual 2020 (6) 1-0 was played in one game. The drawback of this advance is that it weakens the e4-pawn, so Black can just continue the development and exploit this issue in the future. } 8... Be7 9. f5 ( { If } 9. g3 Qb6 $1 { [%cal Gf6g4] White faces some problems on the kingside. } ) 9... Bd7 10. Bg5 Bc6 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Nd5 { The only way of getting some stability in White's position. Even then, after } 12... Bxd5 13. Qxd5 Nc6 14. O-O-O O-O 15. Kb1 Rc8 $11 { I prefer Black's chances. The d6-pawn doesn't matter here, and Black can develop dangerous play on the dark squares. } ) ( 8. Bg5 $2 { looks simply pointless. } 8... Nbd7 9. g3 h6 10. Bc1 Rc8 11. Bg2 b5 $15 { [%cal Gf8e7,Gd8c7] This seems already pleasant for Black. } ) ( 8. Bb2 { [%csl Ye5] avoids the advance d6-d5 by keeping e5 under pressure. On the other hand, the bishop doesn't look special on b2. } 8... Nbd7 9. g3 Be7 10. Bg2 b5 11. O-O Rc8 { This looks like a pleasant version of the 6.g3 line for Black as White lacks a clear plan. For example: } 12. h3 { [%cal Yg3g4,Ge2g3] A typical idea in such positions, aiming to improve the Ne2 via g3 after g3-g4. However, it can be strongly met by } 12... Nc5 { [%cal Yb5b4] } 13. a3 h5 $1 { [%cal Gd8d7,Ya6a5] when White simply has a cramped position. After avoiding the plan with g3-g4 we can continue improving our position with Qd7 followed by a6-a5, with promising chances. } ) 8... d5 { In the game Svidler tried an active plan with h7-h5. Although the way he played seems fine, I think this is a more direct path to solving the opening problems. } 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Bg2 Bb4 11. Bb2 ( 11. Bd2 { neutralizes the pin but relieves the pressure on the d-file. After } 11... Nc6 12. O-O Nde7 $11 { Black manages to organize the pieces in a comfortable way. } ) 11... Nc6 12. a3 ( { In case of } 12. O-O Nf6 $5 13. a3 Be7 $11 { Black's position looks fine. } ) 12... Bxc3+ 13. Nxc3 Nxc3 14. Bxc3 ( { After } 14. Qxd8+ Rxd8 15. Bxc3 f6 $11 { The endgame should be equal, as the bishop pair doesn't look dangerous. } ) 14... Qc7 { Not the only path, but a very simple one. Black has a good plan of installing the knight on d4, which seems enough to equalize. For example: } 15. O-O O-O 16. Re1 Rad8 17. Qe2 Nd4 18. Bxd4 exd4 $11 *
